<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<meta name="color-scheme" content="light">
<title>Wesleyan Daily Curriculum</title>
<link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com">
<link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=EB+Garamond:ital,wght@0,400;0,500;0,600;1,400;1,500&family=DM+Sans:wght@300;400;500&family=Cinzel:wght@400;500&display=swap" rel="stylesheet">
<style>
*,*::before,*::after{box-sizing:border-box;margin:0;padding:0;}
html{scroll-behavior:smooth;}
body{background:#f5f0e8!important;color:#1a1612!important;font-family:'EB Garamond',Georgia,serif;font-size:17px;line-height:1.7;min-height:100vh;color-scheme:light only;}
header{background:#1a1612;color:#fdfaf4;padding:3rem 2rem 2.5rem;text-align:center;position:relative;overflow:hidden;}
header::before{content:'';position:absolute;inset:0;background:radial-gradient(ellipse at 50% 120%,rgba(139,58,30,.35) 0%,transparent 70%);pointer-events:none;}
.eyebrow{font-family:'DM Sans',system-ui,sans-serif;font-size:.7rem;font-weight:500;letter-spacing:.18em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#c9922a;margin-bottom:.75rem;}
header h1{font-family:'Cinzel',serif;font-size:clamp(1.6rem,4vw,2.8rem);font-weight:400;letter-spacing:.04em;line-height:1.2;margin-bottom:.75rem;color:#fdfaf4;}
header p.sub{font-style:italic;font-size:1rem;color:#f0d89a;max-width:520px;margin:0 auto 1.5rem;}
.hline{width:60px;height:1px;background:#7a2e12;margin:0 auto;}
.quad-key{background:#fdfaf4;border-bottom:1px solid #d4c9b0;display:flex;justify-content:center;flex-wrap:wrap;}
.qk-item{display:flex;align-items:center;gap:.5rem;padding:.75rem 1.25rem;border-right:1px solid #d4c9b0;font-family:'DM Sans',system-ui,sans-serif;font-size:.75rem;}
.qk-item:last-child{border-right:none;}
.qk-dot{width:10px;height:10px;border-radius:50%;flex-shrink:0;}
.qk-label{font-weight:500;color:#1a1612;}
.qk-sub{color:#4a403a;font-size:.7rem;}
.nav-outer{background:#1a1612;border-top:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,.08);position:sticky;top:0;z-index:100;}
.nav-year{display:flex;justify-content:center;flex-wrap:wrap;}
.nav-tab{font-family:'DM Sans',system-ui,sans-serif;font-size:.72rem;font-weight:500;letter-spacing:.1em;text-transform:uppercase;color:rgba(255,255,255,.5);padding:.8rem 1.2rem;cursor:pointer;border:none;border-bottom:2px solid transparent;background:none;transition:color .2s,border-color .2s;}
.nav-tab:hover{color:rgba(255,255,255,.85);}
.nav-tab.active{color:#c9922a;border-bottom-color:#7a2e12;}
.subnav{background:#2a221e;display:flex;justify-content:center;flex-wrap:wrap;border-bottom:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,.06);}
.snav-tab{font-family:'DM Sans',system-ui,sans-serif;font-size:.65rem;font-weight:500;letter-spacing:.1em;text-transform:uppercase;color:rgba(255,255,255,.38);padding:.6rem 1rem;cursor:pointer;border:none;border-bottom:2px solid transparent;background:none;transition:color .15s;}
.snav-tab:hover{color:rgba(255,255,255,.65);}
.snav-tab.active{color:#c9922a;border-bottom-color:#7a2e12;}
main{max-width:860px;margin:0 auto;padding:2.5rem 1.25rem 5rem;background:#f5f0e8;color:#1a1612;}
.section{display:none;}.section.active{display:block;}
.overview-lede{font-size:1.1rem;font-style:italic;color:#4a403a;border-left:3px solid #7a2e12;padding-left:1.25rem;margin-bottom:2.5rem;}
.quad-explainer{display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fit,minmax(180px,1fr));gap:1px;background:#d4c9b0;border:1px solid #d4c9b0;margin-bottom:2.5rem;}
.quad-card{background:#fdfaf4;padding:1.25rem 1.25rem 1.5rem;}
.quad-card-bar{height:3px;width:32px;margin-bottom:.75rem;border-radius:1px;}
.quad-card h3{font-family:'DM Sans',system-ui,sans-serif;font-size:.75rem;font-weight:600;letter-spacing:.1em;text-transform:uppercase;margin-bottom:.35rem;}
.quad-card p{font-family:'DM Sans',system-ui,sans-serif;font-size:.78rem;color:#4a403a;line-height:1.5;}
.quad-card .timing{font-family:'DM Sans',system-ui,sans-serif;font-size:.68rem;font-weight:500;color:#7a2e12;margin-top:.5rem;}
.ov-table{width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;margin-bottom:2.5rem;font-family:'DM Sans',system-ui,sans-serif;font-size:.82rem;}
.ov-table thead tr{background:#1a1612;color:#c9922a;}
.ov-table th{padding:.6rem .9rem;text-align:left;font-weight:500;letter-spacing:.08em;text-transform:uppercase;font-size:.65rem;}
.ov-table tbody tr{background:#fdfaf4;}
.ov-table tbody tr:nth-child(even){background:#f0ebe0;}
.ov-table td{padding:.65rem .9rem;border-bottom:1px solid #d4c9b0;color:#1a1612;vertical-align:top;}
.ov-table td:first-child{color:#7a2e12;font-weight:500;}
.unit-label{font-family:'Cinzel',serif;font-size:.75rem;letter-spacing:.15em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#7a2e12;margin-bottom:.5rem;}
.unit-title{font-family:'EB Garamond',Georgia,serif;font-size:1.45rem;font-weight:600;margin-bottom:.25rem;color:#1a1612;}
.unit-desc{font-style:italic;color:#4a403a;font-size:.95rem;margin-bottom:2rem;}
.week-block{margin-bottom:.5rem;}
.week-head{display:flex;align-items:center;gap:.75rem;padding:.85rem 1.1rem;background:#e8dfc8;color:#1a1612;cursor:pointer;user-select:none;border:1px solid #d4c9b0;transition:background .15s;}
.week-head:hover{background:#ddd4ba;}
.week-num{font-family:'DM Sans',system-ui,sans-serif;font-size:.65rem;font-weight:600;letter-spacing:.12em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#7a2e12;min-width:52px;}
.week-title{font-family:'EB Garamond',Georgia,serif;font-weight:600;font-size:.98rem;flex:1;}
.week-toggle{color:#4a403a;font-size:1rem;transition:transform .2s;}
.week-block.open .week-toggle{transform:rotate(180deg);}
.week-body{display:none;border:1px solid #d4c9b0;border-top:none;}
.week-block.open .week-body{display:block;}
.day-card{border-bottom:1px solid #d4c9b0;background:#fdfaf4;color:#1a1612;}
.day-card:last-child{border-bottom:none;}
.day-head{display:flex;align-items:center;gap:.75rem;padding:.75rem 1.1rem;cursor:pointer;background:#fdfaf4;transition:background .12s;}
.day-head:hover{background:#f0ebe0;}
.day-label{font-family:'DM Sans',system-ui,sans-serif;font-size:.63rem;font-weight:600;letter-spacing:.1em;text-transform:uppercase;min-width:72px;color:#4a403a;}
.day-title{font-family:'DM Sans',system-ui,sans-serif;font-size:.82rem;font-weight:500;flex:1;color:#1a1612;}
.day-toggle{color:#4a403a;font-size:.9rem;transition:transform .2s;}
.day-card.open .day-toggle{transform:rotate(180deg);}
.day-body{display:none;}
.day-card.open .day-body{display:block;}
.movement{border-top:1px solid #e8dfc8;padding:1.1rem 1.25rem 1.25rem;background:#fdfaf4;color:#1a1612;}
.movement:first-child{border-top:none;}
.mvmt-head{display:flex;align-items:center;gap:.6rem;margin-bottom:.75rem;}
.mvmt-dot{width:8px;height:8px;border-radius:50%;flex-shrink:0;}
.mvmt-label{font-family:'DM Sans',system-ui,sans-serif;font-size:.62rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;}
.mvmt-sub{font-family:'DM Sans',system-ui,sans-serif;font-size:.68rem;color:#4a403a;margin-left:auto;}
.movement p,.movement li{font-size:.93rem;color:#1a1612;line-height:1.65;}
.movement ul{list-style:none;padding:0;}
.movement ul li{padding:.2rem 0 .2rem 1.1rem;position:relative;}
.movement ul li::before{content:'arr';position:absolute;left:0;color:#7a2e12;font-size:.8rem;}
.movement em{font-style:italic;}
.movement strong{font-weight:600;}
.prompt-box{background:#f5f0e8;border-left:3px solid #7a5a0e;padding:.85rem 1rem;font-style:italic;font-size:.9rem;color:#3a3028;margin-top:.5rem;line-height:1.65;}
.c-scripture .mvmt-dot{background:#2d6a9f;}.c-scripture .mvmt-label{color:#1a4a75;}
.c-tradition .mvmt-dot{background:#7a2e12;}.c-tradition .mvmt-label{color:#7a2e12;}
.c-reason .mvmt-dot{background:#5a4a00;}.c-reason .mvmt-label{color:#4a3a00;}
.c-experience .mvmt-dot{background:#2d6644;}.c-experience .mvmt-label{color:#1f4d32;}
.dot-s{background:#2d6a9f;}.dot-t{background:#7a2e12;}.dot-r{background:#5a4a00;}.dot-e{background:#2d6644;}
.course-divider{margin:2.5rem 0 1.75rem;padding-bottom:.6rem;border-bottom:1px solid #d4c9b0;font-family:'Cinzel',serif;font-size:.78rem;letter-spacing:.12em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#7a2e12;}
.placeholder-note{font-style:italic;color:#4a403a;font-size:.95rem;margin-top:1rem;padding:1.25rem;background:#fdfaf4;border:1px solid #d4c9b0;border-left:3px solid #7a2e12;}
@media(max-width:600px){.nav-tab{padding:.7rem .7rem;font-size:.65rem;}main{padding:1.75rem .9rem 4rem;}.qk-sub{display:none;}}
</style>
</head>
<body>
<header>
  <div class="eyebrow">Personal Formation Track &middot; Wesleyan-Methodist</div>
  <h1>A Daily Rule of Study</h1>
  <p class="sub">Three years. Five days a week. Every session ordered by the Wesleyan Quadrilateral.</p>
  <div class="hline"></div>
</header>

<div class="quad-key">
  <div class="qk-item"><span class="qk-dot dot-s"></span><span class="qk-label">Scripture</span><span class="qk-sub">&nbsp;&middot; 20 min</span></div>
  <div class="qk-item"><span class="qk-dot dot-t"></span><span class="qk-label">Tradition</span><span class="qk-sub">&nbsp;&middot; 35 min</span></div>
  <div class="qk-item"><span class="qk-dot dot-r"></span><span class="qk-label">Reason</span><span class="qk-sub">&nbsp;&middot; 20 min</span></div>
  <div class="qk-item"><span class="qk-dot dot-e"></span><span class="qk-label">Experience</span><span class="qk-sub">&nbsp;&middot; 15 min</span></div>
</div>

<div class="nav-outer">
  <div class="nav-year">
    <button class="nav-tab active" onclick="showYear('overview',this)">Overview</button>
    <button class="nav-tab" onclick="showYear('y1',this)">Year I</button>
    <button class="nav-tab" onclick="showYear('y2',this)">Year II</button>
    <button class="nav-tab" onclick="showYear('y3',this)">Year III</button>
  </div>
  <div class="subnav" id="sn-y1" style="display:none;">
    <button class="snav-tab active" onclick="showCourse('y1','c11',this)">1.1 Scripture</button>
    <button class="snav-tab" onclick="showCourse('y1','c12',this)">1.2 Wesleyan Theology</button>
    <button class="snav-tab" onclick="showCourse('y1','c13',this)">1.3 Prayer</button>
    <button class="snav-tab" onclick="showCourse('y1','c14',this)">1.4 Early Church</button>
  </div>
  <div class="subnav" id="sn-y2" style="display:none;">
    <button class="snav-tab active" onclick="showCourse('y2','c21',this)">2.1 Systematic Theology</button>
    <button class="snav-tab" onclick="showCourse('y2','c22',this)">2.2 Church History</button>
    <button class="snav-tab" onclick="showCourse('y2','c23',this)">2.3 Spiritual Direction</button>
  </div>
  <div class="subnav" id="sn-y3" style="display:none;">
    <button class="snav-tab active" onclick="showCourse('y3','c31',this)">3.1 Ethics</button>
    <button class="snav-tab" onclick="showCourse('y3','c32',this)">3.2 Apologetics</button>
    <button class="snav-tab" onclick="showCourse('y3','c33',this)">3.3 Capstone</button>
  </div>
</div>

<main>
<section id="overview" class="section active">
  <p class="overview-lede">Each study session follows the same four movements &mdash; Wesley&rsquo;s own sources of theological authority &mdash; applied to every day&rsquo;s content. Scripture grounds it, Tradition informs it, Reason examines it, Experience embodies it. Same structure, every day, across three years.</p>
  <div class="quad-explainer">
    <div class="quad-card"><div class="quad-card-bar" style="background:#2d6a9f;"></div><h3 style="color:#1a4a75;">Scripture</h3><p>Lectio Divina on the day&rsquo;s assigned passage. Not study &mdash; attentive listening. Let the text read you as much as you read it.</p><div class="timing">20 minutes</div></div>
    <div class="quad-card"><div class="quad-card-bar" style="background:#7a2e12;"></div><h3 style="color:#7a2e12;">Tradition</h3><p>Primary text reading &mdash; the day&rsquo;s assigned pages from the unit&rsquo;s core book. The cloud of witnesses speaks into the present moment.</p><div class="timing">35 minutes</div></div>
    <div class="quad-card"><div class="quad-card-bar" style="background:#5a4a00;"></div><h3 style="color:#4a3a00;">Reason</h3><p>A written reflection prompt. Two to three paragraphs minimum. Don&rsquo;t resolve prematurely &mdash; think on paper and let the thinking do its work.</p><div class="timing">20 minutes</div></div>
    <div class="quad-card"><div class="quad-card-bar" style="background:#2d6644;"></div><h3 style="color:#1f4d32;">Experience</h3><p>A formational practice tied to the day&rsquo;s content &mdash; prayer, silence, memorization, a physical act of obedience, an examen.</p><div class="timing">15 minutes</div></div>
  </div>
  <h3 style="font-family:'DM Sans',system-ui,sans-serif;font-size:.72rem;font-weight:600;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#7a2e12;margin-bottom:1rem;">Study Schedule</h3>
  <table class="ov-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Day</th><th>Status</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Monday</td><td>Study day</td><td>Full 90-min Quadrilateral session</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Tuesday</td><td>Study day</td><td>Full 90-min Quadrilateral session</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Wednesday</td><td>Rest</td><td>Fasting, devotional walk, no formal study</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Thursday</td><td>Study day</td><td>Full 90-min Quadrilateral session</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Friday</td><td>Study day</td><td>Full 90-min Quadrilateral session</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Saturday</td><td>Study day</td><td>Week synthesis session &mdash; review + essay</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Sunday</td><td>Sabbath</td><td>Rest, worship, no formal study</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <h3 style="font-family:'DM Sans',system-ui,sans-serif;font-size:.72rem;font-weight:600;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#7a2e12;margin-bottom:1rem;">Three-Year Map</h3>
  <table class="ov-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Year</th><th>Theme</th><th>Courses</th><th>Weeks</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Year I</td><td>Foundations &mdash; What to believe</td><td>Scripture &middot; Wesleyan Theology &middot; Prayer &middot; Early Church</td><td>~36</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Year II</td><td>Deepening &mdash; How to live it</td><td>Systematic Theology &middot; Church History &middot; Spiritual Direction</td><td>~34</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Year III</td><td>Integration &mdash; How to embody it</td><td>Ethics &middot; Apologetics &middot; Capstone</td><td>~30</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</section><section id="y1" class="section">
  <div id="y1-c11" class="course-section"><div class="course-divider">Course 1.1 &mdash; Scripture: The Story and Its Grammar</div><div class="unit-label" style="margin-top:1rem;">Unit 1 &middot; 2 Weeks</div><div class="unit-title">The Shape of the Biblical Story</div><div class="unit-desc">Reading Scripture as a single unified narrative &mdash; creation, fall, Israel, Jesus, church, new creation &mdash; and locating yourself within it. N.T. Wright as your primary guide.</div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 1</span>
        <span class="week-title">Creation, Narrative, and the Question of Story</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">In the beginning &mdash; Genesis and the grammar of creation</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Genesis 1:1&ndash;2:3<br>Read the creation account slowly, aloud if possible. First read: simply listen. Second: notice the phrase that arrests you. Third: sit in silence with it. What does <em>very good</em> mean when spoken over something that includes you?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> N.T. Wright, <em>The New Testament and the People of God</em>, Chapter 1: &ldquo;The Challenge of the New Testament.&rdquo; Wright argues the NT cannot be understood apart from its narrative world and introduces his five-act model of Scripture as a single drama. Read for the framework. Mark any passage where he explains what it means to read Scripture as <em>story</em> rather than sourcebook.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">You have read Scripture your whole life in fragments &mdash; sermons, devotionals, individual verses. What would change about how you approach a passage if you always asked first: <em>where does this sit in the larger story?</em> Write two paragraphs. Be specific about a passage you have read differently in the past.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Step outside. Look at something in creation &mdash; a tree, the sky, a plant in your South Austin yard. Sit with it for five minutes in silence. Then pray: <em>God, you called this good. Help me see it as you see it.</em> Journal one sentence about what you noticed.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The five-act drama &mdash; how Wright reads the whole Bible</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Genesis 3:1&ndash;24<br>The fall. Read it as a story, not a doctrine. What is the serpent&rsquo;s actual lie? What does the man do when confronted? Notice how quickly deflection enters the narrative. What word or image stays with you after the third reading?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> N.T. Wright, <em>The New Testament and the People of God</em>, Chapter 2: &ldquo;The Nature of History and Literature.&rdquo; Wright distinguishes between worldview-stories (the big narratives people live by) and symbol-systems. Note his argument that first-century Jews had a specific story they told about themselves &mdash; and that Jesus crashed into it. Underline his definition of &ldquo;worldview.&rdquo;</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">What is the worldview-story you told about yourself before your faith became serious? What story are you living now? Are there places where the old story still operates underneath the new one &mdash; habits of mind, patterns of fear, ways you relate to failure? Name them honestly.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray Genesis 3:9 back to God: <em>&ldquo;Where are you?&rdquo;</em> Sit in silence and let God ask it of <em>you.</em> Don&rsquo;t rush to answer. Journal where you are hiding &mdash; not in dramatic sin, but in the ordinary ways: busyness, distraction, competence, performance. One paragraph.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Abraham and the call that changes everything</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Genesis 12:1&ndash;9<br>&ldquo;Go from your country, your people and your father&rsquo;s household to the land I will show you.&rdquo; God gives no destination. Read it three times. What does it feel like to be called somewhere unnamed? What does Abraham&rsquo;s immediate obedience in verse 4 suggest about the nature of faith?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> N.T. Wright, <em>The New Testament and the People of God</em>, Chapter 3: &ldquo;Stories in Early Judaism.&rdquo; Focus on Wright&rsquo;s account of the Jewish story of exile and return &mdash; the idea that Israel was still in exile even when living in the land. This is essential background for understanding Jesus&rsquo;s announcement of the Kingdom.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wright argues the Jews of Jesus&rsquo;s day saw themselves as a people whose story was unfinished &mdash; still waiting for God to act. Does your faith feel like a finished story or an unfinished one? Where is God still acting in the narrative of your life in ways you can&rsquo;t yet see the end of? Write concretely.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>On your devotional walk today, hold one question in mind without answering it: <em>What is God calling me toward that I cannot yet name?</em> Don&rsquo;t journal about it. Just walk and hold the question open. Return and write one sentence only about what came.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Exodus &mdash; the God who acts in history</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Exodus 3:1&ndash;15<br>The burning bush. God declares his name &mdash; <em>I AM WHO I AM.</em> Moses has objections, and God addresses each one but does not remove the call. What is the relationship between God&rsquo;s self-disclosure and his commission? What word in this passage do you find yourself returning to?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> N.T. Wright, <em>The New Testament and the People of God</em>, Chapters 4&ndash;5. Pay close attention to Wright&rsquo;s argument that Jewish symbols &mdash; Temple, Torah, Land, ethnicity &mdash; were not merely religious but narrative. They were ways of saying &ldquo;we are the people in the middle of God&rsquo;s story.&rdquo;</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">What are your own narrative symbols &mdash; the objects, places, practices, relationships that embody your story with God? Your morning routine, your journal, Dana, your church, Austin itself. Write about two of them specifically. What do they mean? What would their loss mean?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray Exodus 3:14 as a declaration over your day: <em>I AM has sent me.</em> Then sit in silence for 10 minutes. What do you feel when you say those words? Relief? Resistance? Inadequacy? Write one honest paragraph about your reaction.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Synthesis &mdash; locating yourself in the biblical story</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Exodus 20:1&ndash;17<br>The Ten Commandments &mdash; but read them as a gift after rescue, not a test before acceptance. The preface is everything: <em>&ldquo;I am the Lord your God, who brought you out of Egypt.&rdquo;</em> The law comes after the exodus. What changes when you read the commands as the shape of a freed life rather than the price of freedom?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Gordon Fee &amp; Douglas Stuart, <em>How to Read the Bible for All Its Worth</em>, Chapter 1: &ldquo;Introduction: The Need to Interpret.&rdquo; Fee and Stuart are practical where Wright is theoretical. Their rules of thumb for reading Scripture carefully will ground Wright&rsquo;s larger framework in daily practice.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write one full page &mdash; your &ldquo;Story of the Story.&rdquo; In Wright&rsquo;s five-act framework (Creation, Fall, Israel, Jesus, Church/New Creation), where are you? Not abstractly &mdash; you, Trevor, in South Austin, in 2026. What act are you living in? What has come before you in the story? What are you responsible for now? What are you waiting for?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen: Review this week&rsquo;s five sessions. Where did Scripture most resist you? Where did Tradition most surprise you? Where did Reason reach its limit? Where did Experience feel most alive? Write four short answers, one per quadrant.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 2</span>
        <span class="week-title">Covenant, Law, and the Shape of the Freed Life</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Covenant &mdash; what God commits himself to</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Exodus 34:5&ndash;9<br>God proclaims his own name to Moses: <em>compassionate, gracious, slow to anger, abounding in love.</em> This is the closest the Old Testament comes to a definition of God&rsquo;s character. Read it three times. Let the list of attributes slow you down. Which one do you most need today?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Gordon Fee &amp; Douglas Stuart, <em>How to Read the Bible for All Its Worth</em>, Chapter 4: &ldquo;The Old Testament Narratives: Their Proper Use.&rdquo; Note their warnings about reading OT narratives as timeless moral lessons rather than as parts of a larger covenant story.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">The Wesleyan tradition speaks of prevenient grace &mdash; God&rsquo;s pursuit of the human before the human is even aware. Where do you see prevenient grace at work in the Old Testament narratives you&rsquo;ve read this week? Where do you see it in your own history before you named your faith?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Slowly read Exodus 34:6&ndash;7 aloud three times, each time emphasizing a different word or phrase. Then write the verse from memory without looking. What was hardest to remember? The process of memorization is itself a theological act &mdash; it moves truth from the page into the body.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The Law as gift &mdash; Torah as the shape of covenant life</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Psalm 119:97&ndash;112<br>The psalmist loves the Law. This is not legalism &mdash; it is delight in the shape of the freed life. Read it slowly. Note the words: lamp, light, sweeter than honey, inheritance. What does it mean to love a set of commands the way the psalmist does?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Gordon Fee &amp; Douglas Stuart, <em>How to Read the Bible for All Its Worth</em>, Chapter 9: &ldquo;The Law(s): Covenant Stipulations for Israel.&rdquo; Read their careful distinction between laws binding on Christians and those specific to Israel&rsquo;s covenant. Their three-category framework (civil, ceremonial, moral) is classically useful even if imperfect.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">The Wesleyan tradition holds that the moral law (as summarized in love of God and neighbor) remains in force for Christians &mdash; not as a means of justification but as the shape of sanctified life. How does this differ from legalism? Write a definition of each and a clear line between them.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Choose one of the Ten Commandments you have not violated dramatically but may treat as unnecessary for you specifically. Sit with it for ten minutes. Ask: Is there a subtle way I dishonor this? Is there a way to <em>keep</em> this more fully? Write one paragraph.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Wilderness &mdash; the formation of a people</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Deuteronomy 8:1&ndash;10<br>Moses reflects on forty years of wilderness: <em>&ldquo;He humbled you, causing you to hunger&hellip; to teach you that man does not live on bread alone.&rdquo;</em> The wilderness is not a detour from formation &mdash; it is the method of it. What word lands most heavily on you today?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Dallas Willard, <em>The Spirit of the Disciplines</em>, Chapter 1: &ldquo;The Secret of the Spiritual Life.&rdquo; Willard argues formation is never passive &mdash; it requires the intentional arrangement of our lives. Read his concept of spiritual training in light of Israel&rsquo;s wilderness formation.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">What has been your wilderness &mdash; the season God used not to punish but to form? Not necessarily a dramatic crisis. It may be the long slow season of not knowing, of waiting, of diminishment. What did it produce in you that easier seasons could not have? Write honestly.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Today is a fast day. Let the hunger you feel remind you of Deuteronomy 8:3. Each time you feel the absence of food, say the verse aloud: <em>&ldquo;Man does not live on bread alone, but on every word that comes from the mouth of God.&rdquo;</em> Let the body be a teacher.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Promise and Land &mdash; reading the Old Testament forward</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Joshua 1:1&ndash;9<br><em>&ldquo;Be strong and courageous&hellip; for the Lord your God will be with you wherever you go.&rdquo;</em> Moses is dead. Joshua inherits an unfinished promise. Notice what God commands Joshua to do with the Law: meditate on it day and night. What does <em>meditate</em> mean in practice?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Christopher Wright, <em>Knowing God Through the Old Testament</em>, Introduction and Chapter 1: &ldquo;The God Who Keeps His Promises.&rdquo; Wright argues the OT is primarily a revelation of God&rsquo;s character, not a collection of types pointing to Christ. Read his case for reading the OT on its own terms first.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Christopher Wright argues we cannot know Jesus fully without knowing the God of the Old Testament. The NT writers assumed their readers knew the Hebrew story. What do you lose if you skip the Old Testament? What specifically changes about your understanding of the cross if you don&rsquo;t know the Exodus?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray Joshua 1:9 as a commission over your own life. Write it out by hand. Then write beneath it: one thing you are currently afraid of that you are being asked to move toward anyway. Pray it specifically. Don&rsquo;t resolve it &mdash; just name it before God.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Unit 1 synthesis &mdash; the Story and your place in it</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Romans 15:4<br>A single verse. <em>&ldquo;For everything that was written in the past was written to teach us, so that through the endurance taught in the Scriptures and the encouragement they provide we might have hope.&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times slowly. What does Paul assume about the relationship between the old story and the new community?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Return to your notes and underlines from both weeks of Unit 1. Re-read the passages you marked. Identify the single most important claim Wright makes about reading Scripture as story. Write it in one sentence &mdash; as clearly as you can &mdash; as if explaining it to someone who has never considered the idea.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Unit 1 synthesis essay (one full page): &ldquo;How reading Scripture as a unified story changes everything.&rdquo; Argue the case. Use at least two examples from the passages you&rsquo;ve studied. Address the Wesleyan angle: if Scripture is a story about God&rsquo;s relentless pursuit of humanity through grace, what does that say about human freedom and responsibility within the plot?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Unit Examen: What is one thing these two weeks have done <em>in</em> you &mdash; not just taught you? What is one belief you held before Unit 1 that you now hold differently? What is one practice you want to carry forward from this unit into the rest of your life?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div><div class="unit-label" style="margin-top:2.5rem;">Unit 2 &middot; 3 Weeks</div><div class="unit-title">How to Read the Old Testament</div><div class="unit-desc">Isaiah 40&ndash;55, the Servant Songs, and the character of God revealed through Israel&rsquo;s deepest suffering and greatest hope. Isaiah 53 read now in full context.</div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 3</span>
        <span class="week-title">The God Who Speaks into Exile &mdash; Isaiah 40&ndash;48</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Comfort, comfort my people &mdash; the voice of Isaiah 40</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Isaiah 40:1&ndash;11<br><em>&ldquo;Comfort, comfort my people, says your God.&rdquo;</em> Context: Israel is in Babylonian exile, the temple destroyed. God speaks comfort into the worst moment. Read it three times. Which phrase arrests you most &mdash; and why today specifically?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> John Goldingay, <em>Old Testament Theology, Vol. 1: Israel&rsquo;s Gospel</em>, Chapter 1 opening. Goldingay argues the Old Testament is itself a &ldquo;gospel&rdquo; &mdash; good news &mdash; before the New Testament arrives. Read his framing of Isaiah as proclamation, not merely prediction.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Isaiah 40 is addressed to a people in exile who cannot see how God&rsquo;s promises still hold. When have you been in that position &mdash; where the evidence suggested God&rsquo;s word had failed? How does Isaiah&rsquo;s response (not argument but proclamation) address that kind of doubt differently than rational defense does?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Read Isaiah 40:28&ndash;31 aloud, standing up. Then sit and be still for 10 minutes. Let the words do their work. Write one sentence: what does hope feel like in your body right now, in this moment?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The incomparable God &mdash; Isaiah 40:12&ndash;31</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Isaiah 40:12&ndash;26<br>A rapid-fire sequence of rhetorical questions about God&rsquo;s incomparability. <em>&ldquo;Who has measured the waters in the hollow of his hand?&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Let the questions accumulate. By the end, what do they produce in you &mdash; awe, smallness, relief?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> A.W. Tozer, <em>The Knowledge of the Holy</em>, Chapter 1: &ldquo;Why We Must Think Rightly About God&rdquo; and Chapter 4: &ldquo;The Self-Existence of God.&rdquo; Tozer argues that a low view of God is the root of all spiritual poverty. Note where his argument about God&rsquo;s character connects to what Isaiah proclaims.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Tozer says &ldquo;what comes into our minds when we think about God is the most important thing about us.&rdquo; What actually comes into your mind &mdash; not what you believe you should think, but what comes unbidden when you picture God? Write it honestly. Then write what Isaiah 40 says about God and notice the gap.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Worship walk. Take your devotional walk today in worship only &mdash; not petition, not intercession. Just acknowledgment of who God is. Use Isaiah 40&rsquo;s language: incomparable, everlasting, creator of the ends of the earth. Let the walk be a single extended act of recognition.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The first Servant Song &mdash; Isaiah 42</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Isaiah 42:1&ndash;9<br><em>&ldquo;Here is my servant, whom I uphold, my chosen one in whom I delight.&rdquo;</em> Who is the servant? Read it three times. What does the servant&rsquo;s method tell you &mdash; not loud, not crying out in the streets, not breaking a bruised reed? What word or phrase stays?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Christopher Wright, <em>Knowing God Through the Old Testament</em>, Chapter 3: &ldquo;The God Who Redeems.&rdquo; Wright traces the concept of redemption through the OT &mdash; not as a transaction but as a relationship of rescue by a near kinsman. Read his account of <em>go&rsquo;el</em> (redeemer) and let it reshape how you understand what God does in Isaiah.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">The Servant in Isaiah 42 does not accomplish his mission through power but through gentleness and faithfulness. He &ldquo;will not falter or be discouraged till he establishes justice.&rdquo; How does this portrait challenge your default images of how God acts? How does it challenge your own approach to influence and persuasion?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Intercessory prayer. Pray for one person in your life who is a &ldquo;bruised reed&rdquo; right now &mdash; fragile, close to breaking. Don&rsquo;t pray for them to get better. Pray for them the way the Servant tends them: without crushing, without quenching. Sit in silence after for five minutes.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Isaiah 49 &mdash; the Servant&rsquo;s call and its cost</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Isaiah 49:1&ndash;7<br><em>&ldquo;I have labored in vain; I have spent my strength for nothing at all.&rdquo;</em> The Servant confesses a sense of futility &mdash; and then receives a more expansive commission. What does it mean that faithfulness passes through the experience of apparent failure?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> John Goldingay, <em>Old Testament Theology, Vol. 1</em>, section on Isaiah&rsquo;s Servant. Goldingay is careful about not rushing the Servant Songs to Jesus &mdash; he reads them first as Israel&rsquo;s self-understanding as a light to the nations.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Have you experienced a season of &ldquo;labored in vain&rdquo; &mdash; where your faithfulness seemed to produce nothing? The Servant&rsquo;s response is not to try harder but to trust that God&rsquo;s purposes are larger than visible results. Write about one area of your life where you are being asked to be faithful without visible fruit right now.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Begin memorizing Isaiah 53:4&ndash;6 this week. Today: read it aloud five times, slowly. Don&rsquo;t try to memorize yet &mdash; just let the words enter you. Write it out once by hand. What do you notice when you write it that you didn&rsquo;t notice when you read it?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Week synthesis &mdash; what exile teaches about God</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Isaiah 43:1&ndash;7<br><em>&ldquo;Do not fear, for I have redeemed you; I have summoned you by name; you are mine.&rdquo;</em> Note the verbs of intimacy and belonging &mdash; not possession in the sense of control but belonging in the sense of covenant. What does &ldquo;you are mine&rdquo; feel like to receive?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Return to this week&rsquo;s reading notes. Re-read the passages you underlined in Goldingay, Tozer, and Christopher Wright. Identify one idea from each author that most changed how you read Isaiah. Write one sentence per author capturing the key insight.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Isaiah speaks to a people in exile. God does not explain why it happened &mdash; he simply speaks comfort and commission. How do you hold together the silence of God in suffering (Isaiah 40&ndash;49 does not answer &ldquo;why&rdquo;) with the proclaimed presence of God in suffering? Write your honest theology of this tension.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Isaiah 53:4&ndash;6 memorization. Write it from memory. Check it. Write it again. Note what you got wrong &mdash; the gaps are not failures but the places where the text has not yet settled into your body.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 4</span>
        <span class="week-title">Isaiah 52&ndash;55 &mdash; The Suffering Servant and New Creation</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Isaiah 52:13&ndash;53:12 &mdash; your anchor, read in full context</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Isaiah 52:13&ndash;53:12<br>Read it aloud. Slowly. All of it. Three times. You have read this passage before &mdash; but you have now read the twelve chapters that precede it. Notice what changes. What do you hear differently now that you&rsquo;ve lived in Isaiah 40&ndash;51 for a week?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Christopher Wright, <em>Knowing God Through the Old Testament</em>, Chapter 5: &ldquo;The God Who Suffers.&rdquo; Wright asks: does God suffer? He traces this question through Isaiah and the psalms of lament. His argument &mdash; that the Servant&rsquo;s suffering reveals something about the nature of God himself &mdash; is careful and moving. Read slowly.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Isaiah 53 has been your evidential anchor for the Christian claim. Having now read it in the context of Isaiah 40&ndash;52 &mdash; with Israel in exile, three prior Servant Songs, the promise of new exodus &mdash; how has the meaning deepened or shifted? What does it say about God&rsquo;s <em>character</em>, not only about atonement?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Write Isaiah 53:4&ndash;6 from memory. Then read the whole passage once more, slowly. Sit in silence for five minutes. Let it be prayer without words. This is not a study exercise &mdash; it is an encounter. What do you want to say to God after reading it?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Isaiah 54&ndash;55 &mdash; invitation and new creation</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Isaiah 55:1&ndash;13<br><em>&ldquo;Come, all you who are thirsty, come to the waters&hellip; without money and without cost.&rdquo;</em> The grand invitation after the Servant&rsquo;s suffering. Read it three times. Notice the economic metaphor. What does this say about the nature of salvation? What word do you carry?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Randy Maddox, <em>Responsible Grace</em>, Chapter 3 opening section on &ldquo;Grace as Responsible Love.&rdquo; Maddox introduces Wesley&rsquo;s view of grace not as a force but as a relational reality &mdash; God&rsquo;s love pursuing, enabling, and inviting. Read his account of prevenient grace in light of Isaiah 55&rsquo;s open invitation.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Isaiah 55 ends with <em>&ldquo;the mountains and hills will burst into song and all the trees of the field will clap their hands.&rdquo;</em> New creation language &mdash; the whole cosmos responding to the rescue. What would it mean for Isaiah 55&rsquo;s invitation to be literally true, not metaphorically true? What would you have to believe about the material world?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray Isaiah 55:8&ndash;9 as a posture of release: <em>&ldquo;My thoughts are not your thoughts, neither are your ways my ways.&rdquo;</em> Choose one situation where you have been insisting on your own understanding of how things should go. Hold it open-handed before God. Write one sentence of release.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Reading the OT christologically &mdash; without flattening it</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Luke 24:25&ndash;27, 44&ndash;47<br>The risen Jesus on the road to Emmaus, explaining that <em>&ldquo;everything must be fulfilled that is written about me in the Law of Moses, the Prophets, and the Psalms.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. What does Jesus assume about his disciples&rsquo; ability to read the Old Testament?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Gordon Fee &amp; Douglas Stuart, <em>How to Read the Bible for All Its Worth</em>, Chapter 6: &ldquo;The Prophets: Enforcing the Covenant in Israel.&rdquo; Fee and Stuart are careful: not every prophet is a prediction of Christ. They give a framework for distinguishing direct messianic prophecy from covenant enforcement. Read their guidelines carefully.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">How do you read the Old Testament now &mdash; differently than before this unit? Write a brief methodology: three principles you will apply when you open the Hebrew scriptures going forward. Not abstract rules &mdash; actual questions you will ask of the text each time you open it.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Write Isaiah 53:4&ndash;6 from memory one final time without looking. Then speak it aloud as a personal confession in first person: <em>&ldquo;He took up my infirmities.&rdquo;</em> Let it be prayer, not recitation. Sit in silence afterward.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The character of God in the Old Testament &mdash; who is this God?</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Hosea 11:1&ndash;11<br><em>&ldquo;When Israel was a child, I loved him&hellip; How can I give you up, Ephraim?&rdquo;</em> God speaks as a parent grieving over a wayward child. The emotional register here is startling &mdash; grief, longing, refusal to abandon. Read it three times. What does this passage do to your image of God?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Christopher Wright, <em>Knowing God Through the Old Testament</em>, Chapter 6: &ldquo;The God Who Loves.&rdquo; Wright argues the Old Testament is saturated with the language of divine love &mdash; <em>hesed</em> (steadfast love), <em>rahamim</em> (compassion, from the word for womb). Read his account of these terms and let them re-color the OT you&rsquo;ve been reading.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">The God of the Old Testament is often caricatured as wrathful and the God of the New Testament as loving. Having spent three weeks in Isaiah and surrounding texts: how would you respond to that caricature? What have these texts shown you about God&rsquo;s character that doesn&rsquo;t fit the stereotype?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray Hosea 11:1&ndash;4 back to God from your own position &mdash; as the child who was called and went after idols. Name the idols. Not dramatically &mdash; just the quiet ones: comfort, reputation, control, certainty. Hold each one before God without explanation.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Unit 2 synthesis &mdash; the Old Testament as your Scripture</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 2 Timothy 3:14&ndash;17<br><em>&ldquo;All Scripture is God-breathed and is useful for teaching, rebuking, correcting, and training in righteousness.&rdquo;</em> When Paul wrote this, &ldquo;Scripture&rdquo; meant the Hebrew Bible. Read it three times. What does it mean that the OT is sufficient to make you &ldquo;thoroughly equipped for every good work&rdquo;?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your journal entries from the past three weeks. Look for patterns: where did God show up consistently? Where did you resist the text? Which readings produced the most movement? Write a half-page summary of what this unit has done to your reading of the Old Testament.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Unit 2 synthesis essay: &ldquo;Isaiah 53 in context.&rdquo; Now that you have read the chapter in its literary and theological setting &mdash; the Servant Songs, the exile, the new exodus, the God of <em>hesed</em> &mdash; write one full page on what the passage means. Not just as a prediction of the cross, but as a revelation of how God operates in history.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Recite Isaiah 53:4&ndash;6 from memory. Then sit in silence for 10 minutes &mdash; no agenda, no petition. Just presence. Weekly Examen: one sentence per quadrant on what Scripture, Tradition, Reason, and Experience each did in you this week.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>  </div>
  <div id="y1-c12" class="course-section" style="display:none;"><div class="course-divider">Course 1.2 &mdash; Wesleyan Theology: The Distinctive Grammar</div><div class="unit-label" style="margin-top:2rem;">Unit 1 &middot; 2 Weeks</div><div class="unit-title">Wesley the Man</div><div class="unit-desc">Who was John Wesley? Not an icon but a person &mdash; driven, flawed, insatiably curious, and inexhaustibly energetic. His biography is itself a theology of what happens when prevenient grace gets a willing collaborator.</div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 1</span>
        <span class="week-title">John Wesley: Oxford, Aldersgate, and the formation of a reformer</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Before Aldersgate &mdash; the moralist who couldn't be moral enough</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Romans 7:14&ndash;25<br><em>&ldquo;I do not do the good I want to do, but the evil I do not want to do &mdash; this I keep on doing.&rdquo;</em> Paul&rsquo;s confession of internal contradiction. Read it three times. This was Wesley&rsquo;s experience before Aldersgate. What word or phrase arrests you most today?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Kenneth Collins, <em>The Theology of John Wesley</em>, Chapter 1: &ldquo;The Way of Salvation.&rdquo; Collins traces Wesley&rsquo;s early life &mdash; the Holy Club at Oxford, the Georgia mission failure, the encounter with Moravians. Read his account of what Wesley was trying to achieve and why it wasn&rsquo;t working.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wesley spent years trying to earn what he already had access to through grace. Where do you recognize the same pattern in yourself &mdash; performing for an acceptance that has already been offered? Write about a specific current area, not a past one.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray Romans 7:24&ndash;25 back to God: <em>&ldquo;What a wretched man I am! Who will rescue me from this body that is subject to death? Thanks be to God, who delivers me through Jesus Christ our Lord!&rdquo;</em> The answer comes immediately after the cry. Sit with that sequence. Journal one sentence.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Aldersgate &mdash; the heart strangely warmed</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Ephesians 2:1&ndash;10<br><em>&ldquo;For it is by grace you have been saved, through faith &mdash; and this is not from yourselves, it is the gift of God.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. This is the doctrine Wesley heard preached at Aldersgate. What does it feel like to read these words as a gift rather than a demand?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Kenneth Collins, <em>The Theology of John Wesley</em>, Chapter 2: &ldquo;Justification by Faith.&rdquo; Collins traces what changed for Wesley at Aldersgate &mdash; not a new doctrine but a new experience of a doctrine he already knew. Read his careful account of assurance and how it differs from presumption.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wesley famously said his heart was &ldquo;strangely warmed&rdquo; &mdash; not &ldquo;my mind was finally convinced.&rdquo; What is the difference between intellectual assent to a doctrine and experiential assurance of it? Do you have assurance? What does it feel like when you have it, and what does its absence feel like?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Wesley&rsquo;s journal entry from May 24, 1738: he went to a Moravian meeting on Aldersgate Street &ldquo;very unwillingly.&rdquo; God met him in his reluctance. Pray for the place in your own life where you are showing up &ldquo;very unwillingly.&rdquo; What might God be doing there?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The Georgia failure &mdash; what grace teaches through humiliation</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 2 Corinthians 12:9&ndash;10<br><em>&ldquo;My grace is sufficient for you, for my power is made perfect in weakness.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Before Wesley&rsquo;s success there was spectacular failure &mdash; mission, romantic disaster, near-legal disaster. What word arrests you today?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> D. Bruce Hindmarsh, <em>The Spirit of Early Evangelicalism</em>, Chapter 1: &ldquo;The Formation of Evangelical Identity.&rdquo; Hindmarsh traces how the evangelical movement of the 18th century was shaped not despite its failures but through them. Read his account of what failure does that success cannot.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wesley&rsquo;s Georgia mission was a disaster by any external measure &mdash; yet it was formative in ways his Oxford successes were not. What has failure done in you that success has not been able to do? Be specific. Don&rsquo;t theologize it &mdash; name it.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Write one paragraph about a failure you have not yet fully received as formative. Then pray: <em>God, what are you doing here that I cannot yet see?</em> Sit in silence for 10 minutes. Don&rsquo;t demand an answer.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Wesley&rsquo;s method &mdash; why he organized everything</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Acts 2:42&ndash;47<br>The first Christian community: devoted to teaching, fellowship, breaking bread, prayer. Read it three times. Wesley looked at this passage and built the class meeting system to approximate it. What does &ldquo;devoted&rdquo; mean in this context? What word arrests you?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> David Hempton, <em>Methodism: Empire of the Spirit</em>, Chapter 1: &ldquo;The Making of a Methodist.&rdquo; Hempton traces how Wesley&rsquo;s methods &mdash; class meetings, field preaching, itinerant ministry, the connexion &mdash; were not bureaucratic but spiritual. Read his account of how organization was itself a means of grace for Wesley.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wesley believed the Holy Spirit works through structure, not just spontaneity. He organized class meetings of 12, bands of intimates, and quarterly love feasts. What structures in your own life currently support your formation? What structures are missing that you know you need?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Wesley&rsquo;s General Rules for the early Methodist societies: (1) Do no harm. (2) Do all the good you can. (3) Attend to the ordinances of God. Write these out slowly. Then: apply each rule to one specific area of your life this week. Write three sentences &mdash; one per rule.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Week synthesis &mdash; what Wesley&rsquo;s biography teaches</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 1 Timothy 4:7&ndash;8<br><em>&ldquo;Train yourself to be godly. For physical training is of some value, but godliness has value for all things.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Paul uses an athletic metaphor for spiritual formation. What does it mean to <em>train</em> for godliness rather than simply intend it?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your notes from this week. Then read Wesley&rsquo;s own account of Aldersgate from his <em>Journal</em>, May 24, 1738 (available free online). Read it slowly &mdash; Wesley&rsquo;s own words, not a summary.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write a one-page response to Wesley&rsquo;s life so far: What in his formation do you recognize in your own? What in his failures do you recognize? What in his breakthrough do you want? Don&rsquo;t write about Wesley &mdash; write about yourself, using Wesley as the mirror.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen: four sentences, one per quadrant. Then one specific practice from Wesley&rsquo;s General Rules you will carry into next week. Name it. Write it.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 2</span>
        <span class="week-title">Wesley&rsquo;s world &mdash; the revival and its enemies</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Field preaching &mdash; taking the gospel to the margins</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Luke 4:16&ndash;21<br>Jesus reads from Isaiah in the synagogue and announces the Kingdom: good news to the poor, freedom for prisoners, sight for the blind. Read it three times. Wesley began field preaching because the poor had no access to churches. What does Jesus&rsquo;s announcement imply about where the Kingdom goes first?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> David Hempton, <em>Methodism: Empire of the Spirit</em>, Chapter 2: &ldquo;Method, Passion, and Power.&rdquo; Hempton traces the sociology of early Methodism &mdash; why it exploded among the working poor, the miners, the marginalized. Read his account of why the poor responded to Wesley where the educated didn&rsquo;t.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wesley preached to coal miners at Kingswood who had no church access and were considered unevangelizable. He went to them rather than waiting for them to come to him. What does this say about how the gospel travels? Where in your own life are you waiting for someone to come to you when you should go?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray Luke 4:18 as a personal commission: <em>&ldquo;The Spirit of the Lord is on me, because he has anointed me to proclaim good news to the poor.&rdquo;</em> Who are the &ldquo;poor&rdquo; in your specific world? Name them. Pray for two of them specifically.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Opposition and perseverance &mdash; Wesley&rsquo;s critics</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Acts 5:38&ndash;39<br>Gamaliel&rsquo;s counsel: <em>&ldquo;If their purpose or activity is of human origin, it will fail. But if it is from God, you will not be able to stop these men.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Wesley faced mobs, church exclusion, and academic contempt. What enables someone to continue in the face of sustained institutional opposition?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> D. Bruce Hindmarsh, <em>The Spirit of Early Evangelicalism</em>, Chapter 2: &ldquo;The Formation of Evangelical Experience.&rdquo; Hindmarsh traces how early evangelicals &mdash; Wesley, Whitefield, Edwards &mdash; developed a shared grammar of experience that sustained them through opposition. Read his account of what they held in common.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wesley was excluded from Anglican pulpits, attacked by mobs, and accused of enthusiasm (the 18th-century version of being unhinged). Yet he persevered for 50 years. What is the difference between stubborn ego and Spirit-empowered perseverance? How would you tell the difference in your own life when you face opposition?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Think of one legitimate, Spirit-led thing you have backed away from because of opposition or discouragement. Sit with it for 10 minutes. Pray Gamaliel&rsquo;s test over it: <em>Is this of human origin or of God?</em> Write your honest answer.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Wesley and Whitefield &mdash; the Calvinist rupture</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Romans 9:14&ndash;16<br><em>&ldquo;I will have mercy on whom I have mercy, and I will have compassion on whom I have compassion.&rdquo;</em> This is the Calvinist&rsquo;s anchor text. Read it three times. How does the Wesleyan account of prevenient grace respond to this passage without ignoring it?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Alister McGrath, <em>Christianity&rsquo;s Dangerous Idea</em>, Chapter 6: &ldquo;Calvin&rsquo;s Legacy.&rdquo; McGrath traces the Reformed tradition&rsquo;s distinctive commitments. Read his account of the Calvinist-Arminian fault line that split Wesley and Whitefield despite their friendship.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wesley and Whitefield were both converted, both field preachers, both used powerfully by God &mdash; and they disagreed sharply on election and predestination. Write a clear statement of the Calvinist position and the Wesleyan position. Where is the genuine theological difference? Where is it a difference of emphasis? Where might both be wrong?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray for a Christian you disagree with theologically &mdash; not someone you dislike, but someone whose theology you think is genuinely mistaken. Pray for them as a brother or sister. Notice what praying for them does to your posture toward the disagreement. Write one sentence.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Social holiness &mdash; Wesley and the abolition of slavery</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Amos 5:21&ndash;24<br><em>&ldquo;But let justice roll on like a river, righteousness like a never-failing stream!&rdquo;</em> God rejects worship without justice. Read it three times. Wesley&rsquo;s last letter before his death was to William Wilberforce, urging abolition. What does it say about his theology that holiness demanded political action?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> David Hempton, <em>Methodism: Empire of the Spirit</em>, Chapter 4: &ldquo;Methodism and Society.&rdquo; Hempton traces how Wesleyan theology generated social reform movements &mdash; abolition, prison reform, orphan care, education for the poor. Read his account of what in the theology made this possible.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wesley argued that &ldquo;there is no holiness but social holiness.&rdquo; He did not mean holiness is a social project &mdash; he meant the holy life cannot be lived in isolation from others. What social consequence does your faith currently have? Not what you believe it should have in principle &mdash; what it actually has in practice?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Read Wesley&rsquo;s letter to William Wilberforce (February 24, 1791) &mdash; available free online. It is 200 words, written by a dying 87-year-old. Read it slowly. Then write: what is the William Wilberforce moment in your own world &mdash; the cause your faith is supposed to be funding with its energy?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Unit 1 synthesis &mdash; the man and his method</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Philippians 3:12&ndash;14<br><em>&ldquo;Not that I have already obtained all this, or have already arrived at my goal, but I press on.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Wesley pressed on for 50 years. What does &ldquo;pressing on&rdquo; actually look like across a lifetime? What keeps it from becoming mere stubbornness?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Kenneth Collins, <em>The Theology of John Wesley</em>, Chapter 12: &ldquo;The Nature of Salvation.&rdquo; Collins provides a theological synthesis of Wesley&rsquo;s soteriology. Read his summary of the <em>ordo salutis</em> (order of salvation) in Wesley: prevenient grace &rarr; repentance &rarr; justification &rarr; new birth &rarr; sanctification &rarr; entire sanctification.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write one full page: &ldquo;What Wesley&rsquo;s life teaches me about mine.&rdquo; Address specifically: what his failures show you, what his perseverance asks of you, what his social holiness demands of you, and what his method suggests you need that you don&rsquo;t currently have.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: one concrete thing from Wesley&rsquo;s practice &mdash; the General Rules, the class meeting, the social engagement &mdash; that you want to incorporate into your own Rule of Life. Write it.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div><div class="unit-label" style="margin-top:2rem;">Unit 2 &middot; 2 Weeks</div><div class="unit-title">Prevenient Grace</div><div class="unit-desc">The most distinctively Wesleyan idea in all of Christian theology: God&rsquo;s grace that goes before us, enabling our response before we even know we are responding. This is not a minor footnote &mdash; it is the hinge on which Wesleyan soteriology turns.</div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 3</span>
        <span class="week-title">What prevenient grace is &mdash; and what it requires</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Grace before faith &mdash; the God who pursues first</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> John 6:44<br><em>&ldquo;No one can come to me unless the Father who sent me draws them.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Calvinists read &ldquo;draws&rdquo; as irresistible. Wesleyans read it as a real but resistible drawing given to all. What does your theology require you to do with this verse? What does it say about the God who draws?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Randy Maddox, <em>Responsible Grace</em>, Chapter 3: &ldquo;The God of Responsible Grace: Prevenient Grace.&rdquo; Maddox gives the definitive account of prevenient grace in the Wesleyan tradition &mdash; how it differs from Calvinist irresistible grace and from Pelagian human initiative. Read carefully.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Prevenient grace means no one comes to God in a vacuum &mdash; they come because God was already working in them before they were aware of it. Trace the prevenient grace in your own story. Where was God working in you before you named it? What drew you? Who was used? What prepared the ground?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray for one person you love who does not yet believe. Not for their conversion &mdash; for your awareness of where prevenient grace is already at work in them. Ask God to show you what he is already doing. Write one sentence about what you see.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Resistible grace &mdash; what human freedom actually means</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Revelation 3:20<br><em>&ldquo;Here I am! I stand at the door and knock.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The door has a handle on the inside. God knocks &mdash; he does not break in. What does this image say about the nature of divine love and human freedom?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Randy Maddox, <em>Responsible Grace</em>, Chapter 4: &ldquo;Responsible Grace: Human Response-ability.&rdquo; Maddox traces Wesley&rsquo;s insistence that grace restores, not eliminates, human agency. The Wesleyan term is &ldquo;response-ability&rdquo; &mdash; grace enables response but does not compel it. Read carefully.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">The Calvinist objection: if grace is resistible, can God guarantee anything? The Wesleyan answer: God does not guarantee individual outcomes but guarantees his own relentless pursuit. Write your honest evaluation. Which account of God&rsquo;s sovereignty do you find more theologically coherent? Which do you find more personally liveable?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Where are you currently resisting something you sense God drawing you toward? Name it honestly before God. Then sit in silence for 10 minutes without resolving it. The awareness itself is part of the work.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Conscience as vehicle of prevenient grace</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Romans 2:14&ndash;16<br>Paul argues that Gentiles &mdash; without the Law &mdash; show &ldquo;the requirements of the law written on their hearts, their consciences also bearing witness.&rdquo; Read it three times. Wesley argued this universal moral conscience is the operation of prevenient grace. What does this mean for how you treat the moral intuitions of non-Christians?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Kenneth Collins, <em>The Theology of John Wesley</em>, Chapter 3: &ldquo;Prevenient Grace.&rdquo; Collins traces how Wesley understood the <em>imago Dei</em> as partially restored by prevenient grace in all people &mdash; which is why conscience, beauty, and moral intuition exist outside the church.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">If prevenient grace operates in all people through conscience and beauty, what does this mean for your engagement with people who are not Christians? Does it change how you listen to them, argue with them, learn from them? Write a concrete implication for one specific relationship in your life right now.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Think of a non-Christian in your life whose moral instincts you respect or whose perception of truth impresses you. Spend 10 minutes considering: where is God already at work in them? Then pray for them &mdash; not as a project but as someone already being pursued.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Original sin and the need for grace</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Romans 5:12&ndash;19<br>Paul&rsquo;s account of the two Adams: sin entered through one man, grace came through the other. Read it three times. Note the asymmetry: where sin increased, grace increased more. What does Paul&rsquo;s &ldquo;much more&rdquo; and &ldquo;how much more&rdquo; suggest about the relative power of sin and grace?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Randy Maddox, <em>Responsible Grace</em>, Chapter 5: &ldquo;The Corruption of Human Nature.&rdquo; Maddox traces Wesley&rsquo;s view of original sin &mdash; not that humans are as bad as they could possibly be, but that their capacity to respond to God is damaged and requires the restoration that prevenient grace provides.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wesley held both original sin (humanity is genuinely corrupted) and prevenient grace (God has given all people enough restoration to be able to respond). These two claims together produce the Wesleyan view of evangelism: everyone can respond, and everyone needs to. Write what these two claims change about how you think about the people you encounter in your sales work and in Austin.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Daily examen with a prevenient grace lens: Where did you encounter someone today in whom you sensed God at work? Where did someone speak truth or show beauty or act with justice in ways that surprised you? Write two examples and pray a blessing over each person.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Unit 2 synthesis &mdash; grace all the way down</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Psalm 139:7&ndash;12<br><em>&ldquo;Where can I go from your Spirit? Where can I flee from your presence?&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The psalmist discovers that God&rsquo;s presence is inescapable &mdash; not as threat but as reassurance. This is prevenient grace in the Psalms: nowhere you can go where God is not already there.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your notes from Maddox and Collins this unit. Then read Wesley&rsquo;s sermon &ldquo;On Working Out Our Own Salvation&rdquo; (Philippians 2:12&ndash;13). Wesley uses this passage to show how divine grace and human effort are not in competition: &ldquo;God works, therefore work.&rdquo;</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Unit 2 synthesis essay: &ldquo;How prevenient grace changes everything.&rdquo; One full page. Address: (1) what it means that God was pursuing you before you knew it, (2) what it means that grace is resistible, (3) what it means that all people have enough grace to respond, and (4) what this does to the way you see the people around you who are not yet believers.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: one way you will pray differently this week because of what you have learned about prevenient grace. Write it specifically.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div><div class="unit-label" style="margin-top:2rem;">Unit 3 &middot; 3 Weeks</div><div class="unit-title">Justification and Sanctification</div><div class="unit-desc">Wesley held two things simultaneously that others tend to separate: you are fully justified before God through faith alone, and you are progressively transformed into the image of Christ. Both are by grace. Neither is optional.</div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 4</span>
        <span class="week-title">Justification &mdash; what God declares</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Justification by faith &mdash; the Reformation insight Wesley kept</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Romans 3:21&ndash;26<br><em>&ldquo;This righteousness is given through faith in Jesus Christ to all who believe.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Paul&rsquo;s word <em>dikaioo</em> &mdash; to justify &mdash; is a legal declaration, not a moral transformation. What does it mean to be declared righteous before you are made righteous? What word arrests you?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Kenneth Collins, <em>The Theology of John Wesley</em>, Chapter 5: &ldquo;Justification and the New Birth.&rdquo; Collins traces Wesley&rsquo;s carefully qualified appropriation of the Reformation doctrine &mdash; justification is relative change (our standing before God) while sanctification is real change (our nature). Both are essential.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wesley said justification answers the question &ldquo;What has God done for me?&rdquo; while sanctification answers &ldquo;What is God doing in me?&rdquo; These are not the same question. Which question do you live in most naturally? Which do you neglect? Write honestly.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray Galatians 2:20 slowly: <em>&ldquo;I have been crucified with Christ and I no longer live, but Christ lives in me.&rdquo;</em> This is both justification (crucified with Christ) and sanctification (Christ lives in me) in one sentence. Sit with it for 10 minutes. What does it mean for Christ to &ldquo;live in you&rdquo; today specifically?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Assurance &mdash; knowing you are known</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Romans 8:15&ndash;17<br><em>&ldquo;The Spirit himself testifies with our spirit that we are God&rsquo;s children.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Wesley placed great weight on the witness of the Spirit &mdash; an inner assurance of adoption that is not mere feeling but Spirit-mediated certainty. Do you have this? What does its presence or absence feel like?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Randy Maddox, <em>Responsible Grace</em>, Chapter 7: &ldquo;Assurance of Salvation.&rdquo; Maddox traces how Wesley distinguished the direct witness of the Spirit (an immediate assurance) from the indirect witness (the fruit of a changed life). Read his careful account of how these two work together.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wesley said assurance is the normal expectation of Christian experience, not an optional extra. Yet he also knew seasons of its absence (his Georgia years). Write your honest account: Do you currently have assurance? If so, what grounds it &mdash; the Spirit&rsquo;s witness, the fruit of your life, or doctrine? If not, what would help?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Sit in silence for 10 minutes and allow yourself to hear &mdash; or notice the absence of &mdash; the Spirit&rsquo;s witness. Don&rsquo;t manufacture it. Don&rsquo;t panic at its absence. Write one honest sentence about what was present in the silence.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The new birth &mdash; what changes at conversion</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> John 3:1&ndash;8<br>The conversation with Nicodemus. <em>&ldquo;You must be born again.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Notice that Nicodemus is a Pharisee &mdash; a religious professional, not a pagan. The new birth is not for the obviously irreligious. It is for everyone. What does <em>born again</em> mean that <em>morally improved</em> doesn&rsquo;t?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Kenneth Collins, <em>The Theology of John Wesley</em>, Chapter 6: &ldquo;The New Birth.&rdquo; Collins traces Wesley&rsquo;s distinction between justification (what God declares) and the new birth (what God begins to do in us). The new birth is the initiating moment of sanctification &mdash; the beginning of real transformation, not just declared status.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wesley distinguished between the outward sign (baptism) and the inward reality (new birth) &mdash; insisting the latter cannot be assumed from the former. Can you name the moment of your new birth, or the season in which it happened? What changed? What did not change that you expected would? Write your account.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Write a letter to yourself at the moment of your new birth &mdash; or if you can&rsquo;t name a specific moment, to yourself at the earliest point of genuine spiritual awakening. What do you want to tell that person? What do you know now that they didn&rsquo;t?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Sanctification begins &mdash; what the Spirit starts</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 2 Corinthians 3:18<br><em>&ldquo;We all, who with unveiled faces contemplate the Lord&rsquo;s glory, are being transformed into his image with ever-increasing glory, which comes from the Lord, who is the Spirit.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Note the passive: being transformed. Note the agent: the Lord, who is the Spirit. What is your role in this?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Dallas Willard, <em>Renovation of the Heart</em>, Chapter 2: &ldquo;The Transformation of the Human Spirit.&rdquo; Willard argues that transformation is not automatic but requires the intentional engagement of the human will, even though it is ultimately the Spirit&rsquo;s work. Read his account of how VIM (Vision, Intention, Means) applies to sanctification.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">2 Corinthians 3:18 makes transformation sound passive &mdash; we are <em>being</em> transformed. Willard insists we must cooperate actively. Wesley said &ldquo;God works, therefore work.&rdquo; Write your working theology of cooperation: what is your role and what is God&rsquo;s role in your own sanctification? Be specific about one area you are currently in.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Willard&rsquo;s VIM for your own sanctification: Vision (what does the transformed Trevor look like, specifically?), Intention (are you genuinely committed or merely interested?), Means (what specific practices are your means?). Write one paragraph per letter. Be concrete. No abstractions.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Week synthesis &mdash; declared and being made</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Philippians 1:6<br><em>&ldquo;He who began a good work in you will carry it on to completion until the day of Christ Jesus.&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times. This is the promise underneath all of sanctification. God does not start what he does not finish. What does this promise feel like to receive today?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your journal from this week. Then read Wesley&rsquo;s sermon &ldquo;The Scripture Way of Salvation.&rdquo; Wesley summarizes his whole soteriology in one sermon. Read it slowly &mdash; it is his most comprehensive single statement of justification and sanctification together.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write a one-page summary of the Wesleyan ordo salutis as you now understand it: prevenient grace, conviction, repentance, justification, new birth, initial sanctification, growth in grace, entire sanctification (coming in Unit 4). Write it in plain English &mdash; as if explaining it to someone who has never heard it.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: where are you right now in the <em>ordo salutis</em> you just described? Not where you think you should be &mdash; where you honestly sense you are. Write one paragraph.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 5</span>
        <span class="week-title">Sanctification &mdash; what God is making</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Growth in grace &mdash; the long middle</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Hebrews 12:1&ndash;3<br><em>&ldquo;Let us run with perseverance the race marked out for us, fixing our eyes on Jesus.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The race metaphor implies sustained effort across time, not a single sprint. What does perseverance in holiness look like when the emotional energy of conversion has faded?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Dallas Willard, <em>Renovation of the Heart</em>, Chapter 3: &ldquo;The Transformation of the Mind.&rdquo; Willard argues that the mind is the first and most important battleground of sanctification &mdash; not feelings, not behavior, but the deep habits of thought that generate both. Read his account of what it means to have the &ldquo;mind of Christ.&rdquo;</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Willard argues that what you think about habitually, especially without intending to, shapes who you are becoming. What are your unguarded thoughts &mdash; the ones that arise spontaneously when you are driving, exercising, falling asleep? What are they forming you into? Write honestly.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Willard&rsquo;s exercise: For one day this week (today), notice every time your mind runs toward anxious rehearsal, competitive comparison, or self-congratulation. Don&rsquo;t suppress these thoughts &mdash; name them and release them. At day&rsquo;s end, write what you observed.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The disciplines as training, not earning</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 1 Corinthians 9:24&ndash;27<br>Paul trains his body and beats it into submission &mdash; not for salvation but for effective service. Read it three times. The spiritual disciplines are not ways to earn grace but ways to make yourself available to grace. What does the training metaphor change about how you approach practices like fasting and prayer?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Dallas Willard, <em>The Spirit of the Disciplines</em>, Chapter 5: &ldquo;Disciplines for the Spirit.&rdquo; Willard distinguishes between disciplines of abstinence (fasting, solitude, silence, simplicity) and disciplines of engagement (Bible study, worship, service, confession). Read his account of how each type trains a different capacity.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">You have a regular fasting practice on Wednesdays. Willard would say this is training your body to not be controlled by appetite &mdash; which then extends to all appetites, not just food. Write an honest account of what your fasting practice is currently doing in you. Not what you think it should do &mdash; what you observe it actually doing.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Willard&rsquo;s rule: arrange your life to receive as much grace as possible. Map your week and identify two &lsquo;dead spots&rsquo; &mdash; times you are regularly in a posture that makes you less available to God. Write what one change would make those times more open. Commit to trying it this week.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Temptation and the sin that remains</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Galatians 5:16&ndash;25<br>The conflict between flesh and Spirit. <em>&ldquo;The flesh desires what is contrary to the Spirit, and the Spirit what is contrary to the flesh. They are in conflict with each other.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Paul lists the works of the flesh and the fruit of the Spirit. What patterns of the flesh do you most recognize in your own life right now?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Kenneth Collins, <em>The Theology of John Wesley</em>, Chapter 8: &ldquo;Sanctification and Sin.&rdquo; Collins traces Wesley&rsquo;s nuanced view: the justified Christian is freed from the dominion of sin but not from its presence. Wesley called remaining sin &ldquo;remains of the image of the beast.&rdquo; Read his account carefully.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wesley distinguished between willful transgression of known law (which breaks fellowship with God) and involuntary failures (which do not). He also argued that sanctification progressively reduces even involuntary sin as the heart is more fully cleansed. Where do you sense the Spirit making progress in your own life? Where do you sense you are stuck?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Galatians 5:22&ndash;23: the fruit of the Spirit. Read each word slowly &mdash; love, joy, peace, patience, kindness, goodness, faithfulness, gentleness, self-control. Rank them from most present to least present in your life right now. Don&rsquo;t ask &lsquo;which should I have&rsquo; &mdash; ask &lsquo;which do I notice?&rsquo; The gaps are the next frontier of formation.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Relationships as the crucible of sanctification</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Colossians 3:12&ndash;17<br><em>&ldquo;Bear with each other and forgive one another if any of you has a grievance against someone.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Paul locates sanctification not in individual achievement but in the texture of communal life. What would it mean to treat your relationships &mdash; with Dana, colleagues, your church &mdash; as the primary classroom of holiness?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Dietrich Bonhoeffer, <em>Life Together</em>, Chapter 1: &ldquo;Community.&rdquo; Bonhoeffer argues that Christian community is not the fulfillment of a dream of ideal fellowship but the schooling of love in the presence of real, difficult, particular people. Read his account of how disillusionment with community is necessary to genuine community.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Bonhoeffer says: &ldquo;He who loves his dream of a community more than the Christian community itself becomes a destroyer of the latter.&rdquo; Where in your life are you loving the idea of a relationship more than the actual person? Name the relationship. Write what the actual person needs from you that the dream-version doesn&rsquo;t require.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Practice: Choose one relationship this week and give it intentional sanctifying attention. Not fixing &mdash; attending. One act of genuine listening, one act of patience, one act of service that costs you something minor. Write what you chose and what it required.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Unit 3 synthesis &mdash; declared and being made</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 1 John 3:2<br><em>&ldquo;We know that when Christ appears, we shall be like him, for we shall see him as he is.&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times. The endpoint of sanctification: likeness to Christ. Not achievement &mdash; sight. We will be like him because we will finally see him clearly. What does this suggest about the relationship between vision and transformation?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read Wesley&rsquo;s sermon &ldquo;On the Wedding Garment&rdquo; &mdash; Wesley&rsquo;s account of what inward holiness actually looks like. Note his insistence that the outward forms of religion are worthless without the inward transformation they are meant to serve.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Unit 3 synthesis essay: &ldquo;Where I am in the process of sanctification.&rdquo; One honest page. Not aspirational &mdash; descriptive. Where have you grown? Where are you stuck? What specific things are forming you right now? What specific things are deforming you? What is the single most important next step in your sanctification that you can name?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: one discipline you will add or deepen this month as a specific means of sanctification. Name it, define the practice, and write what you expect it to train.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div><div class="unit-label" style="margin-top:2rem;">Unit 4 &middot; 2 Weeks</div><div class="unit-title">Entire Sanctification</div><div class="unit-desc">Wesley&rsquo;s most controversial and most distinctively Wesleyan claim: that the Holy Spirit can so purify the heart that love of God and neighbor becomes the habitual, dominant orientation of the will. Not sinless perfection &mdash; something more nuanced and more demanding than that.</div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 6</span>
        <span class="week-title">What entire sanctification is &mdash; and is not</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Perfect love &mdash; Wesley&rsquo;s definition</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Matthew 22:36&ndash;40<br><em>&ldquo;Love the Lord your God with all your heart and with all your soul and with all your mind&hellip; Love your neighbor as yourself.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Wesley said entire sanctification is the fulfillment of this command as the habitual orientation of the heart. Not a summit reached once &mdash; a direction sustained.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Kenneth Collins, <em>The Theology of John Wesley</em>, Chapter 10: &ldquo;Entire Sanctification.&rdquo; Collins gives the clearest scholarly account of what Wesley meant and didn&rsquo;t mean. Read carefully &mdash; especially his account of how entire sanctification differs from sinless perfection and how Wesley clarified his position across his ministry.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wesley said entire sanctification is &lsquo;the renewal of the heart in the full image of God.&rsquo; He was careful: it does not mean freedom from mistakes, ignorance, or infirmity &mdash; only from intentional sin and from the inward &lsquo;bent to sinning.&rsquo; What would it mean for love rather than self-interest to be the default orientation of your will? Write what would change.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray 1 Thessalonians 5:23&ndash;24 as a request: <em>&ldquo;May God himself, the God of peace, sanctify you through and through.&rdquo;</em> Notice: the agent is God. Sit in silence for 10 minutes and hold the prayer open without filling it. Entire sanctification begins in consent, not achievement.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">What perfect love looks like in practice</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 1 John 4:16&ndash;21<br><em>&ldquo;God is love. Whoever lives in love lives in God, and God in them.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The language is remarkable: not &lsquo;whoever obeys God&rsquo;s commands&rsquo; but &lsquo;whoever lives in love.&rsquo; What does it mean for love to be the element you <em>live in</em> rather than the thing you occasionally manage to do?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Wesley, Standard Sermon: &ldquo;On Perfection.&rdquo; Read the full sermon. Wesley clarifies what he means by &lsquo;Christian perfection&rsquo; &mdash; it is perfection of intention (love as the dominant motive) not perfection of performance (no mistakes). Note every clarification he makes about what perfection is <em>not.</em></p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wesley said he had met people he believed had experienced entire sanctification. Their characteristics: deep humility, freedom from anxiety, consistency of love even under pressure, absence of resentment. Write honestly: where are these present in you? Where are they most absent? The most absent places are the most formative frontier.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Practice of love under pressure: Think of someone who consistently irritates, drains, or provokes you. For 10 minutes, pray for them with genuine warmth &mdash; not petitioning for their change but genuinely loving them. Notice what this costs you. That cost is the gap between where you are and where entire sanctification would put you.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The crisis and the process &mdash; how sanctification comes</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Luke 11:9&ndash;13<br><em>&ldquo;If you then, though you are evil, know how to give good gifts to your children, how much more will your Father in heaven give the Holy Spirit to those who ask him!&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Wesley believed entire sanctification could be sought in prayer. Have you asked? Why or why not?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Randy Maddox, <em>Responsible Grace</em>, Chapter 9: &ldquo;Recovering Responsible Grace: Entire Sanctification.&rdquo; Maddox navigates the ongoing debate in Wesleyan theology about whether entire sanctification is primarily a crisis moment or a gradual process. Read his careful account of how Wesley held both.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wesley said entire sanctification typically comes through a combination of gradual growth and a definite moment of crisis surrender &mdash; like marriage, which involves both the gradual growth of love and the specific moment of commitment. Where are you in that dynamic? Are you growing gradually but avoiding the commitment? Or committed but neglecting the growth?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Write a prayer of consecration &mdash; not claiming entire sanctification, but opening yourself fully to whatever God wants to do. Wesley called this &lsquo;presenting yourself as a living sacrifice.&rsquo; Write it in your own words. Sign it. Date it.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The ongoing life of sanctification &mdash; humility afterward</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Galatians 6:1<br><em>&ldquo;Brothers and sisters, if someone is caught in a sin, you who live by the Spirit should restore that person gently. But watch yourselves, or you also may be tempted.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Even those who have been sanctified must watch themselves. What does the danger of spiritual pride say about the nature of entire sanctification?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Kenneth Collins, <em>The Theology of John Wesley</em>, Chapter 11: &ldquo;The Via Salutis and Its Completion.&rdquo; Collins traces how Wesley understood the life after entire sanctification &mdash; not stasis but continued growth, vulnerability to temptation through ignorance, and the need for ongoing means of grace.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">The Wesleyan tradition has sometimes produced spiritual pride in those who believed they had attained entire sanctification. Collins traces Wesley&rsquo;s antidote: the more sanctified you are, the more clearly you see your own unworthiness. Write: what would guard you specifically against spiritual pride in your own formation?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Wesley&rsquo;s band meeting questions (used in intimate accountability groups): (1) What known sins have you committed since last we met? (2) What temptations have you met with? (3) How were you delivered? (4) What have you thought, said, or done of which you are uncertain? Write your honest answers to each right now.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Unit 4 synthesis &mdash; the telos of formation</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Ephesians 4:13<br><em>&ldquo;Until we all reach unity in the faith and in the knowledge of the Son of God and become mature, attaining to the whole measure of the fullness of Christ.&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times. The telos: the fullness of Christ. Wesley called this entire sanctification. What does it mean to hold this as a real and expected destination, not an impossible ideal?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your journal from this unit. Then read A.W. Tozer&rsquo;s essay &ldquo;The Pursuit of God&rdquo; (Chapter 1). Tozer is not Wesleyan but his account of the hungry soul&rsquo;s pursuit of God captures the spirit of entire sanctification better than many Wesleyan accounts. Read it as a complement.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Course 1.2 synthesis essay: &ldquo;What Wesleyan theology has done to my understanding of salvation.&rdquo; Two full pages. Cover: prevenient grace, justification, new birth, sanctification, entire sanctification, and the ordo salutis as a whole. Write in your own voice, with specific examples from your own life. This is not an academic paper &mdash; it is a confession.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: write one paragraph about where you sense you are in the ordo salutis. Then write one paragraph about what you want. Then write one prayer of consecration &mdash; in your own words, your own voice, addressed to the God who is doing this.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div></div>
<div id="y1-c13" class="course-section" style="display:none;"><div class="course-divider">Course 1.3 &mdash; The Grammar of Prayer</div><div class="unit-label" style="margin-top:2rem;">Unit 1 &middot; 3 Weeks</div><div class="unit-title">Contemplative Prayer in the Christian Tradition</div><div class="unit-desc">Richard Foster and A.W. Tozer on the nature, practice, and deepening of prayer. Not technique &mdash; orientation. Prayer as the primary posture of the soul before God.</div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 1</span>
        <span class="week-title">What prayer is &mdash; and what keeps us from it</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Prayer as conversation, not performance</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Matthew 6:5&ndash;8<br>Jesus warns against prayer as public performance and as empty repetition. Read it three times. <em>&ldquo;Your Father knows what you need before you ask him.&rdquo;</em> If God already knows, why pray? What does this verse say about the purpose of prayer?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Richard Foster, <em>Prayer: Finding the Heart&rsquo;s True Home</em>, Introduction and Chapter 1: &ldquo;Simple Prayer.&rdquo; Foster argues that ordinary, unpolished, simple prayer is the foundation &mdash; before any more sophisticated form. Read his account of what simple prayer actually is and why it matters.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Foster says most people&rsquo;s problem with prayer is not lack of technique but lack of honesty. They pray what they think they should feel rather than what they actually feel. Write a completely honest prayer right now &mdash; whatever is actually in you today. Let it be as unpolished and direct as you can make it.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray for 10 minutes using only the word &lsquo;Father.&rsquo; Nothing else. Sit in that single word and let it expand. Notice what it surfaces &mdash; resistance, relief, longing, confusion. Journal one sentence about what happened in the space the single word opened.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The veil &mdash; what keeps us from God&rsquo;s presence</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Hebrews 10:19&ndash;22<br><em>&ldquo;We have confidence to enter the Most Holy Place by the blood of Jesus&hellip; let us draw near to God with a sincere heart and with the full assurance that faith brings.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Full access &mdash; already given. What keeps you from using it?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> A.W. Tozer, <em>The Pursuit of God</em>, Chapter 3: &ldquo;Removing the Veil.&rdquo; Tozer argues that a veil of self &mdash; ego, pretense, self-protection &mdash; stands between the believer and genuine communion with God. This veil must be torn, as the Temple veil was torn, by intentional surrender. Read carefully.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Tozer writes: <em>&lsquo;The heart of the world is breaking under this load of pride and pretense.&rsquo;</em> What is the specific veil between you and God? Not in general &mdash; in practice, in your actual prayer life. Is it distraction? Self-consciousness? Doubt? Unconfessed sin? The weight of hurry? Name it specifically.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Tozer&rsquo;s exercise: sit in complete silence for 15 minutes. Don&rsquo;t pray in words. Don&rsquo;t structure it. Simply present yourself before God without agenda. Notice the discomfort that arises &mdash; the urge to fill the silence, to do something, to produce. Write what you observed.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Lectio Divina &mdash; the practice at the heart of this curriculum</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Psalm 46:10<br><em>&ldquo;Be still, and know that I am God.&rdquo;</em> A single verse. Read it ten times, each time resting longer on a different word. Be still &mdash; and know &mdash; that I am &mdash; God. What does the word <em>still</em> require of you specifically?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Richard Foster, <em>Prayer: Finding the Heart&rsquo;s True Home</em>, Chapter 8: &ldquo;Meditative Prayer.&rdquo; Foster describes Lectio Divina as a form of prayer &mdash; not study. The four movements: Lectio (reading), Meditatio (rumination), Oratio (response), Contemplatio (resting). Read his account of each movement.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">You have been practicing Lectio Divina throughout this curriculum. Write an honest assessment: What is working in your practice? What tends to derail it? What have you learned about the way God speaks to you through Scripture in this way? Be specific &mdash; use examples from sessions you remember.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Practice Psalm 46 using full four-movement Lectio today &mdash; but take more time than usual on Contemplatio. After Oratio (your response in prayer), simply rest. No more words. 10 minutes of silence. Write afterward: what was the quality of the silence? Was it empty, full, restless, peaceful?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Intercession &mdash; praying for others as a spiritual discipline</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 1 Timothy 2:1&ndash;4<br><em>&ldquo;I urge, then, first of all, that petitions, prayers, intercession, and thanksgiving be made for all people.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Paul places intercession first. What does it mean to make intercession a primary practice &mdash; not an afterthought at the end of personal petition?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Richard Foster, <em>Prayer: Finding the Heart&rsquo;s True Home</em>, Chapter 13: &ldquo;Intercessory Prayer.&rdquo; Foster argues that genuine intercession transforms the one who prays as much as it serves the one prayed for &mdash; because it requires us to see people as God sees them rather than as we want them to be.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Foster distinguishes between praying <em>at</em> people (trying to change them through your prayer) and praying <em>for</em> them (holding them before God and releasing them to him). Which mode characterizes your intercession most? Write about one person you have been praying <em>at</em> and what it would mean to pray <em>for</em> them instead.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Intercessory practice: Sit for 15 minutes and pray for five people by name &mdash; one per minute of silence, one per minute of petition, one per minute of thanksgiving, one per minute of blessing, one in complete surrender. Write afterward: which mode of prayer felt most natural? Which felt most foreign?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Week synthesis &mdash; the posture beneath the practice</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Luke 18:1<br><em>&ldquo;Then Jesus told his disciples a parable to show them that they should always pray and not give up.&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times. <em>Always pray and not give up.</em> What does Jesus assume about the nature of prayer &mdash; that it is sometimes unrewarding, that God sometimes seems slow, that persistence is required? What word arrests you?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your prayer journal from this week. Then read Foster&rsquo;s Chapter 3: &ldquo;The Prayer of Examen.&rdquo; Foster&rsquo;s account of the Examen as a form of prayer &mdash; not just self-examination but the practice of noticing God&rsquo;s presence through the day &mdash; will shape how you close this week.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write your theology of prayer as it stands today &mdash; not what you were taught, what you actually believe and practice. What is prayer for? What makes it effective? What makes it ineffective? What do you most need to grow in? One honest page.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: one specific change you will make to your prayer practice this week &mdash; not a resolution, a specific experiment. Name it. Write it. Begin tomorrow.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 2</span>
        <span class="week-title">The modes of prayer &mdash; learning the full vocabulary</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Confession &mdash; the prayer that clears the air</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Psalm 51:1&ndash;12<br>David&rsquo;s great confession after the Bathsheba affair. <em>&ldquo;Create in me a pure heart, O God, and renew a steadfast spirit within me.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Note what David asks for: not just forgiveness of the act but renovation of the heart. What word or phrase arrests you today?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Richard Foster, <em>Prayer: Finding the Heart&rsquo;s True Home</em>, Chapter 4: &ldquo;Prayer of Examen&rdquo; and Chapter 5: &ldquo;Tears and Laughter.&rdquo; Foster argues that genuine confession requires the kind of grief over sin that produces change, not merely the relief of discharge. Read his account of what authentic confession looks and feels like.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">There is a kind of confession that is really just downloading &mdash; naming sins to feel better without genuine sorrow or intention to change. Foster calls this &lsquo;cheap confession.&rsquo; Write the difference between cheap confession and costly confession. Then write an honest confession &mdash; not general, specific &mdash; that costs you something to name.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray Psalm 51:10 as a request: <em>&ldquo;Create in me a pure heart, O God.&rdquo;</em> Sit with the word <em>create</em> &mdash; this is a creative act, <em>bara</em>, the same word used for creation from nothing. What do you need God to create in you that cannot be produced by your own effort? Sit in silence for 10 minutes after asking.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Thanksgiving &mdash; the prayer that reorients</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Philippians 4:4&ndash;7<br><em>&ldquo;Do not be anxious about anything, but in every situation, by prayer and petition, with thanksgiving, present your requests to God.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Thanksgiving comes before petition here. What does it mean to enter petition through gratitude rather than anxiety?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Richard Foster, <em>Prayer: Finding the Heart&rsquo;s True Home</em>, Chapter 6: &ldquo;The Prayer of Adoration&rdquo; and Chapter 7: &ldquo;Petitionary Prayer.&rdquo; Foster traces the movement from adoration through thanksgiving to petition &mdash; arguing that petition that skips adoration tends to reduce God to a vending machine. Read his account of the proper sequence.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">G.K. Chesterton called gratitude the mother of all virtues &mdash; the first movement of the soul that recognizes it has received rather than achieved. What in your life right now do you most take for granted? Write a list of ten things. Then write: why is each one a gift rather than an entitlement?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Thanksgiving practice: For 15 minutes, pray only in thanksgiving &mdash; no requests, no confession, no intercession. Just gratitude. When you run out of words, sit in silence. Notice what happens when thanksgiving exhausts your obvious list and you must go deeper. Write one sentence about what you found at the bottom.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Silence &mdash; the prayer beyond words</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Habakkuk 2:20<br><em>&ldquo;The Lord is in his holy temple; let all the earth be silent before him.&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times. Silence is not the absence of prayer &mdash; it is its fullest form. What keeps you from silence? What does silence threaten?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> A.W. Tozer, <em>The Pursuit of God</em>, Chapter 8: &ldquo;Restoring the Creator-Creature Relation.&rdquo; Tozer argues that the fundamental posture of the creature before the Creator is receptivity, not activity &mdash; and that most contemporary Christianity has reversed this. Read his account of what it means to be &lsquo;acquainted with God.&rsquo;</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Tozer writes that God is always speaking but we are rarely listening &mdash; not because God is quiet but because we are loud. What are the specific noises that fill your life and compete with the silence in which God is most audible? List them. Then write: which one would be hardest to reduce and why?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Silence practice: 15 minutes of complete silence &mdash; no music, no phone, no movement. Simply sit before God in the posture of a creature before its Creator. Breathe slowly. Don&rsquo;t ask for anything. Don&rsquo;t confess anything. Be present. Write one word afterward that captures what it was like.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Contemplative prayer &mdash; what your quieter access to God is</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Psalm 131:1&ndash;3<br><em>&ldquo;My heart is not lifted up, my eyes are not raised too high&hellip; I have calmed and quieted myself, I am like a weaned child with its mother.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The weaned child is not nursing &mdash; it is simply resting in its mother&rsquo;s presence. What does this image say about contemplative prayer?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Richard Foster, <em>Prayer: Finding the Heart&rsquo;s True Home</em>, Chapter 22: &ldquo;Contemplative Prayer.&rdquo; Foster traces the long Christian tradition of contemplative prayer &mdash; from the Desert Fathers through John of the Cross to Thomas Merton &mdash; and argues it is not an elite mystical achievement but the normal telos of the prayer life. Read carefully.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">You have described your access to God as quieter and more interior than what you encountered in Atlanta. Foster would call this a contemplative disposition. Write: what does this mode of prayer do in you that more expressive forms don&rsquo;t? What do you risk losing if you only pray this way? What is its genuine strength?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Extended contemplative prayer: 15 minutes. Begin with a brief Lectio Divina on Psalm 131. Then release all words and simply rest in God&rsquo;s presence. If thoughts come, gently return. Don&rsquo;t evaluate the quality of the silence afterward &mdash; the soul cannot assess itself while resting. Journal one sentence.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Week synthesis &mdash; the full vocabulary of prayer</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Colossians 4:2<br><em>&ldquo;Devote yourselves to prayer, being watchful and thankful.&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times. Devotion, watchfulness, thanksgiving &mdash; three words. What does <em>devote</em> mean in the context of everything you have practiced this week?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your prayer journal from the past two weeks. Identify the one mode of prayer &mdash; confession, thanksgiving, intercession, silence, contemplation &mdash; that you have most avoided or found most difficult. Re-read Foster&rsquo;s chapter on that mode.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write a map of your current prayer life: how much time, what modes, what is present, what is missing, what you would like to develop. Not a plan for improvement &mdash; an honest account of where you are. Then write one paragraph: what does your prayer life say about your actual relationship with God right now?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: one new mode of prayer you will deliberately practice this week. Write what it is, when you will do it, and what you expect to be uncomfortable about it.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 3</span>
        <span class="week-title">Obstacles, darkness, and the long arc of prayer</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">When prayer feels like nothing &mdash; the dark night</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Psalm 22:1&ndash;5<br><em>&ldquo;My God, my God, why have you forsaken me? Why are you so far from saving me?&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Jesus prayed this from the cross. The psalmist prayed it before him. What does the existence of this prayer in Scripture authorize in your own prayer life?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Richard Foster, <em>Prayer: Finding the Heart&rsquo;s True Home</em>, Chapter 17: &ldquo;The Prayer of the Forsaken.&rdquo; Foster traces the tradition of the <em>noche oscura</em> &mdash; the dark night of the soul described by John of the Cross &mdash; and argues it is not a sign of God&rsquo;s absence but of his closest work. Read his account carefully.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Foster argues that the dark night is not depression, doubt, or punishment &mdash; it is a specific work of God that strips away our images of God until we encounter God himself. Have you experienced anything like this? Write honestly. If not, what do you imagine it would feel like? What would it take from you?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray Psalm 22:1 as it is &mdash; as a lament, not a theological statement. Let it be a cry rather than a recitation. Then read verse 24: <em>&ldquo;For he has not despised or scorned the suffering of the afflicted one; he has not hidden his face from him but has listened to his cry for help.&rdquo;</em> Sit with both verses together. Write one sentence.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Distractions &mdash; the wandering mind and what it teaches</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Luke 10:38&ndash;42<br>Martha and Mary. Martha is distracted by much serving. Jesus says Mary has chosen the better part. Read it three times. Note: Jesus does not say Martha&rsquo;s work is wrong &mdash; only that it has displaced the better thing. What is displacing the better thing in your own prayer life right now?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> A.W. Tozer, <em>The Pursuit of God</em>, Chapter 4: &ldquo;Apprehending God.&rdquo; Tozer argues that we apprehend God through spiritual attention &mdash; a deliberate, sustained turning of the whole being toward God. Read his account of what distraction does to this capacity and how it can be trained.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Tozer says the ability to attend to God spiritually is like a muscle &mdash; it atrophies without use and strengthens with exercise. Write an honest account of your attention capacity in prayer right now. When does your mind wander? What does it wander toward? What does the pattern of your distraction reveal about where your desire actually lives?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Distraction practice: Set a timer for 10 minutes of silent prayer. Every time your mind wanders, gently note what it wandered toward and return. Don&rsquo;t be harsh about the wandering &mdash; the returning is the practice. Afterward, write a list of every category your mind visited. What does the list reveal?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Petitionary prayer &mdash; what it means to ask</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Matthew 7:7&ndash;11<br><em>&ldquo;Ask and it will be given to you; seek and you will find; knock and the door will be opened to you.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Jesus commands asking. Not suggesting it, not permitting it &mdash; commanding it. What makes you reluctant to ask God for things? What does reluctance reveal?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Richard Foster, <em>Prayer: Finding the Heart&rsquo;s True Home</em>, Chapter 7: &ldquo;Petitionary Prayer.&rdquo; Foster addresses the theology behind petition &mdash; why it is not manipulation of God, not presumption on his goodness, but an act of dependence that honors the relationship. Read his account of how genuine petition differs from vending-machine prayer.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write ten things you genuinely want to ask God for right now &mdash; not what you think you should ask for, what you actually want. Read them back. Which ones are you embarrassed by? Which feel too small? Which feel too large? Foster argues all of these are appropriate &mdash; the embarrassment is the veil again. Write about what the list reveals.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Bring your list of ten requests to God in 15 minutes of prayer. Ask for each one specifically. Then sit in silence and hold them before God without pressing. The posture of petition that trusts is open-handed &mdash; I want this, and I release it. Write one sentence about what it felt like to ask.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Gratitude as a way of seeing &mdash; the prayer beneath all prayer</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 1 Thessalonians 5:16&ndash;18<br><em>&ldquo;Rejoice always, pray continually, give thanks in all circumstances; for this is God&rsquo;s will for you in Christ Jesus.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Not <em>for</em> all circumstances &mdash; <em>in</em> all circumstances. What is the difference? What enables thanksgiving in circumstances you cannot be thankful for?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Eugene Peterson, <em>Answering God: The Psalms as Tools for Prayer</em>, Chapter 1: &ldquo;Prayer: Answering Speech.&rdquo; Peterson argues that prayer is first of all response &mdash; God speaks and we answer. Gratitude is the form of speech that most honestly names the situation: we have received, we did not create. Read his opening argument.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Peterson&rsquo;s claim: we do not begin prayer, we respond to it. God is always speaking &mdash; in Scripture, in creation, in circumstance, in the Spirit&rsquo;s prompting. Prayer is our answer. Write what you are answering right now. What is God saying to you in this season that you have been responding to &mdash; whether in prayer or in avoidance?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Practice: For 15 minutes, pray only in response to what you see, hear, and sense around you. Let each thing you notice become a prompt: a bird, a sound, the light in the room, a thought, a sensation. Let it all become prayer. Don&rsquo;t structure it. Just respond. Write two sentences afterward about what this felt like.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Unit 1 synthesis &mdash; prayer as your primary posture</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Psalm 27:4<br><em>&ldquo;One thing I ask from the Lord, this only do I seek: that I may dwell in the house of the Lord all the days of my life, to gaze on the beauty of the Lord and to seek him in his temple.&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times. One thing. What is your one thing right now?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your prayer journal from the past three weeks. Identify the three most significant moments in your prayer life during this unit &mdash; moments when something shifted, when God seemed near, when you hit resistance, when silence was full. Write one sentence per moment.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Unit 1 synthesis essay: &ldquo;My prayer life as it stands.&rdquo; One honest page. Not aspirational &mdash; descriptive. What modes of prayer are most natural to you? What are you avoiding? What has this unit opened? What has it shown you about the gap between your intended prayer life and your actual one?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: one specific commitment about prayer you are making from this unit. Not a vague resolution &mdash; a specific practice, at a specific time, for a specific duration. Write it. Begin tomorrow.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div><div class="unit-label" style="margin-top:2rem;">Unit 2 &middot; 2 Weeks</div><div class="unit-title">The Psalms as a School of Prayer</div><div class="unit-desc">Walter Brueggemann on orientation, disorientation, and reorientation. The Psalms not as religious poetry but as the training ground for a prayer life that can hold both joy and desolation without collapsing.</div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 4</span>
        <span class="week-title">Brueggemann&rsquo;s three movements &mdash; learning the full range</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Psalms of orientation &mdash; when life is ordered and God is near</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Psalm 23<br>The shepherd psalm. Read it three times &mdash; slowly, not as a familiar text but as a fresh one. What does it mean to <em>lack nothing</em>? What does it mean to fear no evil? When have you most felt the reality described here? What word arrests you today?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Walter Brueggemann, <em>The Message of the Psalms</em>, Introduction and Chapter 1: &ldquo;Psalms of Orientation.&rdquo; Brueggemann introduces his threefold framework: psalms of orientation (life is ordered, God is good), disorientation (life has collapsed, God seems absent), and new orientation (something unexpected has emerged from the darkness). Read his introduction carefully.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Brueggemann argues psalms of orientation are theologically important but spiritually dangerous if they are the only psalms you pray &mdash; because they can become a comfortable denial of reality. Where in your life right now do you have genuine orientation &mdash; things that are ordered, good, and full of God&rsquo;s presence? Write specifically. Don&rsquo;t understate it.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray Psalm 23 with full Lectio Divina. On the third reading, stay with the phrase that arrests you for 10 minutes in silence. Then write: what does this phrase say about where you are in your life with God right now?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Psalms of disorientation &mdash; when the floor falls out</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Psalm 88<br>The darkest psalm &mdash; the one with no resolution. Read it three times. Note the ending: <em>&ldquo;darkness is my closest friend.&rdquo;</em> There is no turn, no &lsquo;but God.&rsquo; What does the existence of this psalm in the canon say about what God permits us to bring to him?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Walter Brueggemann, <em>The Message of the Psalms</em>, Chapter 2: &ldquo;Psalms of Disorientation.&rdquo; Brueggemann argues these psalms are spiritually essential &mdash; they give permission to name reality honestly before God. A faith that cannot hold darkness will collapse in darkness. Read his account of what these psalms authorize.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Psalm 88 ends in darkness. No doxology, no resolution, no &lsquo;yet I will trust.&rsquo; Just darkness. Brueggemann argues this is spiritually more honest than false resolution. What unresolved grief or darkness do you carry that you have not yet named in prayer? Write it. You don&rsquo;t have to resolve it &mdash; just name it before God as honestly as the psalmist named his.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray Psalm 88 aloud &mdash; as your own prayer, not as recitation. Let the darkness it names be real. Sit in silence after for 10 minutes. Write one sentence: what is it like to pray a psalm that ends without comfort?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Psalms of new orientation &mdash; what emerges from the darkness</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Psalm 30<br><em>&ldquo;Weeping may stay for the night, but rejoicing comes in the morning.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Psalm 30 is a psalm of new orientation &mdash; the testimony of one who came through disorientation and found something new on the other side. What does the note of testimony (past tense rescue) do to the present moment?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Walter Brueggemann, <em>The Message of the Psalms</em>, Chapter 3: &ldquo;Psalms of New Orientation.&rdquo; Brueggemann traces how new orientation is not a return to the old stability &mdash; it is the emergence of something unexpected that could only have come through the darkness. Read his account of what resurrection looks like in the Psalms.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">New orientation is not the same as the old orientation restored. Something new has emerged. Think of a season of disorientation in your life that eventually produced new orientation. What was new about the arrival? What did you discover on the far side of darkness that you could not have found on the near side? Write specifically.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray Psalm 30 as testimony &mdash; but substitute your own disorientation and new orientation into the structure. Let it be your own words in the psalm&rsquo;s shape. Write afterward: what does your own experience of new orientation teach you about the nature of God?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Writing your own psalm &mdash; the lament</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Lamentations 3:19&ndash;26<br>The pivot of Lamentations: <em>&ldquo;I remember my affliction and my wandering, the bitterness and the gall&hellip; Yet this I call to mind and therefore I have hope: because of the Lord&rsquo;s great love we are not consumed.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Both &mdash; the bitterness and the hope &mdash; held at once.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Eugene Peterson, <em>Answering God: The Psalms as Tools for Prayer</em>, Chapter 5: &ldquo;Lament.&rdquo; Peterson argues that lament is a form of faith &mdash; you only lament to someone you believe is listening. Lament that addresses God is already an act of trust. Read his account of what lament accomplishes that polite prayer cannot.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write your own psalm &mdash; modeled on Psalm 88 (lament without resolution). Use Brueggemann&rsquo;s structure: name the disorientation honestly, address God directly, do not resolve it prematurely. Let it end wherever it actually ends. This is one of the most challenging and formative exercises in the entire curriculum.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Read your psalm aloud. Then sit in silence for 10 minutes. Don&rsquo;t evaluate it, don&rsquo;t fix it. Let it stand as your honest prayer. Write one sentence: what did writing it do that reading someone else&rsquo;s psalm cannot?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Week synthesis &mdash; the full range of the prayer life</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Psalm 73:1&ndash;28<br>A psalm of disorientation becoming new orientation. The psalmist nearly loses his faith watching the wicked prosper &mdash; until he enters the sanctuary. Read it three times. What happens in the sanctuary that doesn&rsquo;t happen outside it? What does the psalmist see there that changes everything?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your journal from this week. Then re-read Brueggemann&rsquo;s summary framework. Write: assign each of the six psalms you have worked with this unit (23, 88, 30, Lamentations 3, 73, and your own psalm) to Brueggemann&rsquo;s three categories. What does the distribution reveal about where most of your prayer life lives?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Where in Brueggemann&rsquo;s three categories does your prayer life most naturally live? Where do you spend the most time? Where do you avoid going? Write an honest account: if your prayer life is mostly in orientation psalms, what darkness are you not taking to God? If mostly in disorientation, what new orientation might you be refusing?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: assign the current season of your life to one of Brueggemann&rsquo;s three categories. Write a paragraph about why. Then write one psalm &mdash; just five to seven lines &mdash; in that register.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 5</span>
        <span class="week-title">The Psalms in practice &mdash; praying through them</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Psalm 46 &mdash; the fortress in chaos</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Psalm 46<br><em>&ldquo;God is our refuge and strength, an ever-present help in trouble. Therefore we will not fear, though the earth give way.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Note the <em>therefore</em>: because of who God is, not because the chaos has stopped. What word arrests you?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Dietrich Bonhoeffer, <em>Life Together</em>, Chapter 2: &ldquo;The Day with Others.&rdquo; Bonhoeffer on praying the Psalms together &mdash; why the Psalms are not self-expression but Christ&rsquo;s prayer through us. Read his account of what it means to pray a psalm as a community rather than as an individual.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Luther called Psalm 46 his psalm &mdash; it inspired &lsquo;A Mighty Fortress.&rsquo; What is the psalm that is most yours? Not the one you think should be, but the one that has most reliably been a home for you in prayer. Write about it: what has it done in you over time?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray Psalm 46 by singing it &mdash; use Luther&rsquo;s hymn &lsquo;A Mighty Fortress is Our God&rsquo; if you know it, or read it in rhythm if you don&rsquo;t. Let the body participate in the prayer through voice. Write one sentence about what singing a prayer does that reading it doesn&rsquo;t.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Psalms 22 and 130 &mdash; the depth and the waiting</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Psalm 130<br><em>&ldquo;Out of the depths I cry to you, Lord; Lord, hear my voice.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The psalmist waits &mdash; more than sentinels wait for morning. What is the quality of waiting this psalm describes? What is the difference between this waiting and despair?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Walter Brueggemann, <em>The Message of the Psalms</em>, section on Psalms 22 and 130. Brueggemann reads both as psalms of deep disorientation that nonetheless maintain address to God &mdash; which is itself the beginning of new orientation. Read his commentary on each.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Psalm 130:5&ndash;6: waiting with hope. Write about a situation in your life where you are waiting. Not anxious waiting &mdash; sentinel waiting. What does it mean to wait with your face toward the dawn rather than toward the darkness? Is your current waiting more like sentinels or more like someone who has given up on morning?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray Psalm 130 as a waiting prayer &mdash; read it, then sit in silence for 10 minutes in the posture of a sentinel. Face metaphorically toward the dawn. Don&rsquo;t pray for the waiting to end. Pray in the waiting. Write one sentence afterward.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Psalm 139 &mdash; the searched and known life</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Psalm 139:1&ndash;18<br>You have prayed this psalm earlier in the curriculum. Return to it now, after weeks of formation. Read it three times. What do you hear differently now than when you first read it? What has the preceding weeks done to your relationship with being fully known?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Eugene Peterson, <em>Answering God: The Psalms as Tools for Prayer</em>, Chapter 8: &ldquo;The Psalms as Prayer.&rdquo; Peterson&rsquo;s synthesis: the Psalms train us to pray by giving us the full vocabulary of the human-God encounter. Read his final account of why the Psalms are irreplaceable for the prayer life.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Psalm 139:23&ndash;24 is a prayer of invitation: search me, test me, know me, lead me. It is one of the most vulnerable prayers in Scripture. Write what it costs to pray it honestly &mdash; not as a performance of piety, but as a genuine invitation. What are you afraid God will find? What are you hoping he will see?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray Psalm 139:23&ndash;24 as your closing prayer for Unit 2. Sit in silence afterward for 15 minutes. Let the silence be God searching. Don&rsquo;t fill it. Write one sentence afterward: what did God find?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Course 1.3 synthesis &mdash; the prayer life you are building</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Romans 8:26&ndash;27<br><em>&ldquo;The Spirit helps us in our weakness. We do not know what we ought to pray for, but the Spirit himself intercedes for us through wordless groans.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The Spirit prays in you when you don&rsquo;t know how. What does this mean for the sessions of prayer where you feel you have nothing to bring?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your prayer journal from all five weeks of Course 1.3. Identify the week where prayer was most alive. Identify the week where it was most difficult. Re-read the specific passages from each week. What was happening in each?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Course 1.3 synthesis essay: &ldquo;My prayer life, honestly described and honestly desired.&rdquo; Two full pages. Cover: what modes of prayer are most natural to you, what modes you are avoiding, what the Psalms have opened, what obstacles you face, and what the next season of your prayer life needs. Write in your own voice. Don&rsquo;t be vague.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray for 30 minutes &mdash; the longest sustained prayer session of this course. Move through the modes you have practiced: simple prayer, confession, thanksgiving, intercession, petition, silence, contemplation. Let the session be organic &mdash; move between modes as the Spirit leads. Afterward, write one sentence about what you found in the length.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Unit 2 and Course 1.3 final synthesis</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Psalm 1:1&ndash;3<br><em>&ldquo;Blessed is the one&hellip; whose delight is in the law of the Lord, and who meditates on his law day and night.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The Psalter begins with this image: the one whose whole life is shaped by meditation. What would it mean for your whole life to be shaped by the prayer practices you have built in this course?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Final re-read: Tozer, <em>The Pursuit of God</em>, Chapter 10: &ldquo;The Sacrament of Living.&rdquo; Tozer&rsquo;s argument that all of life can become prayer &mdash; that the sacred/secular divide is the enemy of the contemplative life. Read it as the conclusion of everything this course has built.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write one final page: &ldquo;The prayer life I am taking forward.&rdquo; Not aspirational &mdash; committed. Name the specific practices, the specific times, the specific modes. Name the obstacles you know you face. Name the support structures you need. Sign it. Date it.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Course Examen: re-read all five weeks of Weekly Examens from Course 1.3. What pattern do you see? Where has the Spirit been most consistently pressing? What has the course done that you did not expect? Write a paragraph. Then sit in 15 minutes of silence as your final act of Course 1.3.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div></div>
<div id="y1-c14" class="course-section" style="display:none;"><div class="course-divider">Course 1.4 &mdash; Early Church and the Rule of Faith</div><div class="unit-label" style="margin-top:2rem;">Unit 1 &middot; 2 Weeks</div><div class="unit-title">The Apostolic Fathers and the Shape of Early Christianity</div><div class="unit-desc">What did Christianity look like in 100 AD? The Didache, Ignatius of Antioch, and Justo González on the early community that was both fragile and fierce.</div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 1</span>
        <span class="week-title">The first Christians &mdash; what they held and how they lived</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The Didache &mdash; the earliest church manual</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Acts 2:42&ndash;47<br>The early Jerusalem community: teaching, fellowship, breaking bread, prayer. Read it three times. This passage is the ideal; the Didache is the attempt to translate it into practice. What does an ideal look like when it becomes a manual? What word arrests you?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> <em>The Didache</em> (free, public domain) &mdash; read chapters 1&ndash;6: the Two Ways (life and death). The Didache is perhaps the earliest Christian document outside the New Testament. Read it slowly. Note what it assumes its readers already believe and what it is trying to shape.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">The Didache opens with a binary: the way of life and the way of death. It is brutally practical &mdash; no metaphysics, just behavior. What does this reveal about what the earliest Christian teachers thought was most endangered in new believers? What do you think is most endangered in your own formation right now?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>The Didache&rsquo;s way of life begins: &lsquo;Love God who made you; second, love your neighbor as yourself; and do not do to another what you do not want done to you.&rsquo; Write a modern version of the Two Ways for your own life &mdash; the specific behaviors that, practiced, lead toward life, and the specific ones that lead toward death. Be concrete.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Ignatius of Antioch &mdash; facing death with theology intact</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Philippians 1:21&ndash;23<br><em>&ldquo;For to me, to live is Christ and to die is gain.&rdquo;</em> Ignatius wrote his letters on his way to be martyred in Rome. Read it three times. What does it mean to hold life and death with equal peace? What enables that posture?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Ignatius of Antioch, <em>Letter to the Romans</em> (free, public domain) &mdash; read the full letter. Ignatius begs the Roman Christians not to intervene to save him. His language is startling: he wants to be ground by the teeth of wild beasts into pure bread for God. Read it as theology, not martyrology.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Ignatius writes: <em>&lsquo;I am God&rsquo;s wheat, and I am being ground by the teeth of wild beasts so that I may be found to be pure bread.&rsquo;</em> He understands his death as a form of the grain of wheat falling into the ground (John 12:24). What is the theology of formation in this image? What is being ground in you right now?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray Philippians 1:21 as your own confession: <em>&ldquo;For me, to live is Christ and to die is gain.&rdquo;</em> Sit with each half of the sentence. Can you pray the first half honestly? Can you pray the second half honestly? Write your honest answer about where you are with each.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The early church&rsquo;s rule of faith &mdash; what held them together</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 1 Corinthians 15:3&ndash;8<br>Paul&rsquo;s earliest summary of the gospel: Christ died, was buried, was raised, appeared. Read it three times. This is not a creed yet &mdash; it is the oral tradition that preceded creeds. What does its simplicity say about what the gospel is at its core?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Justo González, <em>The Story of Christianity, Vol. 1</em>, Chapters 1&ndash;3: The early community, its opposition, and its first theological crises. González is a superb narrator &mdash; read him for the historical texture of what it was like to be a Christian in the Roman Empire.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">González traces how the early church developed a &lsquo;rule of faith&rsquo; &mdash; a shared summary of Christian belief used to settle disputes about which texts and teachings were authoritative. What does the existence of this rule reveal about the pressures the early church faced? What pressures shape what you think is essential today?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Write your own rule of faith &mdash; the irreducible minimum of Christian belief, stated as clearly and simply as you can. Not a creed to quote &mdash; your own words. What, if you lost it, would mean you had lost Christianity itself? Limit it to 150 words.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Persecution and its theology &mdash; what suffering reveals</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 1 Peter 4:12&ndash;16<br><em>&ldquo;Do not be surprised at the fiery ordeal that has come on you to test you, as though something strange were happening to you.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Peter addresses a community under pressure. Suffering is not strange &mdash; it is the expected shape of the Christian life in a hostile world. What word arrests you?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Justo González, <em>The Story of Christianity, Vol. 1</em>, Chapters 4&ndash;5: Persecution and its effects on early Christianity. González traces how persecution shaped the early church&rsquo;s theology, liturgy, and community life. Read his account of what pressure does to a community of faith.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">González traces how persecution clarified the essential from the peripheral &mdash; you only die for what you actually believe. What would you be willing to lose for your faith, in the world you actually inhabit? Not dramatic martyrdom &mdash; what reputation, what comfort, what relationship? Write honestly.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray for persecuted Christians around the world. Not abstractly &mdash; find the name of a specific country, a specific community currently facing pressure. Pray for them for 10 minutes. Then write: what does praying for them do to the complaints you were carrying about your own life before you prayed?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Week synthesis &mdash; the early church as a mirror</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Revelation 2:2&ndash;4<br>Jesus&rsquo;s letter to the Ephesian church: <em>&ldquo;I know your deeds, your hard work and your perseverance&hellip; Yet I hold this against you: you have forsaken the love you had at first.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Right belief and hard work, without first love. What is &lsquo;first love&rsquo; and how does it leave?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your notes from this week. Then read the Didache chapters 9&ndash;10 on the Eucharist. The earliest eucharistic prayer in Christian literature. Read it slowly &mdash; note what it gives thanks for, what it asks, how it ends.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write a one-page reflection: &ldquo;What the early church shows me about my own faith.&rdquo; What did they have that contemporary Christianity has lost? What do you have that they lacked? What would it mean to recover their simplicity and their ferocity without losing the depth you have also inherited?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: write the rule of faith you drafted on Thursday, but now in the form of a prayer &mdash; addressed to the God who is named in each clause.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 2</span>
        <span class="week-title">The Great Tradition &mdash; 100&ndash;400 AD</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Gnosticism &mdash; the first great heresy and what it reveals</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 1 John 4:2&ndash;3<br><em>&ldquo;Every spirit that acknowledges that Jesus Christ has come in the flesh is from God, but every spirit that does not acknowledge Jesus is not from God.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. John&rsquo;s test is incarnational. Why does it matter so specifically that Jesus came <em>in the flesh</em>?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Justo González, <em>The Story of Christianity, Vol. 1</em>, Chapter 6: &ldquo;Second Century Christianity.&rdquo; González traces the Gnostic challenge &mdash; the claim that matter is evil, that the God of the Old Testament is a lesser deity, that salvation is escape from the body. Read his account of how the church responded.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Gnosticism is not dead. Its core conviction &mdash; that spiritual = good, material = bad &mdash; lives in large swaths of contemporary Christianity. Where do you recognize it in yourself? The belief that God is primarily concerned with your inner spiritual life and not with your body, your work, your physical community? Write specifically.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Incarnation practice: For 15 minutes, treat your body as holy rather than as an obstacle. This is theological, not mystical. Eat something with gratitude. Stretch deliberately. Notice physical sensation without trying to escape it into thought. Write: what does it mean for the Christian body to be a temple of the Holy Spirit in your specific body today?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Irenaeus &mdash; recapitulation and the goodness of creation</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Colossians 1:19&ndash;20<br><em>&ldquo;For God was pleased to have all his fullness dwell in him, and through him to reconcile to himself all things, whether things on earth or things in heaven.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. All things &mdash; not just souls. What does the reconciliation of all things mean?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Justo González, <em>The Story of Christianity, Vol. 1</em>, Chapter 7: &ldquo;Irenaeus of Lyons.&rdquo; Irenaeus developed the concept of <em>recapitulation</em> &mdash; Christ summing up all of human history and creation in himself, going back to the beginning and restoring what was lost. Read González&rsquo;s account carefully.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Irenaeus argued against the Gnostics that creation is not a mistake to be escaped but a project to be completed. Jesus came not to rescue souls from matter but to complete what was begun in Genesis. Write: how does this theology change how you think about your work building Greenline, about the land around you, about the physical world you inhabit?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Irenaeus&rsquo;s great line: <em>&lsquo;The glory of God is a human being fully alive.&rsquo;</em> Write what fully alive means for you &mdash; not in the motivational poster sense, but theologically: what does it mean for a human being to be fully what God intended? Write your answer and one practice that moves you toward it.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Tertullian and Origen &mdash; two ways of engaging culture</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Romans 12:2<br><em>&ldquo;Do not conform to the pattern of this world, but be transformed by the renewing of your mind.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Tertullian asked &lsquo;What has Athens to do with Jerusalem?&rsquo; Origen used Athens to explain Jerusalem. Both were answering this verse. What is your answer?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Justo González, <em>The Story of Christianity, Vol. 1</em>, Chapters 9&ndash;10: Tertullian and Origen. González traces these two towering figures whose opposite approaches to Greek philosophy set the terms of Christian cultural engagement ever since. Read both accounts and note the genuine tensions.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Tertullian&rsquo;s question remains unanswered: how much can you use the tools of secular culture to do theology without those tools distorting the content? Where do you find yourself using secular frameworks (psychological, economic, sociological) to understand your faith? Where is that legitimate? Where might it be distorting?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray for wisdom about how you engage secular culture &mdash; in your sales work, in building Greenline, in your broader interests in geopolitics and finance. Where is secular wisdom a gift? Where is it a seduction? Sit in silence for 10 minutes and ask for discernment. Write one sentence about what emerged.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The desert fathers &mdash; radical formation in the wilderness</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Matthew 4:1&ndash;11<br>Jesus in the wilderness &mdash; the template for the desert fathers who went to the Egyptian desert to do battle with spiritual opposition. Read it three times. What did Jesus do in the wilderness that shaped his ministry? What did the desert fathers think wilderness could do?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Justo González, <em>The Story of Christianity, Vol. 1</em>, Chapter 16: &ldquo;The Monks.&rdquo; González traces the emergence of desert monasticism &mdash; the first systematic experiment in intentional Christian formation. Read his account of Anthony of Egypt and the desert tradition and what it was attempting.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">The desert fathers developed a vocabulary of spiritual combat: <em>acedia</em> (spiritual torpor), <em>logismoi</em> (invasive thoughts), the &lsquo;noonday demon.&rsquo; What is your equivalent of the noonday demon &mdash; the specific spiritual attack that comes for you most reliably, at the moment of greatest vulnerability? Name it precisely.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>A desert practice: eat your next meal in silence, slowly, without phone or distraction. Let the meal be a form of prayer. The desert fathers believed the small, mundane disciplines were the training ground for the large spiritual ones. Write one sentence about what the experience of eating in silence revealed.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Unit 1 synthesis &mdash; the early church as formation</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Hebrews 11:39&ndash;40<br><em>&ldquo;These were all commended for their faith, yet none of them received what had been promised, since God had planned something better for us so that only together with us would they be made perfect.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The early church is waiting for you. You are part of their completion. What does this do to how you hold the tradition?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your notes from both weeks. Then read Jaroslav Pelikan&rsquo;s epigraph: &lsquo;Tradition is the living faith of the dead; traditionalism is the dead faith of the living.&rsquo; Write what this distinction means. Which do you tend toward?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write one full page: &ldquo;What the early church gives me.&rdquo; What do you receive from Ignatius, Irenaeus, the desert fathers, the Didache community? What specific gifts does the tradition hand you that your own century cannot produce? What debts do you owe to people who died before your grandparents were born?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: one practice from the early church tradition you want to incorporate into your own Rule of Life. Write what it is and why.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div><div class="unit-label" style="margin-top:2rem;">Unit 2 &middot; 2 Weeks</div><div class="unit-title">The Creeds: What the Church Decided and Why</div><div class="unit-desc">The councils of Nicaea and Chalcedon were not bureaucratic exercises. They were the church fighting for the gospel itself. Pelikan on the creeds, and the theological logic beneath every line.</div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 3</span>
        <span class="week-title">The Nicene Crisis &mdash; why it mattered</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Arius and the question that split the church</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> John 10:30<br><em>&ldquo;I and the Father are one.&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times. Arius argued this meant unity of purpose, not unity of being. Athanasius argued it meant something ontological. Read it again. What is at stake in the difference?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Jaroslav Pelikan, <em>Credo</em>, Chapters 1&ndash;2: the emergence of conciliar theology and the Arian controversy. Pelikan traces how the church arrived at the Council of Nicaea (325 AD) and what Arius was actually arguing. Read carefully &mdash; Arius was not obviously wrong. The orthodox position required the development of new philosophical vocabulary.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Arius&rsquo;s position was: the Son is the greatest of created beings, subordinate to the Father, who alone is truly God. Athanasius&rsquo;s counter: if the Son is not fully God, he cannot save us &mdash; because only God can do what the Son does. Write Athanasius&rsquo;s argument in your own words. Do you find it compelling? Why or why not?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray the opening of the Nicene Creed slowly: <em>&lsquo;I believe in one God, the Father Almighty, maker of heaven and earth, of all things visible and invisible.&rsquo;</em> Sit with each phrase. Write: which phrase carries the most weight for you today, and why?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Homoousios &mdash; why one word cost everything</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> John 1:14<br><em>&ldquo;The Word became flesh and made his dwelling among us.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The Nicene council chose the word <em>homoousios</em> &mdash; of the same substance as the Father &mdash; rather than <em>homoiousios</em> &mdash; of similar substance. One iota. Why does one letter matter?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Pelikan, <em>Credo</em>, Chapter 3: the Council of Nicaea and the logic of <em>homoousios.</em> Pelikan traces the philosophical difficulty of using a non-biblical word to defend a biblical truth &mdash; and why the church eventually concluded it was necessary. Read his account of how the council reached its conclusion.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write: What does it mean that the church fought bitterly over a single Greek word? Is this a mark of faithful seriousness or ecclesial dysfunction? Pelikan argues it was both &mdash; but ultimately that the precision was worth the cost. Do you agree? What does the fight over <em>homoousios</em> say about the importance of getting theology right?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Memorize the Nicene Creed today &mdash; or as much of it as you can. Read it through three times, then write from memory. Pray each line as you memorize it. The discipline of memorization forces you to slow down at the exact lines where your belief is uncertain. Write one sentence about where you paused.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Athanasius contra mundum &mdash; what faithfulness looks like under pressure</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Daniel 3:16&ndash;18<br>Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego: <em>&ldquo;The God we serve is able to deliver us&hellip; But even if he does not&hellip; we will not serve your gods.&rdquo;</em> Athanasius was exiled five times for holding the Nicene position. Read the passage three times. What enables &lsquo;but even if not&rsquo; faith?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Justo González, <em>The Story of Christianity, Vol. 1</em>, Chapter 17: &ldquo;Athanasius and the Nicene Crisis.&rdquo; González traces Athanasius&rsquo;s five exiles and his refusal to compromise. His famous phrase: <em>Athanasius contra mundum</em> &mdash; Athanasius against the world. Read González&rsquo;s account of what sustained him.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Athanasius held a minority position, supported by the bishop of Rome but opposed by most of the Eastern church and multiple emperors. He did not capitulate. Write: what would it take for you to hold a position contra mundum? Where in your faith do you already do this? Where do you capitulate to avoid the social cost?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray for the gift of courage in your theological convictions &mdash; not stubbornness, but the kind of grounded clarity that Athanasius had. What is the current conviction of yours that costs you something to hold? Sit in silence for 10 minutes and ask for the courage to hold it well.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The Nicene Creed as prayer &mdash; praying what you believe</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Deuteronomy 6:4&ndash;9<br><em>&ldquo;Hear, O Israel: The Lord our God, the Lord is one. Love the Lord your God with all your heart and with all your soul and with all your strength.&rdquo;</em> The Shema &mdash; the Jewish confession that precedes all creeds. Read it three times. What does reciting a confession do that merely believing it privately does not?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Pelikan, <em>Credo</em>, Chapter 4: the creeds as doxology. Pelikan argues that the creeds are not primarily legal documents but liturgical acts &mdash; the church&rsquo;s worship taking a specific shape. Read his account of how reciting the creed is itself a form of prayer.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">The Nicene Creed has been prayed by every generation of Christians since 381 AD. When you recite it, you are praying with Athanasius, with Augustine, with Thomas Aquinas, with John Wesley, with every baptized believer who died before you. Write: what does it mean to pray inside a community that stretches 1,700 years in both directions?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray the Nicene Creed aloud, slowly &mdash; once as a theological statement, once as a personal confession, once as a doxology. Three different postures, same words. Write: what changes when the mode of recitation changes?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Week synthesis &mdash; the creed as home</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Ephesians 4:4&ndash;6<br><em>&ldquo;There is one body and one Spirit&hellip; one Lord, one faith, one baptism; one God and Father of all.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Paul&rsquo;s sevenfold unity. What does it mean that Christian unity is doctrinal, not merely experiential?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your notes from this week. Then write out the Nicene Creed from memory one final time. Check it. Write what you got wrong and what you got right.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write a one-page reflection: &ldquo;The Nicene Creed as my theology.&rdquo; Go through each clause and write a sentence about what it means to you personally &mdash; not the history, not the controversy, what the clause means for your life with God right now. Let the creed be a self-examination.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: write one line from the Nicene Creed that currently feels most alive to you, and one line that currently feels most distant. Write why for each.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 4</span>
        <span class="week-title">Chalcedon and the Shape of Orthodox Christology</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The question Chalcedon had to answer</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> John 11:33&ndash;35<br>Jesus weeps at Lazarus&rsquo;s tomb. Read it three times. God weeps. What is the theological significance of divine tears? What does it mean for the eternal Son of God to have a body that cries?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Justo González, <em>The Story of Christianity, Vol. 1</em>, Chapter 19: &ldquo;The Christological Controversies.&rdquo; González traces the two errors the Council of Chalcedon (451 AD) was trying to avoid: Nestorianism (so separate that Christ is two persons) and Monophysitism (so merged that Christ&rsquo;s humanity is absorbed). Read his account of the theological precision required.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Chalcedon&rsquo;s formula: one person, two natures &mdash; truly God and truly human &mdash; without confusion, change, division, or separation. Write what each of the four negatives protects against. Why does it matter that Christ is not confused (mixed together), not changed (one overwriting the other), not divided (two persons), not separated (two independent beings)?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray the Chalcedonian definition as a meditation. Read it through once slowly. Then sit with the image of Jesus weeping at Lazarus&rsquo;s grave &mdash; fully divine, fully human, genuinely moved. Write: what does Chalcedon protect about the God who wept?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The Apostles&rsquo; Creed &mdash; the older confession</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Luke 1:26&ndash;35<br>The Annunciation: <em>&ldquo;The Holy Spirit will come on you, and the power of the Most High will overshadow you.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The Apostles&rsquo; Creed says &lsquo;born of the Virgin Mary.&rsquo; Why does this specific clause matter? What does it protect about the Incarnation?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Pelikan, <em>Credo</em>, Chapters 5&ndash;6: the Apostles&rsquo; Creed and its history. Pelikan traces the development and use of the Apostles&rsquo; Creed &mdash; older than Nicaea in some form &mdash; and its function in baptismal catechesis. Read his account of how the creed taught new believers what they were entering.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">The Apostles&rsquo; Creed was used to prepare people for baptism &mdash; it was the summary of what they were confessing as they came up out of the water. What would it mean to approach the creed with the freshness of someone about to be baptized &mdash; for whom these words are the first articulation of a new life?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Write out the Apostles&rsquo; Creed from memory. Then read it clause by clause, pausing after each one and writing one sentence about what that clause means for your life today. Let it be a personal examination, not a historical summary.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">What the creeds give to the present</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 1 Corinthians 11:26<br><em>&ldquo;For whenever you eat this bread and drink this cup, you proclaim the Lord&rsquo;s death until he comes.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The church lives between the first and second coming, proclaiming. The creed is part of that proclamation. What does it mean to be a church that confesses rather than merely believes privately?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Pelikan, <em>Credo</em>, Chapter 8: the creed and the future. Pelikan traces how the eschatological clauses of the creed &mdash; the resurrection of the dead, the life of the world to come &mdash; shape the community&rsquo;s posture toward history. Read his account of what &lsquo;I believe in the resurrection of the body&rsquo; has meant for Christian social engagement.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">The creed ends with future tense: resurrection of the dead, life of the world to come. What difference does it make to your present-moment decisions that you believe the body will be raised? That creation will be renewed? That there is a world to come? Write the specific, practical difference in one area of your life where this eschatological belief actually matters.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray the Apostles&rsquo; Creed as a closing prayer for this unit &mdash; once through, slowly, as doxology. Then sit in silence for 10 minutes. Let the creed&rsquo;s content be the territory of the silence. Write one sentence: what does it feel like to inhabit the creed rather than merely recite it?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Course 1.4 synthesis &mdash; the tradition as gift</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Jude 3<br><em>&ldquo;I felt compelled to write and urge you to contend for the faith that was once for all entrusted to God&rsquo;s holy people.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Contending for faith &mdash; not as argument but as stewardship. What does it mean to be a steward of the tradition?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read all of your Course 1.4 journal. Identify the three most significant historical moments from the early church that have most shaped your theology. Write one sentence on each.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Course 1.4 synthesis essay: &ldquo;What the tradition gives and what it asks.&rdquo; Two full pages. Cover: what the early church&rsquo;s simplicity shows you, what the creeds give you that private belief cannot, what Athanasius&rsquo;s faithfulness asks of you, and what the tradition as a whole does to your sense of who you are as a Christian. Write in your own voice.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray the Nicene Creed one final time. Then write: what line of the creed do you most need to inhabit more deeply in the coming year? Not know &mdash; inhabit. Make it your prayer for the year.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Year I synthesis &mdash; the first year&rsquo;s formation</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Psalm 84:5&ndash;7<br><em>&ldquo;Blessed are those whose strength is in you, whose hearts are set on pilgrimage&hellip; They go from strength to strength, till each appears before God in Zion.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Pilgrimage &mdash; not arrival, but directional movement. From strength to strength. What word arrests you?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your journal from the entire Year I. All of it &mdash; Course 1.1 through 1.4. Identify the five most significant formations of the year. Write one sentence on each. Then: write what you believed at the start that you now hold differently. Write what you practice now that you did not practice then.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Year I synthesis essay: &ldquo;What Year I has done in me.&rdquo; Two full pages. Cover: how your reading of Scripture has changed, how your theology of God&rsquo;s grace has changed, how your prayer life has changed, and what the early church has given you. This is the document you will read at the beginning of Year II to know where you started. Write it for your future self.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Year I Examen: Re-read all of your Weekly Examens from the year. What pattern do you see in your responses over time? What is God consistently pressing on? Write a paragraph. Then sit in 20 minutes of silence &mdash; the longest silence of the year &mdash; as your final act of Year I.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div></div>
</section><section id="y2" class="section">
  <div id="y2-c21" class="course-section">
    <div class="course-divider">Course 2.1 &mdash; Systematic Theology</div>
    <div class="unit-label" style="margin-top:1rem;">Unit 1 &middot; 3 Weeks</div>
    <div class="unit-title">The Doctrine of God: Trinity, Attributes, and Character</div>
    <div class="unit-desc">Who is the God we are being formed toward? The Trinity as the explanation of love, the attributes as the shape of his character, and the Wesleyan God who is both sovereign and relational.</div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 1</span>
        <span class="week-title">The Trinity &mdash; why God is love before creation</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Why the Trinity is not an abstract puzzle</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> John 17:20&ndash;26<br>Jesus&rsquo;s high priestly prayer &mdash; his final request before the cross. <em>&ldquo;That they may be one as we are one.&rdquo;</em> The Trinity is not merely a doctrine to defend &mdash; it is a life to be drawn into. Read it three times. What does &ldquo;in us&rdquo; (v.21) mean? What word arrests you?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Michael Reeves, <em>Delighting in the Trinity</em>, Chapter 1: &ldquo;What Was God Doing Before Creation?&rdquo; Reeves argues that the Trinity is not an add-on to Christian theology but its generative center &mdash; without it, God would be a solitary monad incapable of love before anything existed. Mark the argument&rsquo;s key move.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Reeves argues: if God is not Trinitarian, then God needed to create in order to love &mdash; which makes creation a necessity, not a gift. How does the Trinity protect the freedom and graciousness of creation? Why does it matter that God was already love before anything else existed? Connect this to the Wesleyan account of prevenient grace.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray the Lord&rsquo;s Prayer phrase by phrase &mdash; today only the opening: <em>&ldquo;Our Father in heaven, hallowed be your name.&rdquo;</em> Sit with the word <em>Father.</em> What does it invoke in you? What has shaped your association with that word? Write one honest paragraph.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The Father who begets &mdash; eternal generation and what it means</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> John 1:1&ndash;18<br><em>&ldquo;In the beginning was the Word, and the Word was with God, and the Word was God.&rdquo;</em> Note John&rsquo;s deliberate echo of Genesis 1:1. What does it mean that the Word &ldquo;was with God&rdquo; &mdash; a phrase of relationship, not just location? What word do you carry?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Michael Reeves, <em>Delighting in the Trinity</em>, Chapter 2: &ldquo;The Father: The Lover.&rdquo; Reeves argues the primary identity of God is not &ldquo;Creator&rdquo; or &ldquo;Ruler&rdquo; but &ldquo;Father&rdquo; &mdash; a relational identity that precedes all acts. Read his account of why this matters for how we understand who God is toward us.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">If God&rsquo;s primary identity is &ldquo;Father&rdquo; rather than &ldquo;King&rdquo; or &ldquo;Judge,&rdquo; how does that change the grammar of prayer? Which one you lead with shapes everything. How does your own prayer life reflect which identity of God you default to? Write honestly.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray the Lord&rsquo;s Prayer today, only: <em>&ldquo;Your kingdom come, your will be done, on earth as it is in heaven.&rdquo;</em> Sit with <em>on earth as it is in heaven.</em> What would it look like for your life &mdash; your actual day today &mdash; to be arranged as if it is in heaven? Write two sentences.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The Son who reveals &mdash; whoever has seen me has seen the Father</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Colossians 1:15&ndash;20<br><em>&ldquo;The Son is the image of the invisible God.&rdquo;</em> The Son does not merely represent God &mdash; he is the image, the visible form of the invisible. <em>&ldquo;All things were created through him and for him.&rdquo;</em> What does it mean that the universe was made &ldquo;for&rdquo; a person?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Michael Reeves, <em>Delighting in the Trinity</em>, Chapter 3: &ldquo;The Son: The Beloved.&rdquo; Reeves traces how the Son&rsquo;s eternal relationship with the Father is the basis of his mission &mdash; he is sent because he is loved, and his love overflows. Read his account of how the incarnation is the arrival of the eternal relationship into time.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Reeves argues the Son reveals the Father because the Son has known and loved the Father eternally. He shows us from inside the relationship. When Jesus acts with compassion, when he weeps, when he withdraws to pray &mdash; what are you watching? Write your answer carefully &mdash; this is the question behind all Christology.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray the phrase: <em>&ldquo;Give us today our daily bread.&rdquo;</em> Sit with <em>daily</em> &mdash; not monthly, not annually. Today. What are you actually dependent on God for today &mdash; not in theology but in practice? List five things. Pray each one slowly.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The Spirit who applies &mdash; the Spirit in Wesleyan theology</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Romans 8:14&ndash;27<br>The Spirit as the one who intercedes, who bears witness, who leads. Read it three times. Verse 26 is startling: the Spirit <em>&ldquo;intercedes for us through wordless groans.&rdquo;</em> What does it mean that prayer is not something you do alone &mdash; that the Spirit prays in you?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Michael Reeves, <em>Delighting in the Trinity</em>, Chapter 4: &ldquo;The Spirit: The Breath of Love.&rdquo; Reeves traces the Spirit as the &ldquo;bond of love&rdquo; between Father and Son &mdash; the one who draws us into the Trinitarian life. In Wesleyan theology, the Spirit is the agent of prevenient, justifying, and sanctifying grace.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">You have had experiences of the Spirit that were quieter and more interior than what you encountered in Atlanta. Reeves argues the Spirit&rsquo;s work is always to draw attention to the Son, not to itself. How does this criterion help you evaluate different pneumatological experiences &mdash; your own and others&rsquo;? Write your theology of the Spirit&rsquo;s work in you specifically.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray the closing doxology: <em>&ldquo;For yours is the kingdom and the power and the glory forever.&rdquo;</em> Then sit in five minutes of silence. Let the silence be the Spirit&rsquo;s territory &mdash; don&rsquo;t fill it with words or plans. Practice receiving rather than giving in prayer. Write one sentence about what happened.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The Lord&rsquo;s Prayer as Trinitarian formation</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Matthew 6:5&ndash;15<br>The Lord&rsquo;s Prayer in context &mdash; surrounded by warnings about performance and reassurances about the Father who sees in secret. Read it three times. Notice the context Jesus provides before he gives the prayer. What is he protecting against?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Thomas Oden, <em>Classic Christianity</em>, Part I opening section on &ldquo;The Living God.&rdquo; Oden is a Wesleyan systematician &mdash; his account of the divine attributes (holiness, love, justice, mercy) will deepen and systematize what Reeves has opened. Read 15&ndash;20 pages.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write a one-page summary of your doctrine of God as it stands today &mdash; not what you were taught, but what you actually believe after this week. Include: (1) the Trinity as the basis of love, (2) the Spirit&rsquo;s role in your formation, (3) how Trinitarian theology changes the grammar of intercessory prayer. Use specific language &mdash; don&rsquo;t let yourself be vague.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray the entire Lord&rsquo;s Prayer slowly &mdash; one phrase per breath &mdash; seven times. Then: Weekly Examen. Where did Scripture most open something this week? Where did Tradition most challenge you? Where did Reason reach its edge? Where did Experience surprise you? Four sentences.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 2</span>
        <span class="week-title">The Attributes of God &mdash; what God is like</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Holiness and love &mdash; the two poles of God&rsquo;s character</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Isaiah 6:1&ndash;8<br><em>&ldquo;Holy, holy, holy is the Lord Almighty; the whole earth is full of his glory.&rdquo;</em> Isaiah&rsquo;s vision in the temple. Read it three times. Notice the sequence: vision of holiness, confession of uncleanness, cleansing, commission. What word arrests you today?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Thomas Oden, <em>Classic Christianity</em>, Part I, Chapter 2: &ldquo;The Holy One.&rdquo; Oden traces the relationship between God&rsquo;s holiness and love in the Wesleyan tradition &mdash; they are not in tension but are two aspects of the same character. Read his account carefully.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wesley insisted that the goal of salvation is not merely forgiveness but participation in God&rsquo;s holiness &mdash; the restoration of the <em>image of God</em> in us. What does it mean for holiness to be the goal of your formation, not just the standard you fail to meet? Write one page on this.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Read Isaiah 6:5 slowly: <em>&ldquo;Woe to me! I am ruined! For I am a man of unclean lips.&rdquo;</em> Then sit in silence for 10 minutes and let that awareness settle without explanation or defense. Examen of speech: Where did your words this week serve others? Where did they serve only you?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Omniscience and divine knowing &mdash; what it means to be fully known</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Psalm 139:1&ndash;18<br><em>&ldquo;You have searched me, Lord, and you know me.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Note the progression &mdash; God knows your sitting, your rising, your words before you speak them. What does it feel like to be fully known by someone who cannot be deceived and will not leave?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Thomas Oden, <em>Classic Christianity</em>, Part I, Chapter 3: &ldquo;The Omniscient One.&rdquo; Oden addresses the pastoral implications of divine omniscience &mdash; not merely as an attribute to affirm but as a reality to live inside. Read his account of how omniscience relates to prayer.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">The Wesleyan tradition holds that God&rsquo;s omniscience is compatible with human freedom &mdash; God knows what you will freely choose without determining it. How does this differ from Calvinist foreordination? Write the distinction carefully. What does it mean for your accountability before God?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray Psalm 139:23&ndash;24: <em>&ldquo;Search me, God, and know my heart; test me and know my anxious thoughts.&rdquo;</em> This is an invitation, not a confession. Sit in silence for 10 minutes after praying it. Let God search. Write one sentence about what surfaces.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Providence and human freedom in Wesleyan thought</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Romans 8:28&ndash;39<br><em>&ldquo;In all things God works for the good of those who love him.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Note: not &ldquo;all things are good&rdquo; but &ldquo;God works in all things.&rdquo; The distinction matters enormously for how you sit with suffering. What word arrests you?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Randy Maddox, <em>Responsible Grace</em>, Chapter 4: &ldquo;The God of Responsible Grace.&rdquo; Maddox addresses Wesley&rsquo;s account of providence &mdash; how God governs a world in which human freedom is real. Read his treatment of how Wesley held together divine sovereignty and genuine creaturely agency.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">The Wesleyan tradition resists both determinism (everything is fixed) and open theism (God doesn&rsquo;t know what will happen). Where do you currently land? Write your honest working theology of providence. Be specific: how does your view change how you make decisions, grieve losses, or respond to unexpected events?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Take your devotional walk today with this question held open: <em>Where is God working in something I have called a setback?</em> Don&rsquo;t answer it during the walk. Return and write two paragraphs &mdash; one on what you saw, one on what you are willing to trust.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Human dignity and the image of God</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Genesis 1:26&ndash;28 and Psalm 8<br>Two accounts of human dignity. Genesis 1: image-bearers, given dominion. Psalm 8: <em>&ldquo;what is mankind that you are mindful of them?&rdquo;</em> Read both three times. What does it mean to be simultaneously small (Psalm 8) and dignified (Genesis 1)? What word stays with you?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> James K.A. Smith, <em>You Are What You Love</em>, Chapter 1: &ldquo;You Are What You Love.&rdquo; Smith argues that humans are fundamentally <em>desiring</em> creatures &mdash; we are shaped by what we love, not what we know. Read his account of how liturgy (habitual practice) forms the direction of desire.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Smith&rsquo;s key insight: you are not primarily a thinking thing but a <em>wanting</em> thing, and what you want is shaped by what you do habitually. Map your daily habits as &ldquo;liturgies.&rdquo; Which ones are forming you toward God? Which away? Be ruthlessly specific about the actual habits, not the intended ones.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Smith&rsquo;s &ldquo;liturgy audit&rdquo;: for 15 minutes, write out your average day from waking to sleeping. Circle the practices that have a formational direction. Put a cross next to ones oriented toward God. Put an arrow next to ones oriented elsewhere. What do you see?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Week synthesis &mdash; the God who forms us</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 2 Peter 1:3&ndash;11<br><em>&ldquo;His divine power has given us everything we need for a godly life.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Note the progression Peter describes: faith, goodness, knowledge, self-control, perseverance, godliness, mutual affection, love. What does it mean that these are given, not achieved &mdash; but still require participation?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Dallas Willard, <em>Renovation of the Heart</em>, Chapter 1: &ldquo;Spiritual Formation as the Way to Christlikeness.&rdquo; You are reading this already. Re-read Chapter 1 with fresh eyes &mdash; now in the context of Reeves&rsquo;s Trinitarian theology and Oden&rsquo;s account of the divine attributes. What does formation look like if it is formation <em>into</em> Trinitarian life?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write your VIM statement (Willard&rsquo;s Vision, Intention, Means): What is your Vision of the life you are moving toward? What is your Intention &mdash; are you genuinely committed to it, not merely interested? What are the Means &mdash; the specific practices that will take you there? One paragraph per category. Be concrete.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen and unit reflection: You are two weeks into Year II. What has the move from Year I (What to believe) to Year II (How to live it) felt like? What is God pressing on? Four examen sentences, then one paragraph of reflection.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 3</span>
        <span class="week-title">Sin, Evil, and the Problem of Suffering</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The reality of evil &mdash; not explaining it but naming it</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Genesis 4:1&ndash;16<br>Cain and Abel. <em>&ldquo;Sin is crouching at your door; it desires to have you, but you must rule over it.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Notice how God warns Cain before he acts &mdash; prevenient grace operating even here. What does &ldquo;sin is crouching at your door&rdquo; name in your own experience?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> N.T. Wright, <em>Evil and the Justice of God</em>, Chapter 1: &ldquo;Evil: The Fact and the Puzzle.&rdquo; Wright argues the Christian answer to evil is not a philosophical solution but an engagement with it. He traces the inadequacy of both secular and naive religious accounts. Read carefully.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wright says we must neither explain evil away nor be overwhelmed by it &mdash; both are failures of nerve. The Christian response is to name it clearly and then trace what God has done about it in the cross and resurrection. Write: what is the evil you find hardest to name clearly? Not in the abstract &mdash; in your own experience or world.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Sit with the book of Job 3:1&ndash;26 &mdash; Job&rsquo;s lament. Read it aloud. Don&rsquo;t resolve it. Write what remains unresolved for you after reading. This is not a failure of faith &mdash; it is the beginning of honest theology.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The cross as God&rsquo;s response to evil</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Romans 5:6&ndash;11<br><em>&ldquo;God demonstrates his own love for us in this: while we were still sinners, Christ died for us.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Note the timing: not after repentance, not after improvement. While we were still sinners. What does this say about the nature of the love that drives the atonement?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> N.T. Wright, <em>Evil and the Justice of God</em>, Chapter 4: &ldquo;The Cross and the Defeat of Evil.&rdquo; Wright argues the cross is not God&rsquo;s way of satisfying a legal requirement but his way of absorbing evil into himself and exhausting it. Read his argument and evaluate it carefully.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wright&rsquo;s cruciform answer to evil: God enters it rather than explains it. C.S. Lewis&rsquo;s answer: God uses suffering to form character. These are not incompatible, but they address different questions. Write: which answer do you need more? Where has evil in your life called for each response?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Intercessory prayer for those suffering: Name five people or situations where evil is present &mdash; illness, grief, injustice, relationship breakdown. Pray for each one specifically. Not for resolution &mdash; for God&rsquo;s presence. Sit in silence after each name.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Job and the limits of explanation</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Job 38:1&ndash;18<br>God speaks from the whirlwind: <em>&ldquo;Where were you when I laid the earth&rsquo;s foundation?&rdquo;</em> God&rsquo;s answer to Job is not an explanation of his suffering but a revelation of his own incomprehensibility. Read it three times. Is this a satisfying answer? What word arrests you?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> C.S. Lewis, <em>The Problem of Pain</em>, Chapter 6: &ldquo;Human Pain.&rdquo; Lewis distinguishes between pain that builds character and pain that merely destroys. Read his account of how suffering can serve formation without insisting it always does. Note where Lewis is most convincing and where he is most unconvincing.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Lewis was writing before his wife Joy died of cancer. After her death, he wrote <em>A Grief Observed</em> &mdash; a far rawer document that partially undoes <em>The Problem of Pain.</em> Which Lewis do you trust more: the systematic apologist or the grieving husband? What does this tell you about the limits of theodicy?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Write: Where have you experienced suffering that you could not explain? What did it do to your faith &mdash; and what is it doing now? Don&rsquo;t rush to resolution. This is a question to sit with, not answer.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Ecclesiology &mdash; what the church is for</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 1 Corinthians 12:12&ndash;27<br>The body of Christ. <em>&ldquo;If one part suffers, every part suffers with it; if one part is honored, every part rejoices with it.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. What does it mean that your formation is communal, not merely individual? What word arrests you today?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Wesley, Standard Sermon: &ldquo;On the Church.&rdquo; Wesley argues against a merely invisible or purely spiritual conception of the church. The church is a visible community of people practicing the means of grace together. Read his argument and note where his ecclesiology is distinctly Wesleyan.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wesley&rsquo;s &ldquo;no holiness but social holiness&rdquo; claim: sanctification is not a private achievement but a communal formation. What does this mean practically? Where are you currently being formed by community? Where are you trying to be formed alone in ways that may be unsustainable?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Attend Communion this week with intentional preparation. Before you go: read 1 Corinthians 11:23&ndash;26 slowly. After you receive: sit for five minutes in silence. Journal one paragraph about what you brought to the table and what you received.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Unit synthesis &mdash; the God who suffers with us</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Hebrews 4:14&ndash;16<br><em>&ldquo;We do not have a high priest who is unable to empathize with our weaknesses, but we have one who has been tempted in every way, just as we are &mdash; yet he did not sin.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. What does a God who has suffered mean for how you bring your suffering to him?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your journal from this unit. Then read Miroslav Volf, <em>After Our Likeness</em>, Chapter 1: &ldquo;The Church as the Image of the Trinity.&rdquo; Volf argues that the church &mdash; its gathered life, its shared suffering, its communal practices &mdash; is itself an image of Trinitarian life. Read his opening argument.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write a one-page reflection on suffering and formation: What has this unit changed about how you will sit with someone in grief? What would you say differently to someone in deep pain after reading Wright, Lewis, and Job? What would you no longer say?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: one practice from this unit you will carry forward. Name it. Write it. Begin it this week.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div id="y2-c22" class="course-section" style="display:none;"><div class="course-divider">Course 2.2 &mdash; Church History: Reformation to Present</div><div class="unit-label" style="margin-top:2rem;">Unit 1 &middot; 3 Weeks</div><div class="unit-title">The Reformation and Its Fractures</div><div class="unit-desc">Luther, Calvin, and the dangerous idea that the Bible belongs to everyone. McGrath and González on what the Reformation unleashed &mdash; and what it could not control.</div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 1</span>
        <span class="week-title">Luther and the recovery of grace</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The 95 Theses &mdash; what Luther was actually arguing</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Romans 1:16&ndash;17<br><em>&ldquo;For in the gospel the righteousness of God is revealed &mdash; a righteousness that is by faith from first to last.&rdquo;</em> This verse broke open for Luther at his tower experience. Read it three times. What does it mean that righteousness is <em>revealed</em> rather than achieved?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Alister McGrath, <em>Christianity&rsquo;s Dangerous Idea</em>, Chapters 1&ndash;3: the Reformation breakthrough and Luther&rsquo;s discovery. McGrath traces how Luther&rsquo;s reading of Paul led him to a fundamentally different understanding of justification than medieval Catholic theology offered. Read carefully.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Luther&rsquo;s discovery: &lsquo;righteousness of God&rsquo; does not mean God&rsquo;s demand but God&rsquo;s gift &mdash; the righteousness God gives rather than the righteousness God requires. Write the difference clearly. How does this change the grammar of the Christian life? What does it mean for how you think about your standing before God today?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Luther&rsquo;s Reformation began not as a revolt but as an academic dispute. He posted theses for debate &mdash; an ordinary academic practice. Write: where in your own life have things escalated beyond what you intended because you named something true? What does Luther&rsquo;s unintended revolution teach about speaking truth honestly?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Sola scriptura &mdash; the dangerous idea</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 2 Timothy 3:16&ndash;17<br><em>&ldquo;All Scripture is God-breathed and is useful for teaching, rebuking, correcting and training in righteousness.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Luther&rsquo;s appeal: Scripture alone is the final authority. What does &lsquo;alone&rsquo; protect against? What does it risk?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Alister McGrath, <em>Christianity&rsquo;s Dangerous Idea</em>, Chapter 4: &ldquo;The Dangerous Idea.&rdquo; McGrath argues that sola scriptura was not just a theological principle but a cultural earthquake &mdash; once everyone could read the Bible for themselves, the church could not control the interpretation. Read his account of why it was &lsquo;dangerous.&rsquo;</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">McGrath traces how sola scriptura led directly to Protestant fragmentation &mdash; once the Bible is open to private interpretation, who adjudicates disagreement? Wesley tried to answer this with his Quadrilateral. Write your honest evaluation: is sola scriptura a gift, a problem, or both? What does the existence of 40,000 Protestant denominations say?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Practice: Read a passage of Scripture &mdash; Luke 6:27&ndash;36 &mdash; without any commentary, notes, or reference to what others have said. Just the text. Then write your honest interpretation. Then: read one commentary on the passage. Write what the community of interpretation corrects or confirms in your reading.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Calvin and the sovereignty of God</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Isaiah 46:9&ndash;10<br><em>&ldquo;I am God, and there is no other; I am God, and there is none like me. I make known the end from the beginning, from ancient times, what is still to come.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. This is the Reformed anchor text. What does it mean for God to &lsquo;make known the end from the beginning&rsquo;? What does that require of his knowledge of the future?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Alister McGrath, <em>Christianity&rsquo;s Dangerous Idea</em>, Chapter 6: &ldquo;Calvin&rsquo;s Legacy.&rdquo; McGrath traces Calvin&rsquo;s theology &mdash; particularly his doctrine of election and predestination &mdash; and its consequences for Reformed piety, politics, and social ethics. Read his account of what Calvinist theology actually claims.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write a two-paragraph comparison: Calvin&rsquo;s sovereignty (God has elected specific individuals for salvation from eternity, and this election is unconditional) vs. Wesley&rsquo;s responsible grace (God extends grace to all, humans can resist or respond, election is corporate and conditioned on faith). Where is the genuine theological dispute? Is there a synthesis?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray for someone you love whose salvation you are anxious about. The Calvinist says: trust God&rsquo;s election. The Wesleyan says: trust God&rsquo;s pursuing grace and pray specifically. Pray for that person for 10 minutes, using the Wesleyan grammar: God is pursuing them, grace is working, pray for their response. Write one sentence afterward.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The Reformation&rsquo;s social consequences</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Galatians 3:28<br><em>&ldquo;There is neither Jew nor Gentile, neither slave nor free, nor is there male and female, for you are all one in Christ Jesus.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The Reformation&rsquo;s democratization of Scripture had enormous social effects. What does this verse authorize that a hierarchical reading of Christianity might suppress?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Justo González, <em>The Story of Christianity, Vol. 2</em>, Chapters 1&ndash;4: the social consequences of the Reformation. González traces how the Reformation broke down clerical-lay hierarchy, enabled literacy campaigns for Scripture reading, and eventually contributed to broader social democratization. Read his account.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">González traces both the Reformation&rsquo;s liberating effects (priesthood of all believers, Scripture in the vernacular, lay access to the sacraments) and its violent effects (the wars of religion, the persecution of Anabaptists). Write honestly: what does it mean to celebrate a movement that was both liberating and violent? How do you hold the mixed inheritance?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>The priesthood of all believers: Luther&rsquo;s conviction that every believer has direct access to God and is a priest to their neighbor. Write what this means practically for your relationships this week. Who are you a priest to &mdash; who needs you to bring them before God in intercession? Who needs you to speak God&rsquo;s word to them?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Week synthesis &mdash; the Reformation as inheritance</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Acts 17:11<br>The Bereans &lsquo;received the message with great eagerness and examined the Scriptures every day to see if what Paul said was true.&rsquo; Read it three times. Luther&rsquo;s ideal reader. What does it mean to receive teaching with eagerness AND examine it against Scripture?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your notes from this week. Then read Luther&rsquo;s speech at the Diet of Worms (1521): <em>&lsquo;Here I stand, I can do no other.&rsquo;</em> Available free online &mdash; read the full speech, not just the famous line. Read what Luther actually argued and what he was willing to die for.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write one full page: &ldquo;What the Reformation gave me and what it asks of me.&rdquo; What do you owe to Luther&rsquo;s courage? What does his legacy demand of you in terms of your own willingness to name truth under pressure? Where are you currently being asked to stand somewhere?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: one conviction you hold that, like Luther, you are not willing to retract. Write it clearly. Write why. Write what it would cost you to abandon it.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 2</span>
        <span class="week-title">The Reformation&rsquo;s fractures &mdash; Anabaptists and the radical wing</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The Anabaptists &mdash; the Reformation&rsquo;s most dangerous children</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Matthew 5:38&ndash;48<br>Turn the other cheek, love your enemies. Read it three times. The Anabaptists took these commands literally and refused military service, oaths, and violence. Both Luther and Calvin had them executed. What does the church&rsquo;s violence toward its most pacifist members reveal?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Justo González, <em>The Story of Christianity, Vol. 2</em>, Chapter 5: &ldquo;The Anabaptists.&rdquo; González traces the radical Reformation &mdash; the wing that wanted not to reform the church but to leave it entirely and form a pure believers&rsquo; community. Read his account of who they were and why they were persecuted by Catholics and Protestants alike.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">The Anabaptists&rsquo; core conviction: the church should be a gathered community of genuine believers, separate from the state. Both Luther and Calvin rejected this &mdash; they wanted a church that encompassed the whole society. Write your honest assessment: which model fits best with the New Testament? Which fits best with your current context in South Austin?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>The Anabaptists practiced what they called <em>Gelassenheit</em> &mdash; yieldedness, surrender of the self to God and community. Write one paragraph on what genuine surrender to the community of faith would require of you specifically that you currently do not offer.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The Council of Trent &mdash; the Catholic response</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Galatians 1:6&ndash;9<br>Paul&rsquo;s alarm at a &lsquo;different gospel.&rsquo; Read it three times. Trent and the Reformers both believed the other was preaching a different gospel. How do you adjudicate such a dispute? What criteria would you use?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Justo González, <em>The Story of Christianity, Vol. 2</em>, Chapters 6&ndash;7: the Counter-Reformation and the Council of Trent. González traces how the Catholic Church responded to the Reformation &mdash; not only by condemning Protestant positions but by undertaking genuine internal reform. Read his account of what Trent achieved and what it foreclosed.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Trent affirmed: Scripture AND Tradition as joint sources of authority; justification by faith AND works (merit); the Mass as a sacrifice; seven sacraments; purgatory. Wesley accepted some of these (multiple means of grace, the ongoing role of tradition) and rejected others (merit, purgatory, transubstantiation). Write your own evaluation: what in the Catholic tradition do you think the Reformers too quickly rejected?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray for Christian unity &mdash; not uniformity, but genuine charity across the Catholic-Protestant divide. For 10 minutes, pray for the things you hold in common with Catholic Christians and for the genuine humility to keep learning from a tradition that has preserved things your tradition has lost.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The English Reformation &mdash; why the via media matters</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Romans 14:1&ndash;4<br>Paul on welcoming the weak in faith &mdash; those whose convictions differ from yours in secondary matters. Read it three times. The Anglican via media attempted to hold a broad range of Protestant and Catholic sensibilities together. What does this attempt at comprehensiveness teach and what does it risk?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> McGrath, <em>Christianity&rsquo;s Dangerous Idea</em>, Chapter 8: &ldquo;The English Reformation.&rdquo; McGrath traces the peculiar path of the English Reformation &mdash; a Reformation driven as much by politics as by theology, but which produced, through the Book of Common Prayer and the Articles, a distinctive theological settlement. Read his account of what the English Reformation achieved.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wesley was formed inside the Church of England and died inside it &mdash; though his movement effectively left it after his death. He valued the Anglican liturgy, the lectionary, and the via media&rsquo;s breadth. Write: what do you gain from a tradition that values comprehensiveness over doctrinal precision? What do you lose? Which is more dangerous?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Read one prayer from the Book of Common Prayer (available free online) &mdash; the Collect for Purity, or the General Confession. Pray it slowly. The Anglican tradition believed that corporate, written prayer forms the individual. Write one sentence about what praying a written prayer does differently than praying extemporaneously.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The Reformation and Scripture &mdash; what it produced in us</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Nehemiah 8:1&ndash;8<br>Ezra reads the Law to all the people &mdash; men, women, children &mdash; and they weep. Read it three times. The Reformation&rsquo;s great gift: Scripture in the language of the people, read aloud, understood. What does Nehemiah 8 say about what happens when Scripture actually reaches the people?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read McGrath&rsquo;s opening argument from Week 1 about the &lsquo;dangerous idea&rsquo;. Then read Justo González, <em>The Story of Christianity, Vol. 2</em>, Chapter 9: &ldquo;The Spread of the Reformation.&rdquo; González traces how the Reformation spread through literacy, print, and vernacular Scripture. Note the connection between access to Scripture and social change.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">You read Scripture every day in this curriculum. You have access to dozens of translations, commentaries, and tools. You are the inheritor of 500 years of Reformation effort to put the Bible in the hands of ordinary people. Write: what do you owe to that inheritance? What do you take for granted that someone in 1400 would have given their life for?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Take 15 minutes to read a passage of Scripture &mdash; Psalm 119:105&ndash;112 &mdash; in three different translations. Note where they differ. What does the existence of translation diversity reveal about the nature of Scripture, the task of interpretation, and the gift of having multiple witnesses to the text?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Unit 1 synthesis &mdash; the Reformation as ongoing task</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> James 1:22&ndash;25<br><em>&ldquo;Do not merely listen to the word&hellip; Do what it says.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The Reformation produced readers. Wesley wanted doers. What is the relationship between right doctrine and transformed life? Can you have one without the other?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your notes from the past two weeks. Then read the Five Solas (Sola Scriptura, Sola Fide, Sola Gratia, Solus Christus, Soli Deo Gloria) as a single theological statement. Write your Wesleyan evaluation of each: which do you affirm fully, which do you qualify, which do you think needs supplement?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write one full page: &ldquo;What the Reformation asks of me.&rdquo; Not of Christians in general &mdash; of you, Trevor, in 2026. What does the Reformation&rsquo;s democratization of Scripture demand? What does Luther&rsquo;s courage to name truth ask? What does the Reformation&rsquo;s failures warn you against?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: one specific thing you will do differently in how you engage Scripture as a result of this unit. Write it concretely.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 3</span>
        <span class="week-title">The Wesleyan Revival &mdash; what grace looks like in history</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The 18th century &mdash; the world Wesley preached to</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Luke 4:18<br><em>&ldquo;The Spirit of the Lord is on me, because he has anointed me to proclaim good news to the poor.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Wesley preached to the poor because the poor had no access to the church. What does this verse say about where the gospel goes first?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> D. Bruce Hindmarsh, <em>The Spirit of Early Evangelicalism</em>, Chapters 3&ndash;4: the social world of 18th-century England and the emerging evangelical movement. Read Hindmarsh&rsquo;s account of what the 18th century was &mdash; Enlightenment rationalism, industrial poverty, declining church attendance, moral crisis &mdash; into which Wesley preached.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wesley saw himself as a physician to a sick society. He identified the disease (poverty of spirit, literal poverty, gin crisis, child labor) and prescribed a medicine (the gospel of grace, class meetings, social reform). Write: what is the equivalent diagnosis for 2026? What disease does your faith equip you to treat?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray for Austin, specifically &mdash; not abstractly. Name three things that are broken in the city you love. Pray for each one for three minutes. Then write: what is God asking the church in Austin to be in response to these?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The class meeting &mdash; the genius of Wesleyan formation</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Hebrews 10:24&ndash;25<br><em>&ldquo;Let us consider how we may spur one another on toward love and good deeds, not giving up meeting together.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Wesley&rsquo;s class meeting was his answer to this verse &mdash; a weekly gathering of 12 for mutual accountability and encouragement. What is your equivalent?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> David Hempton, <em>Methodism: Empire of the Spirit</em>, Chapter 3: &ldquo;The Class Meeting.&rdquo; Hempton traces how the class meeting was the engine of Wesleyan formation &mdash; the structure that turned individual conversions into sustainable communities of transformation. Read his account of how it worked and why it was effective.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">The class meeting&rsquo;s question: &lsquo;How does your soul prosper?&rsquo; It required honest answer. Not &lsquo;fine&rsquo; &mdash; actual account of one&rsquo;s spiritual state, temptations, failures, and growth. Write: who in your life is currently asking you how your soul prospers? Who are you asking? What is the honest answer to the question right now?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Practice: Find someone in your life &mdash; a trusted friend, a spiritual director, a pastor &mdash; and ask them the class meeting question: &lsquo;How does your soul prosper?&rsquo; Then answer it yourself, honestly, for 5 minutes. Write what emerged from the conversation.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Whitefield and the transatlantic revival &mdash; what happens when the Spirit moves</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Acts 2:14&ndash;21<br>Peter&rsquo;s Pentecost sermon. <em>&ldquo;Your sons and daughters will prophesy, your young men will see visions, your old men will dream dreams.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The Great Awakening in America and the Wesleyan Revival in Britain happened simultaneously. What happens when the Spirit moves across a culture?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Hindmarsh, <em>The Spirit of Early Evangelicalism</em>, Chapter 5: &ldquo;The Transatlantic Awakening.&rdquo; Hindmarsh traces how Whitefield, Edwards, and Wesley (different in theology, united in practice) fueled a transatlantic movement. Read his account of what they held in common and how the movement spread.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">The Great Awakening produced Jonathan Edwards, who wrote one of the most careful evaluations of revival in Christian history (<em>The Distinguishing Marks of a Work of the Spirit of God</em>). His question: how do you tell genuine revival from religious emotion? Write your own criteria: what would make you believe a spiritual movement is genuine? What would make you suspicious?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray for genuine spiritual renewal &mdash; in your own life, your church, Austin, and the broader church in America. Not vague renewal &mdash; specific renewal. What needs to wake up? Pray specifically. Sit in silence for 10 minutes after praying. Write one sentence about what came.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The social consequences of the revival &mdash; what grace produces</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Amos 5:24<br><em>&ldquo;Let justice roll on like a river, righteousness like a never-failing stream.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The Wesleyan revival produced abolitionists, prison reformers, and social reformers. Grace was not only personal &mdash; it was social. What is the necessary connection between genuine conversion and social concern?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Hempton, <em>Methodism: Empire of the Spirit</em>, Chapter 5: &ldquo;Methodism and Social Reform.&rdquo; Hempton traces the direct line from Wesleyan theology to the abolition movement, to factory reform, to education for the poor. Read his account of what the theology made possible that others couldn&rsquo;t see.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wesley&rsquo;s last letter was to Wilberforce, urging abolition. His first social concern was the gin crisis among the poor. His theology of prevenient grace led directly to his conviction that every person had dignity worth protecting. Write: what social conviction does your theology generate? Not what you think it should generate &mdash; what it actually produces in your choices, your spending, your attention.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>One act of social engagement this week: not a donation, a presence. Identify one place where your physical time and attention can serve a person or community that needs it. Write what it is. Do it this week. Report back on Saturday.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Unit 1 and Course 2.2 Week 3 synthesis</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Micah 6:8<br><em>&ldquo;Act justly, love mercy, walk humbly with your God.&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times. The whole Wesleyan social program in one verse. What does each element require from you specifically, in your specific life, right now?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your full Course 2.2 journal. Identify the three most significant formations from Units 1&ndash;3 of this course. Write one sentence on each. What has the study of history done to your faith?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write one page: &ldquo;What church history has done to my theology.&rdquo; Not what you know now that you didn&rsquo;t know before &mdash; what has changed in how you think and live. Has your view of the tradition changed? Has your Wesleyan identity deepened? Has your relationship to the broader ecumenical church changed?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: write one sentence about what the Wesleyan Revival asks of you in 2026.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div><div class="unit-label" style="margin-top:2rem;">Unit 2 &middot; 2 Weeks</div><div class="unit-title">Pentecostalism, Charismatics, and the Third Wave</div><div class="unit-desc">From Azusa Street to Ascend Church Atlanta. A theological account of the movement you have now had personal experience of, from the inside and the outside.</div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 4</span>
        <span class="week-title">Pentecostalism &mdash; the movement and its theology</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Azusa Street and the birth of Pentecostalism</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Acts 1:4&ndash;8<br><em>&ldquo;You will receive power when the Holy Spirit comes on you.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The Pentecostal movement began with this promise as its organizing conviction. What is the difference between a theology of the Spirit and a life lived in the expectation of the Spirit&rsquo;s power?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Allan Anderson, <em>An Introduction to Pentecostalism</em>, Chapters 1&ndash;2: the Azusa Street revival (1906) and the emergence of Pentecostalism. Anderson traces the social context &mdash; a multiracial revival in Los Angeles, led by a Black preacher (William Seymour) &mdash; and the theological claims that emerged from it. Read his account carefully.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Anderson notes that Azusa Street was multiracial in a deeply segregated America &mdash; the Spirit fell without regard to race or class. Frank Bartleman wrote: &lsquo;The color line was washed away in the blood.&rsquo; Write: what does this aspect of Pentecostalism&rsquo;s origin say about what the Spirit&rsquo;s work looks like? What does it say to the contemporary church?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray in the Spirit &mdash; not necessarily in tongues, but in the mode of openness and expectancy that the Pentecostal tradition values. For 10 minutes, pray with your hands open, your posture receptive, your agenda released. Write one sentence about what this posture does to your prayer that a more structured form doesn&rsquo;t.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The theology of the gifts &mdash; what Paul actually says</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 1 Corinthians 12:4&ndash;11<br>The list of gifts. Read it three times. Note: &lsquo;All these are the work of one and the same Spirit, and he distributes them to each one, just as he determines.&rsquo; The Spirit distributes &mdash; not the believer achieves. What does this say about how gifts operate?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Gordon Fee, <em>God&rsquo;s Empowering Presence</em>, selected chapters on the Spirit in Paul. Fee is a New Testament scholar who takes Pentecostal experience seriously. Read his careful exegetical account of the gifts in 1 Corinthians 12&ndash;14 &mdash; not as proof texts for contemporary practice but as Paul&rsquo;s own pastoral theology.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Fee argues Paul&rsquo;s primary concern in 1 Corinthians 12&ndash;14 is not whether gifts exist but how they function in community &mdash; for building up rather than self-display. Write your current position on the gifts of the Spirit: Do they continue? Which ones? How do you evaluate claimed manifestations? What is your hermeneutical basis for your position?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Practice: During your next church gathering, pray for one person &mdash; quietly, invisibly, without telling them. Ask the Spirit for a word of encouragement for them. Whether or not you receive one, write afterward: what did the act of paying Spirit-attentive attention to one person do to you?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The charismatic movement and its discontents</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 1 John 4:1<br><em>&ldquo;Dear friends, do not believe every spirit, but test the spirits to see whether they are from God, because many false prophets have gone out into the world.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The Wesleyan tradition has always combined openness to the Spirit with discernment. What does testing the spirits look like in practice?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Anderson, <em>An Introduction to Pentecostalism</em>, Chapters 3&ndash;4: the charismatic movement and its entry into mainline denominations. Anderson traces how the Pentecostal experience moved from Pentecostal denominations into Catholic, Anglican, and Methodist churches in the 1960s and 70s. Read his account of what changed and what didn&rsquo;t.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">You attended Ascend Church Atlanta &mdash; a charismatic/prophetic congregation &mdash; and came home feeling more grounded in your own quieter contemplative access to God. Anderson would say this is a legitimate outcome: the charismatic encounter clarified rather than replaced your own mode of access. Write your theological assessment of the Atlanta experience now, with more distance.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Jonathan Edwards&rsquo; test for genuine revival: Does it produce greater love for God? Greater love for neighbor? Greater humility? Greater engagement with Scripture? Greater concern for the lost? Apply these five tests to your Atlanta experience. Write your honest evaluation against each.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Wesleyan pneumatology &mdash; how Wesley thought about the Spirit</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Ezekiel 36:26&ndash;27<br><em>&ldquo;I will give you a new heart and put a new spirit in you&hellip; I will put my Spirit in you and move you to follow my decrees.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The Spirit in the Wesleyan tradition is primarily the agent of sanctification &mdash; the one who enables holy living &mdash; not primarily the source of spectacular gifts. What does this emphasis protect?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Randy Maddox, <em>Responsible Grace</em>, Chapter 8: &ldquo;The Holy Spirit and Sanctification.&rdquo; Maddox traces Wesley&rsquo;s pneumatology &mdash; his theology of the Spirit &mdash; which was deeply influenced by Eastern Orthodox theologies of <em>theosis</em> (participation in the divine nature). Read his account of how Wesley integrated the Spirit&rsquo;s transforming work with the Wesleyan concern for holiness.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Maddox argues Wesley&rsquo;s pneumatology is more Eastern than Western &mdash; the Spirit as the one who makes us participants in the divine nature (2 Peter 1:4) rather than primarily the one who gives us power for ministry. How does this framing change the questions you ask about the Spirit? Write: what is the Spirit primarily doing in your life right now &mdash; power or transformation?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Write a two-page personal theological position paper: &ldquo;Where I land on the gifts of the Spirit.&rdquo; Cover: your hermeneutical basis (how you interpret the NT evidence), your personal experience (including Atlanta), your Wesleyan framework, and what you remain genuinely uncertain about. Be honest about the uncertainty. Sign it. Date it.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Week synthesis &mdash; holding the charismatic and the contemplative</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 1 Corinthians 14:1<br><em>&ldquo;Follow the way of love and eagerly desire gifts of the Spirit, especially prophecy.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Both &mdash; love and gifts, contemplative pursuit and eager desire. Paul does not force a choice. What does holding both look like in practice?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your journal from this unit and the Atlanta experience notes you wrote at the time. Then re-read Reeves on the Spirit from Year II, Course 2.1. How has your understanding of the Spirit developed across the curriculum?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write one full page: &ldquo;My pneumatology after Atlanta, after this course, and after two years of formation.&rdquo; Not a position paper &mdash; a narrative. How has your understanding of the Spirit changed? What has been confirmed? What has been corrected? What are you still working out?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: one specific way you will remain open to the Spirit this week that your natural temperament resists. Name it. Try it. Write what happened.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 5</span>
        <span class="week-title">Course 2.2 synthesis &mdash; the church through history</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The church in each age &mdash; what history teaches</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Matthew 16:18<br><em>&ldquo;On this rock I will build my church, and the gates of Hades will not overcome it.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The church has survived persecution, corruption, schism, and betrayal &mdash; and perpetrated some of these. What does its survival say about its foundation?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> González, <em>The Story of Christianity, Vol. 2</em>, Epilogue: González reflects on what the story of Christianity teaches. Read his concluding account of the church as a flawed but persistent witness to a God who does not abandon his purposes.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">G.K. Chesterton: &lsquo;Christianity has not been tried and found wanting; it has been found difficult and left untried.&rsquo; Write your response. Has the church been faithful to its charter? Where has it failed most spectacularly? Where has it succeeded against the odds? What does its mixed record say about the God it claims to represent?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray for the church &mdash; universal and local. Name three specific ways your own local community is failing to be the church. Pray for each one. Then name three specific ways it is genuinely being the church. Give thanks for each.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The ecumenical question &mdash; what unity requires</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> John 17:22&ndash;23<br><em>&ldquo;That they may be one as we are one.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Jesus prays for unity before the cross. 2,000 years later there are 40,000 Protestant denominations. What does this prayer require of you today specifically?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Miroslav Volf, <em>After Our Likeness</em>, Chapter 3: &ldquo;Unity in Trinitarian Perspective.&rdquo; Volf argues that the unity Jesus prays for is not uniformity but the diverse unity that characterizes Trinitarian life &mdash; distinct persons in genuine communion. Read his account of what ecumenism requires.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write your honest theology of Christian unity: what must all Christians hold in common, what are legitimate differences, what makes a community genuinely the church. Then: what does genuine charity toward Christians with whom you significantly disagree require of you practically in the next week?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray John 17 as your own prayer for the church. Sit in silence for 10 minutes after. Write one sentence about what praying for unity feels like when you hold the church&rsquo;s divisions in mind simultaneously.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Course 2.2 synthesis &mdash; history as teacher</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Hebrews 12:1<br><em>&ldquo;Since we are surrounded by such a great cloud of witnesses, let us throw off everything that hinders.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The cloud of witnesses includes Luther, Calvin, Wesley, the Anabaptists, and the Pentecostals. What do they together ask of you?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read all of your Course 2.2 journal &mdash; the Reformation, the Wesleyan Revival, the Pentecostal movement. Identify the five most significant formations across the whole course. Write one sentence on each.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Course 2.2 synthesis essay: &ldquo;What the history of Christianity has done to my faith.&rdquo; Two full pages. Cover: how the Reformation has shaped your relationship to Scripture, how the Wesleyan Revival has shaped your social conscience, how the Pentecostal movement has shaped your pneumatology, and what you have received from the ecumenical church. Write in your own voice.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: one thing church history has permanently changed about how you see your faith. Write one paragraph.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Entering Year III &mdash; what you bring forward</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 2 Corinthians 4:7<br><em>&ldquo;We have this treasure in jars of clay to show that this all-surpassing power is from God and not from us.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. You are a jar of clay carrying the weight of two years of theological formation. What is the treasure? What is the clay? Write honestly.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your Year I synthesis essay and your Year II synthesis essay (if written). Read them as if reading someone else&rsquo;s account. What has changed between the person who wrote Year I and the person who is about to enter Year III?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write one page: &ldquo;Who I am theologically as I enter Year III.&rdquo; What do I know? What am I still uncertain about? What has changed? What has held firm? What am I most hungry for in the third year? Write it as a letter to the Trevor who will read it at the beginning of Year III.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray for the third year &mdash; for what God will do in it, for the courage to engage it fully, for the humility to be changed by it. Sit in silence for 15 minutes after praying. Write one sentence about what you hope Year III does in you.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Year II synthesis &mdash; deepening complete</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Romans 11:33<br><em>&ldquo;Oh, the depth of the riches of the wisdom and knowledge of God! How unsearchable his judgments, and his paths beyond tracing out!&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times. Two years of theological study &mdash; and this is the landing place. Awe. Write: what have you learned that has made you more in awe?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read the entirety of your Year II journal. All four courses. Identify the five most significant formations of the year. Write one sentence on each. Then write what Year II asked of you that Year I didn&rsquo;t.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Year II synthesis essay: &ldquo;What Year II has done in me.&rdquo; Two full pages. Cover: how systematic theology has deepened your doctrine of God, how church history has expanded your sense of the tradition, how the Pentecostal unit has clarified your pneumatology, and what Year II as a whole has changed in how you live. Write for your future self.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Year II Examen: Re-read all Weekly Examens from Year II. What pattern do you see? What has been consistent? Write a paragraph. Then sit in 20 minutes of silence as your final act of Year II.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div></div>
<div id="y2-c23" class="course-section" style="display:none;"><div class="course-divider">Course 2.3 &mdash; Spiritual Direction and the Interior Life</div><div class="unit-label" style="margin-top:2rem;">Unit 1 &middot; 2 Weeks</div><div class="unit-title">What Is Spiritual Direction</div><div class="unit-desc">David Benner and Margaret Guenther on the ancient practice of being accompanied on the interior journey. Not therapy, not counseling, not mentoring &mdash; something older and more specifically spiritual.</div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 1</span>
        <span class="week-title">The practice and its theology</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">What spiritual direction is &mdash; and what it is not</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 1 Samuel 3:1&ndash;10<br>Eli and Samuel. <em>&ldquo;Go, lie down, and if he calls you, say, &lsquo;Speak, Lord, for your servant is listening.&rsquo;&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Eli&rsquo;s role: helping Samuel learn to recognize the voice of God. This is spiritual direction. What is the difference between what Eli does and what a therapist does?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> David Benner, <em>Sacred Companions</em>, Chapters 1&ndash;2: &ldquo;The Nature of Spiritual Friendship&rdquo; and &ldquo;Spiritual Direction.&rdquo; Benner carefully distinguishes spiritual direction from counseling, mentoring, and discipleship. Read his account of what is unique about the spiritual direction relationship.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Benner argues that spiritual direction is primarily about helping someone pay attention to God &mdash; not solving their problems, not teaching them doctrine, not holding them accountable. The director asks: &lsquo;Where is God in this?&rsquo; Write: what does this narrow focus reveal about what is hardest in the spiritual life? Why do we need help paying attention to God?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Think of a person in your life who most consistently helps you pay attention to God. Not the most knowledgeable, the most impressive, or the most productive &mdash; the one in whose presence you are most aware of God. Write one paragraph about them. What do they do that produces this?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The director&rsquo;s posture &mdash; listening as a spiritual act</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Ecclesiastes 5:1&ndash;2<br><em>&ldquo;Guard your steps when you go to the house of God. Go near to listen rather than to offer the sacrifice of fools.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Listening is the primary posture. What makes genuine listening different from waiting to speak?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Margaret Guenther, <em>Holy Listening</em>, Chapter 1: &ldquo;The Spiritual Director as Host.&rdquo; Guenther&rsquo;s image: the director as a host who creates space for the guest (the directee) to arrive fully. Read her account of what holy listening requires of the one who listens.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Guenther argues that most listening in ordinary life is agenda-driven &mdash; we listen for what confirms our view, what will help us respond, what we need to know. Holy listening is presence without agenda. Write: who in your life listens to you this way? What does it feel like to be listened to without an agenda?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Practice: For your next significant conversation, commit to 10 minutes of genuine listening &mdash; no planning your response while they speak, no redirecting to your own experience, no problem-solving until they invite it. Write afterward: what did you notice about the person that you would have missed otherwise?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The directee&rsquo;s posture &mdash; bringing your whole self</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Psalm 62:8<br><em>&ldquo;Pour out your hearts to him, for God is our refuge.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Pouring out the heart &mdash; not a carefully curated presentation but the whole of what is inside. What keeps you from pouring out rather than presenting?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> David Benner, <em>Sacred Companions</em>, Chapter 4: &ldquo;Preparing to Receive Spiritual Direction.&rdquo; Benner traces what the directee brings to the relationship &mdash; not just problems and questions but the full texture of their life with God. Read his account of how to prepare for a direction session.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Benner argues the most important thing a directee brings is honesty about their actual experience &mdash; not their best experience, not their aspirational experience, their actual experience. Write: where do you tend to curate your spiritual self-presentation? What do you usually leave out when describing your spiritual life? Write it now, for yourself.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Practice: Write as if writing to a spiritual director right now. Tell the truth about your interior life in this season &mdash; what is alive, what is dry, what you are avoiding, what God seems to be doing. Don&rsquo;t edit for an audience. Write for 15 minutes. This is your spiritual direction session on paper.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The classic texts of direction &mdash; what the tradition has to say</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Proverbs 11:14<br><em>&ldquo;For lack of guidance a nation falls, but victory is won through many advisers.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The wisdom tradition values counsel &mdash; the recognition that no one sees themselves clearly without the help of another. What has kept you from seeking this kind of accompaniment?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Guenther, <em>Holy Listening</em>, Chapter 2: &ldquo;The Spiritual Director as Midwife.&rdquo; Guenther&rsquo;s second image: the director as one who assists in the birth of what God is bringing forth in the directee. Read her account of what the midwife does and doesn&rsquo;t do &mdash; never forcing, always assisting.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Guenther argues that spiritual direction is inherently about birth &mdash; something new is always trying to emerge. What is trying to be born in you right now in your life with God? Not what you are trying to produce &mdash; what seems to be pushing up from underneath, wanting to emerge? Write honestly.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Consider seeking out a spiritual director &mdash; a real person, not AI, not a mentor, but someone trained in the practice of holy listening. Spend 15 minutes researching spiritual directors in Austin or available online. Write who you found and what step you will take.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Week synthesis &mdash; being accompanied</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Ecclesiastes 4:9&ndash;10<br><em>&ldquo;Two are better than one&hellip; If either of them falls down, one can help the other up. But pity anyone who falls and has no one to help them up.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. What does the wisdom tradition assume about human self-sufficiency? What does it say about your need for another in the spiritual life?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your notes from this week. Then re-read your journal entry from Thursday &mdash; the spiritual direction session on paper. Read it as if reading someone else&rsquo;s account. What do you notice from the outside that you didn&rsquo;t notice from the inside?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write one full page: &ldquo;What I need from spiritual accompaniment.&rdquo; Not what you think you should need &mdash; what you actually need. What questions keep arising that you have no one to bring them to? What aspects of your interior life are going unattended because you are attending them alone? What would regular spiritual direction do for you?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: one concrete step toward securing genuine spiritual accompaniment in your life. Write it. Do it.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 2</span>
        <span class="week-title">The content of direction &mdash; what gets attended to</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">God-images &mdash; the unconscious theology we actually operate from</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Isaiah 40:28&ndash;31<br><em>&ldquo;Do you not know? Have you not heard? The Lord is the everlasting God, the Creator of the ends of the earth. He will not grow tired or weary.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. What comes into your mind when you picture &lsquo;the Lord&rsquo; specifically &mdash; not what you believe doctrinally, but what the mind produces unbidden?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> David Benner, <em>Sacred Companions</em>, Chapter 5: &ldquo;God-Images.&rdquo; Benner argues that our actual operating image of God &mdash; the one that generates our emotional and behavioral responses &mdash; is often very different from our stated theology. Spiritual direction attends to the image beneath the doctrine. Read his account of how to surface these images.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Benner traces four common distorted God-images: the Cosmic Judge, the Divine Vending Machine, the Indifferent Watchmaker, and the Angry Father. Write honestly: which distorted images have been most operative in your history with God? Not your theology &mdash; the emotional responses that surface in prayer, guilt, and crisis. Which image generates those responses?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Spiritual direction exercise: Sit in silence for 15 minutes and invite God to meet you. Notice what arises &mdash; relief, fear, obligation, warmth, distance. Don&rsquo;t evaluate the feelings &mdash; note them. Write afterward: what did your emotional response reveal about your operating God-image today?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Consolation and desolation &mdash; Ignatius&rsquo;s diagnostic tools</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Lamentations 3:17&ndash;21<br>The movement from desolation (<em>&ldquo;I have been deprived of peace; I have forgotten what prosperity is&rdquo;</em>) to hope (<em>&ldquo;Yet this I call to mind and therefore I have hope.&rdquo;</em>). Read it three times. What is the nature of the movement? What produces it?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Dallas Willard, <em>Hearing God</em>, Chapter 5: &ldquo;Recognizing the Voice of God.&rdquo; Willard integrates Ignatian consolation/desolation with a Wesleyan pneumatology. Read his account of how to distinguish the Spirit&rsquo;s prompting from desire, imagination, and habit.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Ignatius defines consolation as any movement of the soul toward God (love, peace, increased faith, joy in God). Desolation is movement away from God (darkness, confusion, disturbance, drawing toward earthly things). These are not happiness and sadness &mdash; they are interior spiritual movements. Write: trace the consolations and desolations of the past 48 hours.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Ignatian rule: make no major decisions during desolation. Examine the desolation itself (what produced it? what is God doing in it?) rather than acting on its impulses. Think of a current decision you are facing. What is the quality of your interior state as you consider it? Write the consolation/desolation map of your current decision landscape.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Prayer in direction &mdash; what the Spirit is doing</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Romans 8:26<br><em>&ldquo;The Spirit helps us in our weakness. We do not know what we ought to pray for, but the Spirit himself intercedes for us through wordless groans.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The Spirit prays in us when we don&rsquo;t know how. What does spiritual direction do with this pneumatological reality?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Guenther, <em>Holy Listening</em>, Chapter 4: &ldquo;Prayer in Direction.&rdquo; Guenther traces how prayer functions inside the direction relationship &mdash; both as content (what is the directee&rsquo;s prayer life like?) and as method (praying together in the session). Read her account of how prayer transforms the direction encounter.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Guenther argues that the direction session itself should be permeated with prayer &mdash; the director listening not just to the directee but to the Spirit, asking &lsquo;What is God doing here?&rsquo; rather than &lsquo;What should I say?&rsquo; Write: what would it mean to bring this quality of Spirit-listening to your ordinary conversations this week?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Practice: In your next significant conversation, silently ask &lsquo;Lord, what are you doing in this person?&rsquo; before you respond. Hold the question throughout the exchange. Write afterward: what did you notice that you would not have noticed without the question?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Bringing your life to direction &mdash; work, relationships, and vocation</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Colossians 3:23<br><em>&ldquo;Whatever you do, work at it with all your heart, as working for the Lord, not for human masters.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Spiritual direction attends to the whole of life, not just the &lsquo;religious&rsquo; parts. What would it mean to bring your sales work, your Greenline project, your relationship with Dana to direction?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Benner, <em>Sacred Companions</em>, Chapter 6: &ldquo;The Scope of Spiritual Direction.&rdquo; Benner argues that everything &mdash; relationships, work, sexuality, money, dreams, fears, bodies &mdash; is material for spiritual direction because all of it is the place where God is working and the person is responding or resisting. Read his account of what &lsquo;the spiritual&rsquo; includes.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Benner argues that we fragment our lives into spiritual and secular at the cost of genuine integration. What aspect of your life do you currently treat as outside the scope of God&rsquo;s direct concern &mdash; too mundane, too complicated, too embarrassing, or too secular to bring to prayer? Name it. Then write: what would it mean to bring it fully into your life with God?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Bring your work week to God for 15 minutes. Not as a to-do list of prayer requests &mdash; as a space where God is present and active. Your cold calls, your pipeline, your Greenline projects. Ask: &lsquo;Lord, what are you doing in my work?&rsquo; Sit with the question in silence. Write what emerged.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Unit 1 synthesis &mdash; the gift of accompaniment</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Job 2:11&ndash;13<br>Job&rsquo;s three friends come and sit with him in silence for seven days before they speak. Read it three times. For seven days, they simply accompany. It is only when they begin to explain that they fail him. What does this say about what accompaniment is and what it isn&rsquo;t?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your journal from both weeks. Then re-read Benner&rsquo;s account of what the directee brings. Ask: what have I been bringing to God and what have I been leaving out? Write a specific account.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write one full page: &ldquo;What I am learning about my interior life through this unit.&rdquo; Not doctrine &mdash; observation. What patterns in your life with God have you noticed over two weeks of attention? What is arising? What is receding? What does God seem to be pressing on?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: one commitment about your interior life you are making as a result of this unit. Write it. Begin it.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div><div class="unit-label" style="margin-top:2rem;">Unit 2 &middot; 3 Weeks</div><div class="unit-title">Discernment: Hearing God in Ordinary Life</div><div class="unit-desc">Dallas Willard on the voice of God. Ignatius&rsquo;s Rules for Discernment applied to your actual life. The integration of everything you have learned about the Spirit&rsquo;s work.</div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 3</span>
        <span class="week-title">What discernment is &mdash; and how it works</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">God speaks &mdash; the foundational conviction</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> John 10:27<br><em>&ldquo;My sheep listen to my voice; I know them, and they follow me.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Jesus assumes his followers can hear his voice. This is not reserved for mystics or prophets. What keeps ordinary Christians from hearing? What does &lsquo;hearing&rsquo; actually mean?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Dallas Willard, <em>Hearing God</em>, Chapters 1&ndash;2: &ldquo;A Paradox About Hearing God&rdquo; and &ldquo;Guidelines for Hearing from God.&rdquo; Willard argues that hearing God is the normal expectation for the Christian life &mdash; not occasional mystical experience but ongoing conversational relationship. Read his account of what this means and what it doesn&rsquo;t.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Willard distinguishes between believing God speaks (doctrinal position) and actually expecting to hear God (lived posture). Many people hold the former without the latter. Write honestly: do you actually expect to hear God &mdash; not just in Scripture but in the texture of your ordinary life? What would change if you genuinely expected it?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Practice: For the next 24 hours, keep a log of every moment when something might be the Spirit&rsquo;s prompting &mdash; a thought about a person, an impulse to do something, a sense of peace or discomfort in a decision. Don&rsquo;t evaluate whether it &lsquo;really was&rsquo; God. Just notice and write. Review the log tonight.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The modes of God&rsquo;s communication &mdash; Scripture, inner voice, circumstance</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Proverbs 3:5&ndash;6<br><em>&ldquo;Trust in the Lord with all your heart and lean not on your own understanding; in all your ways submit to him, and he will make your paths straight.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Note: it says <em>make your paths straight</em> &mdash; not <em>make your path obvious in advance.</em> What does trust look like when the path is not obvious?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Dallas Willard, <em>Hearing God</em>, Chapter 4: &ldquo;The Still Small Voice.&rdquo; Willard traces the primary modes through which God communicates &mdash; Scripture, the inner voice, circumstances, the body&rsquo;s wisdom, other people, dreams &mdash; and gives criteria for evaluating each. Read his account of the &lsquo;still small voice&rsquo; in Elijah&rsquo;s experience.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Willard argues that God&rsquo;s primary mode of communication is the inner voice &mdash; not audible, but personally and clearly addressed. He distinguishes this from subconscious impulse, wishful thinking, and demonic suggestion by its content (consistent with Scripture and Christ&rsquo;s character), its quality (peace, clarity, freedom), and its effect (love and growth). Apply these three criteria to something you have sensed God saying to you recently.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Review the 24-hour log from Monday. Apply Willard&rsquo;s three criteria to each entry. Which seem consistent with the character of the God you have been studying? Which might be desire, anxiety, or habit? Write your honest evaluation of the log.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Ignatian discernment &mdash; the rules applied to real decisions</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> James 1:5<br><em>&ldquo;If any of you lacks wisdom, you should ask God, who gives generously to all without finding fault, and it will be given to you.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Wisdom is available by asking. What is the relationship between asking for wisdom and the careful rational work of discernment?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Dallas Willard, <em>Hearing God</em>, Chapter 8: &ldquo;Recognizing the Voice of God.&rdquo; Willard integrates Ignatian discernment with a Protestant account of divine guidance. Read his account of the Ignatian first, second, and third time of decision (direct inner certainty, consolation/desolation tracking, careful rational deliberation).</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Apply Ignatian discernment to a real decision you currently face &mdash; not a trivial one. Run the Three Times: (1) Is there a deep and settled certainty about one direction? (2) When you imaginatively inhabit each option, which produces consolation (movement toward God) and which desolation? (3) What does careful rational analysis suggest? Write your discernment across all three.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Sit in silence for 15 minutes holding your current decision open before God. Don&rsquo;t try to decide &mdash; just attend. Notice what arises when you are not pressing. Write: what was present in the silence that was not present in your rational analysis?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Community as the corrective &mdash; discernment is never alone</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Proverbs 15:22<br><em>&ldquo;Plans fail for lack of counsel, but with many advisers they succeed.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Individual discernment is necessary but not sufficient. What community structures do you currently have for your major decisions? What is missing?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Benner, <em>Sacred Companions</em>, Chapter 7: &ldquo;Spiritual Direction and Discernment.&rdquo; Benner argues that spiritual direction is inherently discernment-oriented &mdash; the director helps the directee read what God is doing and respond appropriately. Read his account of how direction and discernment are interlocked.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wesleyan discernment was communal: the class meeting, the band, the society. Decisions were not made in isolation but were tested against the community&rsquo;s wisdom. Write honestly: who currently has access to your decision-making process? Not for approval &mdash; for perspective, for correction, for the wisdom that community provides. Who is missing?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Name one major decision you are carrying alone that would benefit from community discernment. Write who specifically you will bring it to, and by when. Then write why you have been carrying it alone.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Unit 2 Week 1 synthesis &mdash; the discerning life</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Philippians 1:9&ndash;10<br><em>&ldquo;And this is my prayer: that your love may abound more and more in knowledge and depth of insight, so that you may be able to discern what is best.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Paul prays for discernment rooted in love, not mere intelligence. What is the relationship between love and clarity?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your discernment work from this week. Review the 24-hour log, the Ignatian three-times exercise, and the journal from Friday. What pattern do you see across these practices?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write one page: &ldquo;What discernment is teaching me about how God speaks.&rdquo; Not doctrine &mdash; experience. What have you noticed this week in your own interior life that you had not noticed before? What does God seem to be saying most consistently across the different modes you have attended to?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: one practice from this unit you will carry into the rest of the curriculum. Name it. Begin it.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 4</span>
        <span class="week-title">Discernment in practice &mdash; the specific disciplines</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The examen as daily discernment</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Psalm 26:2<br><em>&ldquo;Test me, Lord, and try me, examine my heart and my mind.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The psalmist invites examination &mdash; not self-examination alone but God-initiated searching. How is the examen different from self-analysis?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Dallas Willard, <em>Hearing God</em>, Chapter 9: &ldquo;Guidance, Scripture, and the Church.&rdquo; Willard argues that the examen &mdash; the daily review of where God was present and where the self resisted &mdash; is one of the primary practices for developing spiritual discernment over time. Read his account of how the examen trains attention.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">The examen in five movements: (1) Awareness of God&rsquo;s presence. (2) Gratitude for the day. (3) Review the day with the Spirit as guide. (4) Face what is difficult. (5) Look to tomorrow. Write: which movement is most natural to you? Which do you most typically skip? What does the pattern reveal?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Do a full five-movement examen now, taking three minutes per movement. Write your examen in your journal. Then: what did this structured review surface that your usual end-of-day self-review misses?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Vocation and discernment &mdash; what you are called to</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Jeremiah 1:5<br><em>&ldquo;Before I formed you in the womb I knew you, before you were born I set you apart; I appointed you as a prophet to the nations.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Calling is named before formation is complete. What does it mean that vocation precedes full understanding of it?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Benner, <em>Sacred Companions</em>, Chapter 8: &ldquo;Soul-Care and Vocation.&rdquo; Benner argues that spiritual direction is inherently vocational &mdash; it helps people hear and live into their specific calling rather than a generic Christian life. Read his account of how direction attends to the unique person God has made.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Frederick Buechner&rsquo;s definition of vocation: &lsquo;The place where your deep gladness and the world&rsquo;s deep hunger meet.&rsquo; Write your honest account of both halves. Where is your deep gladness? (Not what you think should gladden you &mdash; what actually does.) Where is the world&rsquo;s deep hunger that you are positioned to address? Write the intersection.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Sit in silence for 15 minutes holding the question: <em>What am I specifically called to, that only I can do?</em> Not a career question &mdash; a calling question. Write what surfaces, however incomplete or confusing.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Resistance and discernment &mdash; what the resistance reveals</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Jonah 1:1&ndash;3<br><em>&ldquo;But Jonah ran away from the Lord and headed for Tarshish.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Jonah knew the call and ran in the opposite direction. What does resistance to discernment reveal about the nature of the call? What does running reveal about the runner?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Willard, <em>Hearing God</em>, Chapter 10: &ldquo;Obedience and the Voice of God.&rdquo; Willard argues that discernment and obedience are inseparable &mdash; you hear God&rsquo;s voice more clearly as you obey it, and its clarity diminishes as you resist. Read his account of what sustained resistance does to the capacity for discernment.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Willard&rsquo;s warning: sustained disobedience clouds discernment &mdash; not as punishment but as natural consequence, the way sustained inattention to any voice eventually causes you to stop hearing it. Where in your life is there sustained resistance to something God has clearly said? Write honestly. Not general areas &mdash; one specific clear thing.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray Jonah&rsquo;s prayer from inside the fish (Jonah 2:1&ndash;9). Pray it as your own, using Jonah&rsquo;s situation as a template for your own experience of running and returning. Then sit in silence for 10 minutes. Write one sentence about what it is like to pray from inside the whale.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Integrating everything &mdash; the discerning life as a whole</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Isaiah 30:21<br><em>&ldquo;Whether you turn to the right or to the left, your ears will hear a voice behind you, saying, &lsquo;This is the way; walk in it.&rsquo;&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. A voice behind you &mdash; not in front, showing the whole path. Just one step: this is the way, walk in it. What does this say about the nature of divine guidance?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read all of your Course 2.3 journal. Identify the five most significant formations from the whole course &mdash; from spiritual direction through to discernment. Write one sentence on each.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Course 2.3 synthesis essay: &ldquo;What I have learned about my interior life and God&rsquo;s voice.&rdquo; Two full pages. Cover: what spiritual direction has opened for you, what discernment practices you have learned and which you will use, what God-images you have discovered and what needs to shift, and what the examen has begun to reveal. Write in your own voice &mdash; this is the most personal essay of the curriculum.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: one practice from Course 2.3 that you will carry as a permanent part of your Rule of Life. Name it. Write what it will look like in practice.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Unit 2 and Course 2.3 final synthesis</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Psalm 25:4&ndash;5<br><em>&ldquo;Show me your ways, Lord, teach me your paths. Guide me in your truth and teach me, for you are God my Savior, and my hope is in you all day long.&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times. Three verbs: show, teach, guide. This is the discernment posture. Write: what is the difference between these three and how does each apply to where you are right now?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Final re-read: Willard, <em>Hearing God</em>, Epilogue. Read Willard&rsquo;s conclusion to the whole book. Then read Benner&rsquo;s conclusion to <em>Sacred Companions.</em> Let the two together frame the interior life you are building.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write one final page for Course 2.3: &ldquo;The interior life I am taking into Year III.&rdquo; What do you know about yourself as one who is being directed by the Spirit? What has become clear? What remains opaque? What are you carrying into the third year with greater confidence?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Sit in 20 minutes of silence as your final act of Course 2.3. No agenda, no petition, no examen. Simply be present to God who is present to you. Afterward, write one sentence &mdash; not what you thought or felt, what was there.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 5</span>
        <span class="week-title">Year II final integration</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Synthesis review &mdash; all of Year II</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 2 Corinthians 3:18<br><em>&ldquo;We all, who with unveiled faces contemplate the Lord&rsquo;s glory, are being transformed into his image with ever-increasing glory.&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times. The promise beneath two years of formation. Are you more transformed? In what ways? Write honestly before you do anything else.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your Year I and Year II synthesis essays. Read them as if reading someone else&rsquo;s account of their formation. What has changed? What is recognizably continuous? Write a paragraph about the person who wrote Year I and the person reading it now.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write one full page: &ldquo;What two years of formation has done.&rdquo; Not what you know &mdash; what has changed in who you are. Your doctrine, your prayer, your relationships, your work, your conscience. Don&rsquo;t perform. Write what is actually true.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Sit in 20 minutes of silence as your transition into Year III. No agenda. Just presence. Write one word afterward that names where you are.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div></div>
</section><section id="y3" class="section">
  <div id="y3-c31" class="course-section">
    <div class="course-divider">Course 3.1 &mdash; Christian Ethics</div>
    <div class="unit-label" style="margin-top:1rem;">Unit 1 &middot; 3 Weeks</div>
    <div class="unit-title">The Sermon on the Mount as Ethical Vision</div>
    <div class="unit-desc">Dallas Willard&rsquo;s argument that the Beatitudes are not ideals we fail to reach but descriptions of the life available to us now. Matthew 5&ndash;7 as the curriculum of the Kingdom.</div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 1</span>
        <span class="week-title">The Beatitudes &mdash; the blessed life redefined</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Blessed are the poor in spirit &mdash; the upside-down Kingdom</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Matthew 5:1&ndash;12<br>The Beatitudes. Read them slowly, three times. Do not rush to interpret. Let the rhythm of <em>&ldquo;blessed are&rdquo;</em> accumulate. Who is blessed according to Jesus? Notice that not one of the qualities he names is a virtue in ordinary human accounting. What word or phrase stays with you?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Dallas Willard, <em>The Divine Conspiracy</em>, Chapter 4: &ldquo;Who Is Really Well Off? The Beatitudes.&rdquo; Willard&rsquo;s key argument: the Beatitudes are not conditions for blessing but announcements that every human situation &mdash; even the worst &mdash; is one in which the Kingdom of God is accessible. Read his full treatment of &ldquo;blessed are the poor in spirit.&rdquo;</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Willard argues Jesus is not saying <em>if you are poor in spirit, you will eventually be blessed</em> &mdash; he is saying <em>the Kingdom of God is yours right now, even in your poverty of spirit.</em> What does it mean for your poverty of spirit today &mdash; wherever it is &mdash; to be a place God&rsquo;s Kingdom is already available?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Choose the Beatitude that is hardest for you to receive &mdash; not hardest to practice, hardest to believe is true of you. Sit with it for 10 minutes. Say it slowly as a personal declaration: <em>&ldquo;I am blessed.&rdquo;</em> Write one paragraph about the resistance you feel.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Salt, light, and the public dimension of holiness</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Matthew 5:13&ndash;16<br><em>&ldquo;You are the salt of the earth. You are the light of the world.&rdquo;</em> Present tense &mdash; not &ldquo;become&rdquo; but &ldquo;are.&rdquo; The city on a hill cannot be hidden. What does it mean to be a light not by trying to be visible but by simply being what you are?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Dallas Willard, <em>The Divine Conspiracy</em>, Chapter 5: &ldquo;The Kingdom Suffers Violence.&rdquo; Willard addresses the &ldquo;gospel of sin management&rdquo; &mdash; a version of Christianity concerned only with getting sins forgiven rather than with the life transformation that is actually available. This is a crucial chapter for Wesleyan ethics.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Willard distinguishes between a gospel that only addresses the afterlife and one that addresses the whole of life now. Wesley made the same point in a different vocabulary. What would it mean for your work in sales, in building Greenline, in your relationship with Dana &mdash; for those to be places of Kingdom life rather than secular life interrupted occasionally by spiritual life?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Wesley&rsquo;s sermon &ldquo;The Use of Money&rdquo;: earn all you can, save all you can, give all you can. Today: take 15 minutes to honestly assess where your money is going. Not to produce guilt &mdash; to produce clarity. Write one sentence about one financial habit you want to align more closely with the Kingdom.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">You have heard it said &mdash; the deeper law</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Matthew 5:21&ndash;32<br><em>&ldquo;You have heard it said&hellip; but I say to you.&rdquo;</em> Jesus radicalizes the Law inward. Murder begins with contempt. Adultery begins with the cultivated look. Read it three times. Jesus is not making the law harder &mdash; he is showing where it was always pointing. What does this do to your understanding of sin?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Dallas Willard, <em>The Divine Conspiracy</em>, Chapter 6: &ldquo;The Good Person and the Good Heart.&rdquo; Willard argues Jesus&rsquo;s antitheses (you have heard it said / but I say) are not new rules to follow but a diagnosis of the heart from which behavior flows. Transformation of the heart &mdash; not management of behavior &mdash; is the point. This is classically Wesleyan.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Willard and Wesley both locate the problem below behavior &mdash; in the will, the affections, the habit-patterns of the heart. What is one area of your life where you have been managing behavior without addressing the underlying formation? Be specific. What would address the root rather than the symptom?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Examen of contempt: Review the last 48 hours. Where did you feel contempt &mdash; toward a person, a situation, yourself? Name each instance. Then pray Matthew 5:22 as a diagnostic, not a condemnation. What does Jesus want to do with your contempt?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Love your enemies &mdash; the hardest command</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Matthew 5:43&ndash;48<br><em>&ldquo;Love your enemies and pray for those who persecute you, that you may be children of your Father in heaven.&rdquo;</em> Note the logic: the motivation for loving enemies is not that it works, but that it resembles the Father who causes rain to fall on the just and unjust alike. What word arrests you?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Wesley, Standard Sermon: &ldquo;The More Excellent Way.&rdquo; Wesley argues that love of enemies is not the summit of an elite spirituality &mdash; it is the baseline of the renewed life. Read the full sermon. Note his account of how love transforms not just our actions toward enemies but our perception of them.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wesley&rsquo;s &ldquo;perfect love&rdquo; asks something more than absence of bitterness &mdash; it asks for active love. The loss of your friendship with Caleb was processed with grounded clarity. But what would active love toward Caleb look like now? Not dramatic &mdash; small, specific, real. Write it honestly.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray for one person who has hurt you &mdash; specifically, by name, for five minutes. Not that they would realize their error. Pray for what they actually need. Pray for what God wants for them. This is one of the most demanding practices in the curriculum. Journal one sentence: what did it do in you?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Week synthesis &mdash; the Sermon on the Mount as your formation</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Matthew 7:24&ndash;27<br>The two builders. <em>&ldquo;Everyone who hears these words of mine and puts them into practice is like a wise man who built his house on the rock.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Hearing <em>and</em> practicing &mdash; both required. What does &ldquo;practice&rdquo; mean in the context of everything Jesus has said in chapters 5&ndash;7?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Timothy Keller, <em>Every Good Endeavor</em>, Chapter 1: &ldquo;The Design of Work.&rdquo; Keller argues work is a form of Kingdom participation &mdash; not a necessary evil but a calling. Read it alongside Willard&rsquo;s vision of the Kingdom pervading all of life.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Keller argues all legitimate work participates in the renewal of creation. Willard argues the Kingdom is available in every dimension of ordinary life. Wesley says holiness is social, not merely interior. Write one page: what would it look like for your work week &mdash; your calls, your pipeline, your Greenline projects &mdash; to be a site of Kingdom formation rather than an interruption of it?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences &mdash; one per quadrant. Then: one practice from the Sermon on the Mount you will carry into next week intentionally. Name it. Write it. Begin it Monday.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 2</span>
        <span class="week-title">Work, Money, and the Kingdom</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The Sermon on the Mount and money &mdash; treasure in heaven</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Matthew 6:19&ndash;34<br><em>&ldquo;Do not store up for yourselves treasures on earth&hellip; But seek first his kingdom and his righteousness, and all these things will be given to you as well.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The whole passage is about anxiety and provision. What word arrests you?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Timothy Keller, <em>Every Good Endeavor</em>, Chapter 7: &ldquo;Work Becomes Idolatry.&rdquo; Keller addresses how legitimate work becomes disordered when it provides identity, security, or worth. Read his account of how the gospel frees work from being the place where we find our fundamental meaning.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Keller identifies three ways work becomes idolatrous: when it provides identity (I am what I do), security (I am safe because of what I earn), or community (my colleagues are my real family). Which of these, if any, do you recognize in your relationship to your work? Write honestly, without performance.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Wesley&rsquo;s &ldquo;earn all you can, save all you can, give all you can&rdquo;: Apply each principle specifically to your current income and expenses. Not as a guilt exercise &mdash; as a Kingdom alignment exercise. What would change if you took Wesley&rsquo;s third principle as seriously as the first two?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Vocation &mdash; work as participation in new creation</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Genesis 2:15<br><em>&ldquo;The Lord God took the man and put him in the Garden of Eden to work it and take care of it.&rdquo;</em> Before the fall &mdash; work is the original vocation of the image-bearer, not the consequence of sin. Read it three times. What changes about how you see your Monday when you read this?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Timothy Keller, <em>Every Good Endeavor</em>, Chapter 2: &ldquo;Work as Cultivation.&rdquo; Keller argues that all legitimate work is a form of &ldquo;subduing the earth&rdquo; &mdash; bringing order, beauty, and fruitfulness out of raw material. A sales process, a landscaping project, a client relationship &mdash; all qualify.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Keller argues work participates in the renewal of creation. How does this theological claim change how you approach a cold call, a Greenline project, or the moment a client says yes? Is it possible to do your specific work in a way that expresses the image of God? Write a concrete answer &mdash; not abstract.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray over your work calendar for the coming week. Not for success &mdash; for God&rsquo;s Kingdom to be present in each meeting, call, and project. Name two specific interactions where you want to bring something more than competence. Write what that would look like.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Political theology &mdash; faith and the common good</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Jeremiah 29:4&ndash;7<br><em>&ldquo;Seek the peace and prosperity of the city to which I have carried you into exile. Pray to the Lord for it, because if it prospers, you too will prosper.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Israel is told to invest in the city of their captors. What does this say about how God&rsquo;s people relate to the broader social order?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Miroslav Volf, <em>A Public Faith</em>, Chapter 3: &ldquo;The Prophetic Church.&rdquo; Volf argues that Christian engagement with public life must be neither withdrawal nor dominance &mdash; but prophetic presence. Read his account of what it means to seek the flourishing of the city without collapsing into it.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Given your interest in geopolitics, monetary systems, and second-order thinking: what does a Wesleyan theological framework say to questions of economic justice and national power? Does your faith change your analysis &mdash; or merely provide a vocabulary for conclusions you&rsquo;d reach anyway? Write honestly.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray for Austin: specifically, for South Austin, for the neighborhood around you. Not for abstract flourishing &mdash; for something specific. One neighborhood need, one local injustice, one community you are part of. Write what you prayed.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Ethics of suffering &mdash; solidarity and the cross</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Matthew 25:31&ndash;46<br><em>&ldquo;Whatever you did for one of the least of these brothers and sisters of mine, you did for me.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Jesus identifies himself with the hungry, the stranger, the prisoner. What does this passage demand of you specifically &mdash; not in general, but in your actual life?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Martin Luther King Jr., <em>Letter from Birmingham Jail</em> (full text). Read the whole letter. It is one of the greatest pieces of Christian political theology written in English. Note King&rsquo;s use of Augustine, Aquinas, and Wesley. Note his argument about the &ldquo;white moderate.&rdquo; Read carefully and slowly.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">King distinguishes between a just and an unjust law, drawing on Aquinas. He argues the church has often been a thermometer reflecting the culture rather than a thermostat shaping it. Where is your faith a thermostat? Where is it a thermometer? Write with the same directness King used.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Matthew 25 act of obedience: Choose one concrete act of service toward &ldquo;the least of these&rdquo; that you will do this week. Not a donation &mdash; a presence. Write what it is. Do it before Saturday&rsquo;s session. Report back on Saturday.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Unit synthesis &mdash; Wesleyan ethics as whole-life formation</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Micah 6:8<br><em>&ldquo;He has shown you, O mortal, what is good. And what does the Lord require of you? To act justly and to love mercy and to walk humbly with your God.&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times. This is the whole of the Wesleyan ethical vision in one verse. What does each element ask of you right now, specifically?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your journal from these two weeks. Then read Wesley, Sermon: &ldquo;The Use of Money&rdquo; in full if you haven&rsquo;t already. Wesley&rsquo;s practical ethics about money is one of the most demanding and neglected parts of his teaching. Read it as a mirror.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Course 3.1 synthesis essay: &ldquo;What Wesleyan ethics asks of me.&rdquo; Two pages. Cover: the Sermon on the Mount as present-tense Kingdom availability, work as vocation and new creation participation, solidarity with the suffering, and the public dimension of holiness. Use specific examples from your own life. Make it a confession, not an essay.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Then: One ethical commitment you are making from this course &mdash; specific, measurable, durable. Not a feeling &mdash; a practice. Write it and sign it with today&rsquo;s date.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div id="y3-c32" class="course-section" style="display:none;"><div class="course-divider">Course 3.2 &mdash; Apologetics and Comparative Religion</div><div class="unit-label" style="margin-top:2rem;">Unit 1 &middot; 3 Weeks</div><div class="unit-title">The Resurrection: Historical Grounds for Christian Belief</div><div class="unit-desc">N.T. Wright and Gary Habermas on the historical case for the resurrection. Not merely a theological claim &mdash; a historical one that can be evaluated by normal historical methods.</div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 1</span>
        <span class="week-title">The historical case &mdash; what we can know</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Why the resurrection question matters</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 1 Corinthians 15:14&ndash;19<br><em>&ldquo;If Christ has not been raised, your faith is futile; you are still in your sins.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Paul does not say &lsquo;the resurrection is true for us spiritually.&rsquo; He says if it didn&rsquo;t happen, everything collapses. What is at stake in the physical, historical resurrection?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Gary Habermas &amp; Michael Licona, <em>The Case for the Resurrection of Jesus</em>, Chapters 1&ndash;2: &ldquo;The Resurrection: What&rsquo;s the Big Deal?&rdquo; and &ldquo;The Minimal Facts Approach.&rdquo; Habermas and Licona argue that the resurrection can be established using only facts granted by virtually all historians, including skeptical ones. Read their introduction carefully.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Habermas&rsquo;s minimal facts: (1) Jesus died by crucifixion. (2) His disciples believed they saw him risen. (3) Paul was converted by an appearance. (4) James, Jesus&rsquo;s skeptical brother, was converted by an appearance. (5) The tomb was empty. Write: which of these five do you find most evidentially significant, and why? Which would you want to explore further?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Write the five minimal facts from memory without looking. This is the beginning of a one-page Resurrection brief you will write by the end of this unit. Every day you will add to it. Today: write the first section, stating the minimal facts clearly in your own words.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The crucifixion &mdash; the fact that is certain</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Isaiah 53:7&ndash;9<br><em>&ldquo;He was led like a lamb to the slaughter&hellip; he was cut off from the land of the living.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Written 700 years before the crucifixion. Read it now knowing what happened. What do you notice?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Habermas &amp; Licona, <em>The Case for the Resurrection of Jesus</em>, Chapters 3&ndash;4: the death of Jesus and the post-resurrection appearances. Read their account of the historical evidence for the crucifixion &mdash; pagan, Jewish, and Christian sources &mdash; and their evaluation of alternative theories (swoon, hallucination, legend).</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Habermas and Licona evaluate each alternative to resurrection: (1) Jesus didn&rsquo;t die &mdash; swoon theory. (2) The disciples hallucinated. (3) The early accounts are legendary development. (4) Wrong tomb. Write a brief refutation of each theory, using only the minimal facts. Refutation should be less than two sentences per theory.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Add to your Resurrection brief: section 2 &mdash; &lsquo;The fact of the death: why alternative theories fail.&rsquo; Write it clearly enough that you could state it in a 5-minute conversation.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The empty tomb &mdash; what it establishes</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> John 20:1&ndash;10<br>Mary and the disciples find the empty tomb. Read it three times. Note what John describes: the linen wrappings lying there, the face cloth folded separately. These are not the hallmarks of a made-up story. What does the specific, mundane detail suggest about the account?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> N.T. Wright, <em>The Resurrection of the Son of God</em>, Part V summary: &ldquo;The Empty Tomb and the Risen Body.&rdquo; Wright argues that the empty tomb alone proves nothing &mdash; but combined with the appearances, it creates a cumulative historical case that has no plausible non-resurrection explanation. Read his summary carefully.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wright argues that the Jewish category of resurrection was specific: bodily, physical, at the end of the age for all people together. The early Christians proclaimed a resurrection that violated all three elements &mdash; one person, in the middle of history, with a transformed but physical body. Write: why does the specificity of the resurrection claim matter for its historical evaluation?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Add to your Resurrection brief: section 3 &mdash; &lsquo;The empty tomb: what it does and doesn&rsquo;t prove.&rsquo; Write it as a clear, brief argument.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The appearances &mdash; the evidence that is hardest to explain</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 1 Corinthians 15:3&ndash;8<br>The appearance list. Note: Paul writes this within 20&ndash;25 years of the events, citing a tradition he received within a few years. He names specific witnesses, most of whom are still alive. Read it three times. What does the specificity of the list suggest?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Habermas &amp; Licona, <em>The Case for the Resurrection of Jesus</em>, Chapters 5&ndash;6: the appearances and the conversion of Paul and James. Read their account of why these two conversions are particularly significant evidentially &mdash; neither Paul nor James was a disciple of Jesus before the resurrection.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">The conversion of Paul (from persecutor to apostle) and James (from skeptical brother to martyred church leader) are two of the strongest individual evidences for the resurrection. Neither has a plausible non-resurrection explanation. Write your evaluation: if you were a skeptical historian, what would you make of these two conversions?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Add to your Resurrection brief: section 4 &mdash; &lsquo;The appearances, and the conversions of Paul and James.&rsquo; Write it clearly. You are building toward the one-page brief you will complete on Saturday.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Week synthesis &mdash; the historical case stated</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Acts 17:30&ndash;31<br>Paul before the Athenian philosophers: <em>&ldquo;He has given proof of this to everyone by raising him from the dead.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Paul makes the resurrection a public historical claim, not a private religious one. What does this say about how the early Christians understood the event?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your four Resurrection brief sections. Then read Habermas &amp; Licona&rsquo;s conclusion. Revise and finalize your one-page Resurrection brief: state the minimal facts, refute the alternatives, address the appearances and conversions, and draw your conclusion. Write it clearly enough to use in a real conversation.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write your completed one-page Resurrection brief &mdash; all four sections, polished. Then write below it: what is the one objection to the resurrection you would most struggle to answer? Research it briefly and add a paragraph addressing it.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: recite the five minimal facts from memory. This is the core of your apologetic on the resurrection &mdash; you should be able to state these in any conversation, any time.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 2</span>
        <span class="week-title">Wright&rsquo;s theological account &mdash; what the resurrection means</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The Jewish background to resurrection belief</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Ezekiel 37:1&ndash;14<br>The valley of dry bones. <em>&ldquo;I will put breath in you, and you will come to life.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Israel&rsquo;s corporate resurrection as a metaphor for national restoration. Wright argues that Jesus&rsquo;s resurrection was understood in this context &mdash; the beginning of the promised national and cosmic resurrection.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> N.T. Wright, <em>The Resurrection of the Son of God</em>, Chapters 4&ndash;5: the Jewish background to resurrection belief. Wright traces how diverse Second Temple Jewish beliefs about resurrection set the stage for the specific claim the early Christians made. Read his account of what &lsquo;resurrection&rsquo; meant to a first-century Jew.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wright argues that no Jewish resurrection belief before Jesus anticipated the specific claim the early Christians made &mdash; one person raised in the middle of history with a transformed body. This means the empty tomb and appearances cannot be explained by the disciples &lsquo;spiritualizing&rsquo; or &lsquo;mythologizing&rsquo; earlier categories. Write his argument in your own words.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray Ezekiel 37:3: <em>&ldquo;Son of man, can these bones live?&rdquo;</em> Sit with the question as applied to your own life. What in you is dry, scattered, waiting for breath? Write one honest paragraph.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The resurrection and the new creation</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Romans 8:19&ndash;23<br><em>&ldquo;The whole creation has been groaning as in the pains of childbirth right up to the present time.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The resurrection of Jesus is not an isolated miracle but the first event of the new creation. What does this mean for the material world you inhabit?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> N.T. Wright, <em>The Resurrection of the Son of God</em>, Chapter 18: &ldquo;The Meaning of the Resurrection.&rdquo; Wright argues that the resurrection inaugurates the renewal of creation &mdash; that Jesus&rsquo;s raised body is the prototype of what will happen to all things. Read his theological synthesis of what the resurrection means.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wright argues that resurrection faith should produce not a desire to escape the material world (gnosticism) but a determination to care for and renew it &mdash; because the material world is where the resurrection will arrive. Write what this means for your work in landscaping, in your South Austin yard, in building Greenline. What does resurrection faith say to the person who tends the earth?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Practice: Go outside. Put your hands in the ground, or touch a tree, or tend one of your Texas native plants. Do it as a theological act &mdash; as a small participation in the renewal of creation that the resurrection has begun. Write one sentence about what the act means.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The resurrection and Christian ethics</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 1 Corinthians 15:58<br><em>&ldquo;Therefore, my dear brothers and sisters, stand firm. Let nothing move you. Always give yourselves fully to the work of the Lord, because you know that your labor in the Lord is not in vain.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Resurrection faith produces ethical commitment. Why does it matter that our labor is &lsquo;not in vain&rsquo;?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Wright, <em>The Resurrection of the Son of God</em>, concluding section on resurrection and mission. Wright argues that if the resurrection is true, then every act of justice, every word of truth, every act of beauty is taken up into God&rsquo;s new creation &mdash; nothing done in the Lord is ultimately lost.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Wright&rsquo;s ethical claim: the resurrection means that acts of love done now will be part of the new creation &mdash; they will be present in the renewed world. This gives ordinary ethics an eschatological weight. Write: how does this change how you think about a cold call done with integrity, a landscaping project done beautifully, a relationship tended faithfully?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Write a one-page essay: &ldquo;What the resurrection means for how I live on Monday.&rdquo; Not for eternity in the abstract &mdash; for your actual Monday morning. Use Wright&rsquo;s framework: new creation already begun, every act of love taken up, labor not in vain.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The resurrection as the center of Christian proclamation</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Acts 4:33<br><em>&ldquo;With great power the apostles continued to testify to the resurrection of the Lord Jesus.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The apostles&rsquo; primary testimony was the resurrection, not the teaching, not the miracles &mdash; the resurrection. What does it say about Christianity that its central proclamation is a historical event?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Habermas &amp; Licona, <em>The Case for the Resurrection of Jesus</em>, conclusion. Read their summary of the apologetic case. Then: re-read your own Resurrection brief from Week 1. Revise it with what you have learned in Week 2 about the theological significance of the resurrection.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write your final, two-page Resurrection summary: page one is the historical case (minimal facts, alternatives, appearances, conversions). Page two is the theological significance (new creation, ethics, mission, the renewal of all things). This is the document you could hand someone who asks why you believe in the resurrection.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: who is one person in your life with whom you would want to have a resurrection conversation? Write what you would say and what you would ask them.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Unit 1 synthesis &mdash; the apologetic foundation</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 1 Peter 3:15<br><em>&ldquo;Always be prepared to give an answer to everyone who asks you to give the reason for the hope that you have. But do this with gentleness and respect.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Preparation, gentleness, respect. Write: which of these three is currently weakest in your apologetic practice?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your full Resurrection brief. Then re-read your journal from the two weeks. What has the historical investigation done to your faith &mdash; strengthened it, complicated it, clarified it?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write one full page: &ldquo;The resurrection as my anchor.&rdquo; Not a defense of the resurrection &mdash; a testimony. What does the resurrection mean to you personally, as a person who has now examined the historical evidence carefully? How does it function in your daily life with God?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: pray for the person you named on Friday. Pray specifically for a natural opportunity for an honest conversation. Write what you hope that conversation looks like.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 3</span>
        <span class="week-title">Islam and comparative theology</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">What Islam teaches &mdash; an honest account</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> John 14:6<br><em>&ldquo;I am the way and the truth and the life. No one comes to the Father except through me.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. This claim is directly at odds with Islamic theology. What is the difference between a confident Christian conviction and an arrogant one? What does intellectual charity require?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Timothy George, <em>Is the Father of Jesus the God of Muhammad?</em>, Chapters 1&ndash;3. George gives a careful, respectful account of Islamic theology from a Christian perspective. Read his account of what Islam actually believes &mdash; not a caricature. Note what Islam and Christianity share and where they genuinely diverge.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">George traces the key theological differences: Islam affirms God&rsquo;s unity so strongly that the Trinity is considered <em>shirk</em> (idolatry). Islam denies the crucifixion (Quran 4:157). Islam holds the Quran to be the direct word of God in Arabic. Write a summary of the three most fundamental theological differences between Islam and Christianity, stated fairly.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray for a Muslim &mdash; not as an evangelistic project but as a person made in the image of God and loved by God. Pray for what they actually need. Sit in silence after for 5 minutes. Write one sentence about what praying for a Muslim does to your posture toward Islam.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The epistemological argument &mdash; how Islam grounds its claims</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Deuteronomy 18:21&ndash;22<br>The test of a prophet: if what they prophesy does not come true, they are not a prophet. Read it three times. Both Christianity and Islam make claims that are in principle testable. What are the respective tests, and what is the evidence?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Lamin Sanneh, <em>Whose Religion Is Christianity?</em>, Chapters 1&ndash;3. Sanneh is a former Muslim, now a Christian, who writes about the translatability of Christianity (the gospel into any language, any culture) vs. Islam&rsquo;s insistence on Arabic. Read his argument for why the incarnational logic of Christianity is itself an argument for its truth.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write a two-page comparative paper: the epistemological foundations of Christian faith vs. Islam&rsquo;s claims to revelation. Christianity grounds itself in a historical resurrection that can be investigated. Islam grounds itself in a claimed revelation to a single prophet whose experience cannot be verified. What are the decisive epistemological differences? Where are your own uncertainties?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Read Sanneh&rsquo;s account of his own journey from Islam to Christianity. Write: what in his account resonates with your own experience of coming to faith? What in the intellectual journey is similar? What is different?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Nabeel Qureshi &mdash; the insider account</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Isaiah 45:22<br><em>&ldquo;Turn to me and be saved, all you ends of the earth; for I am God, and there is no other.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. This is the universal claim. What does it require of the person who believes it?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Nabeel Qureshi, <em>Seeking Allah, Finding Jesus</em>, selected chapters (Qureshi was a devout Muslim who became a Christian after investigating the historical evidence). Read his account of what it cost him and what the evidence convinced him of. Read carefully &mdash; he knows Islam from the inside.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Qureshi traces his intellectual journey: the historical case for the resurrection, the textual evidence for the reliability of the Gospels, the difficulties in the Islamic account of the Quran&rsquo;s preservation. Write: what in his argument would you use in a conversation with a Muslim friend? What would you want to understand better first?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray for Nabeel Qureshi, who died of cancer in 2017 at age 34. Then pray for the Muslim community in Austin. Not for their conversion as a project &mdash; for their flourishing, their families, their daily lives. Write one sentence: what does praying for people you disagree with fundamentally do to the disagreement?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Engaging Islam with charity and clarity</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Romans 10:1<br><em>&ldquo;Brothers and sisters, my heart&rsquo;s desire and prayer to God for the Israelites is that they may be saved.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Paul desires the salvation of those who have a sincere but incomplete religious system. What is the relationship between genuine desire for another&rsquo;s good and honest disagreement with their beliefs?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Timothy George, <em>Is the Father of Jesus the God of Muhammad?</em>, final chapter: &ldquo;How Then Should We Engage?&rdquo; George gives practical guidance on Christian engagement with Muslims &mdash; honest about the differences, respectful of the person, hopeful about the possibility of genuine conversation. Read his account.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">George distinguishes between the Islamic God and the Christian God: they share some attributes (creator, all-powerful, all-knowing) but differ fundamentally on the Trinity, the Incarnation, and therefore on the nature of love and salvation. Write: can you hold both the genuine similarities and the fundamental differences honestly at the same time? What does intellectual charity require?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Write a one-page account of how you would engage a Muslim friend in an honest conversation about Jesus. Not a script for conversion &mdash; an approach for genuine dialogue. What would you ask? What would you share? What would you genuinely want to understand about their faith?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Unit synthesis &mdash; apologetics as love</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 1 Corinthians 13:1&ndash;3<br><em>&ldquo;If I speak in the tongues of men or of angels, but do not have love, I am only a resounding gong or a clanging cymbal.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The apologetic unit is sandwiched between ethics (C3.1) and capstone (C3.3) for a reason: truth without love is noise. What does this mean for how you hold the case you have built?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your comparative paper on Islam from Tuesday. Revise it in light of this week&rsquo;s reading &mdash; particularly George&rsquo;s final chapter on charitable engagement. What would you change about the tone or emphasis?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write one full page: &ldquo;What this unit has done to my understanding of other faiths.&rdquo; Not what you now know about Islam &mdash; what the study has done to your posture. Has your confidence in Christianity deepened? Has your respect for sincere believers in other traditions deepened? Has your understanding of what genuine engagement requires changed?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: pray for one person of another faith in your life. Write their name. Write what you genuinely hope for them.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div><div class="unit-label" style="margin-top:2rem;">Unit 2 &middot; 2 Weeks</div><div class="unit-title">Doubt, Deconstruction, and Intellectual Integrity</div><div class="unit-desc">Os Guinness and Alister McGrath on faith that can hold its questions. The apologetic posture that is most intellectually honest and most spiritually sustainable.</div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 4</span>
        <span class="week-title">Doubt as part of faith</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">What doubt is &mdash; and what it is not</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Mark 9:24<br><em>&ldquo;I do believe; help me overcome my unbelief!&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times. Both in one sentence &mdash; belief and unbelief, faith and doubt, held together. What does this verse authorize in the life of the believer?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Os Guinness, <em>God in the Dark</em>, Chapters 1&ndash;3: the nature of doubt and its varieties. Guinness distinguishes between doubt (questioning while remaining engaged) and unbelief (disengaging from the questions). Read his taxonomy of doubt carefully &mdash; he identifies multiple types, each requiring a different response.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Guinness argues that doubt is not the opposite of faith but a part of it &mdash; faith is not certainty but trust in the presence of uncertainty. Write: what is the doubt you return to most? Is it intellectual (a question you can&rsquo;t answer), moral (a problem with God&rsquo;s character), or experiential (a season when God seemed absent)? Write your honest account.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray with your doubt. Don&rsquo;t suppress it, don&rsquo;t perform certainty you don&rsquo;t have. Bring the question to God in 15 minutes of prayer: <em>I believe; help my unbelief.</em> Write one sentence: what did it feel like to pray the doubt rather than the answer?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The intellectual framework &mdash; why faith is reasonable</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Isaiah 1:18<br><em>&ldquo;Come now, let us reason together, says the Lord.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. God invites reasoning &mdash; he does not demand blind acceptance. What does this say about the relationship between reason and faith?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Alister McGrath, <em>Doubting: Growing Through the Uncertainties of Faith</em>, Chapters 1&ndash;4. McGrath argues that intellectual doubt often arises from a misunderstanding of what faith is &mdash; not certainty but trust, not proof but evidence sufficient for commitment. Read his account of how the reformed understanding of faith handles doubt.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">McGrath traces how the post-Enlightenment demand for mathematical certainty before commitment is itself a philosophical position that cannot meet its own standard &mdash; you cannot prove with certainty that certainty is required. Write your evaluation of McGrath&rsquo;s argument. Does it address the specific doubt you named on Monday?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Sit in silence for 15 minutes holding your doubt before God. Don&rsquo;t try to resolve it. Don&rsquo;t try to suppress it. Hold it in the posture of Mark 9:24 &mdash; believing and asking for help with the unbelief simultaneously. Write what the silence does that reasoning doesn&rsquo;t.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Deconstruction &mdash; what it is and how to hold it</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 1 Kings 19:4<br>Elijah under the juniper tree: <em>&ldquo;I have had enough, Lord.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The prophet who called fire from heaven, who outran the king&rsquo;s chariot, is now asking to die. What does his collapse tell you about the relationship between spiritual achievement and spiritual fragility?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Guinness, <em>God in the Dark</em>, Chapters 8&ndash;10: how to move through seasons of deep doubt and spiritual deconstruction. Guinness gives careful pastoral guidance &mdash; what to do, what not to do, how to maintain the posture of trust when the framework has crumbled.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Many people your age have undergone significant deconstruction &mdash; the collapse of a childhood framework of faith. You have navigated your own version of this. Write honestly: what has your faith lost through deconstruction? What has it gained? What do you now hold that you would not have arrived at without the crisis?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Elijah&rsquo;s recovery was not a new argument or a new theological answer. It was food, sleep, the voice of God in a still small wind, and a recommission. Write: what does your own faith need right now that is analogous to bread and water rather than to theological resolution?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Honest faith &mdash; what intellectual integrity requires</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Habakkuk 3:17&ndash;18<br><em>&ldquo;Though the fig tree does not bud and there are no grapes on the vines&hellip; yet I will rejoice in the Lord, I will be joyful in God my Savior.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Faith in the absence of evidence, not in contradiction to evidence. What does <em>yet</em> require?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> McGrath, <em>Doubting</em>, final chapters: faith after doubt. McGrath argues that faith that has been through intellectual doubt is often stronger than faith that has not &mdash; because it has been tested against the alternatives and chosen. Read his account of what intellectual integrity in faith looks like.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write your honest faith statement as it currently stands. Not the version you would write in a church context &mdash; the one you actually hold. What do you believe confidently? What are you uncertain about? What are you still working out? What have you decided to trust without fully understanding? This is the beginning of your capstone theology paper.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: one question about your faith that you are currently carrying. Write it precisely. Don&rsquo;t answer it yet &mdash; hold it.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Unit 2 and Course 3.2 synthesis</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Romans 1:16<br><em>&ldquo;For I am not ashamed of the gospel, because it is the power of God that brings salvation to everyone who believes.&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times. Not ashamed &mdash; which implies the temptation to be ashamed, the awareness that the gospel is offensive to certain audiences. What does it mean to not be ashamed when you know the social cost?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read all of your Course 3.2 journal. Identify the five most significant formations from the whole course &mdash; the resurrection study, the Islam comparative, and the doubt unit. Write one sentence on each.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Course 3.2 synthesis essay: &ldquo;My apologetic and my faith.&rdquo; Two full pages. Cover: the historical case for the resurrection as you now hold it, the engagement with Islam as you now understand it, the role of doubt in your faith, and what intellectual integrity requires of you as a Christian in 2026. Write in your own voice.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: pray 1 Peter 3:15 as a commission over your own life. Write what &lsquo;always being prepared&rsquo; means for you specifically in the next year.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div></div>
<div id="y3-c33" class="course-section" style="display:none;"><div class="course-divider">Course 3.3 &mdash; Capstone: Integration and Vocation</div><div class="unit-label" style="margin-top:2rem;">Unit 1 &middot; 4 Weeks</div><div class="unit-title">Writing Your Theology</div><div class="unit-desc">The most demanding writing of the curriculum: a 10&ndash;15 page personal theological statement in your own voice. Not an academic paper &mdash; a confession. Who is God? Who are you? What is salvation? What is the church? What are you called to?</div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 1</span>
        <span class="week-title">Beginning the statement &mdash; doctrine of God</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Who God is &mdash; your statement begins here</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Exodus 34:6&ndash;7<br>The name God speaks over himself: <em>&ldquo;The Lord, the Lord, the compassionate and gracious God, slow to anger, abounding in love and faithfulness.&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times. After three years of theological formation, what is your answer to the question: who is God? Not doctrine &mdash; your answer, in your own words.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your Year I Systematic Theology journal (Course 2.1) and your Isaiah 40 material (Course 1.1 Unit 2). These are the two places in the curriculum where you most directly addressed the character of God. Re-read both with fresh eyes, noting what has settled and what is still forming.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write the first section of your theological statement: &lsquo;The God I Believe In.&rsquo; Three to four pages. Cover: the Trinity (what it means that God is Father, Son, and Spirit before creation), the attributes (which ones most shape how you live), the Wesleyan distinctives (prevenient grace, responsible love, relational sovereignty), and Isaiah 53 as your evidential anchor. Write in your own voice. No footnotes. No hedging. Your confession.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Read what you just wrote aloud. Slowly. This is not an academic exercise &mdash; it is a declaration. What do you hear in your own words that you didn't know you believed? What feels most true? What feels most performed? Write two sentences of honest evaluation.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Scripture &mdash; your doctrine of the Word</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 2 Timothy 3:16<br><em>&ldquo;All Scripture is God-breathed.&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times. After three years of daily Lectio Divina and sustained Scripture reading: what do you actually believe about Scripture? Not the doctrinal formula &mdash; what Scripture has been in your life.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your Course 1.1 journal &mdash; the Wright unit and the Isaiah unit &mdash; and your notes on sola scriptura from Course 2.2. What has the curriculum done to your doctrine of Scripture? How has reading it as story changed what you think it is?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write the second section of your theological statement: &lsquo;Scripture: What I Believe About the Book I Live From.&rsquo; Two pages. Cover: how you understand Scripture&rsquo;s authority, what the narrative framework (Wright&rsquo;s five acts) has done to your reading, how Lectio Divina has shaped your relationship to the text, and what role reason, tradition, and experience play alongside it. Write concretely &mdash; use examples from your own reading.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Read this section aloud. What does your doctrine of Scripture sound like when it&rsquo;s honest? Write one sentence: what has three years of daily Scripture reading done that you could not have gotten from a doctrine of Scripture alone?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Humanity &mdash; what you are</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Genesis 1:27<br><em>&ldquo;So God created mankind in his own image.&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times. After three years of Willard, Smith, Wesley, and the desert fathers on human nature and formation: what do you believe about what a human being is? What are you?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your journal from Course 2.1 Unit 2 (Anthropology: What Is a Human Being?) and your notes on Smith&rsquo;s liturgy audit and Willard&rsquo;s VIM framework. What has the curriculum taught you about your own nature?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write the third section of your theological statement: &lsquo;Humanity: What I Believe About What I Am.&rsquo; Two pages. Cover: image of God as the foundation of dignity, the fall and its effects (using Wesley&rsquo;s account, not a purely Reformed one), the body-soul unity that your Muay Thai training and fasting practice embody, and the liturgical nature of human formation (Smith). Write personally &mdash; use yourself as the primary example.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Read this section aloud. What does your anthropology reveal about the kind of formation you most need? Write one honest sentence.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Salvation &mdash; the Wesleyan distinctive</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Romans 8:29&ndash;30<br><em>&ldquo;For those God foreknew he also predestined to be conformed to the image of his Son.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The goal of salvation: conformity to Christ&rsquo;s image. This is entire sanctification in Pauline language. Write: what does it mean for this to be the destination of your life?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your Course 1.2 journal &mdash; all four units: Wesley the man, prevenient grace, justification and sanctification, entire sanctification. This is the theological heart of your Wesleyan formation. Re-read with an eye toward synthesis: what is the single most important claim in all of it?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write the fourth section of your theological statement: &lsquo;Salvation: The Wesleyan Account I Have Made My Own.&rsquo; Three pages. Cover the full ordo salutis in Wesley&rsquo;s framework: prevenient grace (your own history of being pursued before you knew it), justification (what changed at your conversion), new birth, sanctification (where you are in the process), entire sanctification (what you are moving toward). Write as confession and testimony, not lecture.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Read this section aloud. This is the most distinctively Wesleyan section of your statement. What do you most want someone to understand about salvation who has only heard the Reformed version? Write two sentences.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Week synthesis &mdash; the statement takes shape</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Philippians 3:12<br><em>&ldquo;Not that I have already obtained all this, or have already arrived at my goal, but I press on.&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times. Paul&rsquo;s theological statement includes honest incompleteness. Write: what in your theological statement is still &lsquo;pressing on&rsquo; rather than arrived?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read everything you&rsquo;ve written this week &mdash; all four sections. Read it as a whole for the first time. Does it cohere? Does the God you describe in section one match the salvation you describe in section four? Does the humanity you describe in section three match the formation you have undergone?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write a one-page integration note: where does your theological statement feel most alive? Where does it feel most performed? Where are the places you wrote what you thought you should believe rather than what you actually believe? Go back and revise those places. The statement must be yours, not a Wesleyan textbook in your name.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: one theological claim you have written this week that you are most proud of. One you are least certain about. Write both.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 2</span>
        <span class="week-title">Church, vocation, and eschatology</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The church &mdash; what you believe it is for</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Ephesians 4:11&ndash;13<br><em>&ldquo;To equip his people for works of service, so that the body of Christ may be built up until we all reach unity in the faith.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The church&rsquo;s purpose: equipping for service, building toward maturity, reaching unity. How does this compare to what you have experienced church to be in practice?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your journal from Course 2.1 Unit 4 (Ecclesiology and Sacraments) and your Volf notes from Course 2.2. What has the curriculum taught you about what the church is and should be?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write the fifth section of your theological statement: &lsquo;The Church: What I Believe the Community of Faith Is For.&rsquo; Two pages. Cover: Wesley&rsquo;s vision of the church as a community of formation (class meetings, means of grace), Volf&rsquo;s account of the church as the image of the Trinity, the sacraments as means of grace, and your own experience of church community &mdash; what it has given you and where it has fallen short.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Read this section aloud. What do you most want from the local church that you are not currently receiving? What are you most failing to give? Write two honest sentences.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Vocation &mdash; what you are called to</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Jeremiah 29:11<br><em>&ldquo;&lsquo;For I know the plans I have for you,&rsquo; declares the Lord, &lsquo;plans to prosper you and not to harm you, plans to give you hope and a future.&rsquo;&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. After three years of formation, more questions or fewer? Write: what do you know about your calling that you didn&rsquo;t know before?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your vocation journal from Course 3.1 (Keller, Kingdom and work) and your discernment notes from Course 2.3. What has the curriculum taught you about your specific calling?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write the sixth section of your theological statement: &lsquo;Vocation: What I Believe I Am Called To.&rsquo; Two pages. Cover: Keller&rsquo;s theology of work as new creation participation, the Wesleyan account of holiness as social and public, your specific calling in sales and in building Greenline, your calling in your relationship with Dana, and the larger question of what you are building toward in your one life. Write honestly &mdash; not what sounds noble, what you actually believe.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Read this section aloud. This is the most personal section of the statement. What did you write that surprised you? What did you avoid writing that should be there? Write it now.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Eschatology &mdash; the end that shapes the present</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Revelation 21:3&ndash;5<br><em>&ldquo;Look! God&rsquo;s dwelling place is now among the people, and he will dwell with them.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The new creation: God with us, tears wiped away, all things made new. After three years of formation, what do you believe about how this story ends?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your notes from the resurrection unit in Course 3.2 &mdash; particularly Wright on new creation and the ethical implications of resurrection faith. How has the study of the resurrection shaped your eschatology?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write the seventh section of your theological statement: &lsquo;Eschatology: What I Believe About How This Ends.&rsquo; Two pages. Cover: the resurrection of the body (Wright&rsquo;s new creation framework), the renewal of all things (not escape from creation but creation redeemed), the ethical implications (every act of love done now matters eternally), and what hope in the new creation does to how you live on an ordinary Tuesday in South Austin. Write concretely.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Read this section aloud. What does your eschatology ask of you tomorrow? Not in general &mdash; tomorrow specifically. Write one sentence.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The statement complete &mdash; reading it whole</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 2 Corinthians 4:7<br><em>&ldquo;We have this treasure in jars of clay.&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times. Your theological statement is a jar of clay &mdash; finite, imperfect, the product of a particular person at a particular moment. And it holds treasure. Read your entire statement aloud from beginning to end.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read all seven sections of your theological statement. Read for coherence (does the whole hang together?), honesty (is there anything you wrote for appearance rather than truth?), and completeness (is there something essential missing?).</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write a conclusion to your theological statement: &lsquo;Three Years Later: Who I Am Now.&rsquo; Two pages. Address the questions Wesley asked of every believer: Do you know that your sins are forgiven? Do you know that God loves you? Are you growing in love of God and neighbor? Are you moving toward entire sanctification? Answer each one honestly. Then answer the question Willard poses: are you with Jesus, learning from him, being formed into his likeness? Write your honest answer.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Read the conclusion aloud. This is the end of your theological statement. It should be simultaneously humble and confident &mdash; aware of how far you have to go, certain of what has already been given. Write one sentence: what do you most want to be true of yourself in three more years?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Week synthesis &mdash; the statement as a living document</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Psalm 90:12<br><em>&ldquo;Teach us to number our days, that we may gain a heart of wisdom.&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times. Your theological statement is a document of your numbered days &mdash; what you have learned in the days you have been given. What has this week of writing taught you about yourself?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Read your complete theological statement one final time. Then read the Wesleyan covenant prayer: <em>&lsquo;I am no longer my own but yours. Put me to what you will, rank me with whom you will; put me to doing, put me to suffering&hellip;&rsquo;</em> Read the statement and then the prayer. What is the relationship between what you believe and what you are offering?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write a one-page cover letter for your theological statement, addressed to yourself at the beginning of Year I. Tell them what these three years will do. What they will lose. What they will find. What questions they should bring into the curriculum. What they should not be afraid of. What will surprise them most.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: sign and date your theological statement. It is complete. File it somewhere you will find it in ten years.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 3</span>
        <span class="week-title">The statement in conversation &mdash; testing and refining</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Sharing your theology &mdash; what you will defend</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> 1 Peter 3:15<br><em>&ldquo;Always be prepared to give an answer to everyone who asks you to give the reason for the hope that you have.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Your theological statement is the written version of this answer. Who do you want to be able to give it to? What would you need to change to make it accessible to them?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read the section of your statement on salvation. This is the section most people will ask about, most directly &mdash; &lsquo;Why are you a Christian?&rsquo; Read it with a skeptical friend in mind. Is it honest? Is it clear? Does it invite conversation or close it down?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write a one-page version of your theology of salvation &mdash; the Wesleyan account &mdash; in language accessible to someone who has never been to church. No theological jargon. No assumed familiarity with the vocabulary. Test it: could you hand this to your most secular friend and have them understand what you believe and why?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Give the one-page version to someone &mdash; a friend, a colleague, Dana &mdash; and ask them what questions it raises. Write their questions. These are the places where your theology needs more work, more accessibility, or more honesty.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Where the statement has gaps &mdash; what three years left unresolved</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Job 40:4<br>Job&rsquo;s response to God from the whirlwind: <em>&ldquo;I am unworthy &mdash; how can I reply to you? I put my hand over my mouth.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The most honest theological posture is not certainty but stunned awe. Where do you still put your hand over your mouth?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read the section of your statement on the church. This is typically the most underdeveloped section of a personal theology &mdash; we have stronger convictions about God and salvation than about ecclesiology. Read it and identify what is missing or underdeveloped.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write an honest appendix to your theological statement: &lsquo;What I Don&rsquo;t Yet Know.&rsquo; List the five theological questions you are still genuinely wrestling with. Not questions you have an answer to but perform uncertainty about &mdash; real open questions. For each one, write: why it matters, what the best argument on each side is, and what you will need to keep learning to approach an answer.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Read your appendix aloud. Intellectual humility is not weakness &mdash; it is the sign of a theology that is alive rather than closed. Write one sentence: what is the question you most want to resolve in the next decade?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The statement and your life &mdash; what it asks</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> James 2:17<br><em>&ldquo;Faith by itself, if it is not accompanied by action, is dead.&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times. Your theological statement is not complete until it generates action. What does it require of you that you are not yet doing?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your statement&rsquo;s vocation section and your Course 3.1 journal. What has your theology of vocation, Kingdom, and ethics generated in terms of actual commitments? Where is the gap between what you believe and how you live largest?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write an action audit of your theological statement: for each section, write one specific change in your life that your stated theology requires. God section: how does your theology of the Trinity change your prayer practice specifically? Salvation section: how does your theology of sanctification change one specific habit? Church section: one specific commitment to community. Vocation section: one specific practice in your work. Eschatology section: one specific act that reflects resurrection hope. Seven sections, seven actions.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Read the action audit aloud. This is the gap between theology and life. Write one sentence: which of the seven actions is most urgent? Begin it before Saturday.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Preparing for the Rule of Life &mdash; the bridge</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Joshua 24:15<br><em>&ldquo;As for me and my household, we will serve the Lord.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Joshua&rsquo;s declaration is not a feeling &mdash; it is a covenant. Your Rule of Life, which begins next unit, will be your version of this declaration. What specific commitments is your theology generating?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Read Marjorie Thompson, <em>Soul Feast</em>, Chapter 10: &lsquo;A Rule of Life.&rsquo; Thompson gives the most accessible account of what a Rule of Life is, what it covers, and how to write one. Read it as the bridge between your theological statement (what you believe) and your Rule of Life (what you commit to practice).</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Thompson says a Rule of Life is &lsquo;a schedule and set of practices and relational commitments that help you intentionally make space for God in your everyday life.&rsquo; Write a first draft of what yours might include: daily practices, weekly rhythms, annual commitments, relational covenants. Don&rsquo;t finalize it &mdash; just sketch what your theology is generating.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray your first-draft Rule of Life back to God. Hold each item and ask: Is this genuine or performative? Is this sustainable or aspirational? Is this responsive to grace or an attempt to earn it? Write your honest evaluation.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Unit 1 synthesis &mdash; theology as living document</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Deuteronomy 6:6&ndash;7<br><em>&ldquo;These commandments that I give you today are to be on your hearts. Impress them on your children. Talk about them when you sit at home and when you walk along the road.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Theology that is on the heart, not just in a document. What would it mean for your theological statement to be on your heart?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your full theological statement one more time &mdash; all of it, including the appendix and the action audit. Identify the three sentences that most capture what you most deeply believe. Write them out separately.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write your three-sentence theology &mdash; the irreducible core of your statement, the thing you would say if you had only 30 seconds. This should be genuinely yours, not a canned formula. Test it: would you say this to a skeptical friend? To someone in crisis? At a funeral? Write it. Revise it. Write it again.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: read your three-sentence theology aloud three times. Memorize it. This is the thing you will carry.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 4</span>
        <span class="week-title">Theology and mission &mdash; the statement sent out</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The theology you hold and the people around you</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Matthew 28:19&ndash;20<br><em>&ldquo;Go and make disciples of all nations&hellip; teaching them to obey everything I have commanded you.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The Great Commission follows from everything you now believe. What does your theology send you to?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your Course 3.1 ethics journal &mdash; the Sermon on the Mount, MLK&rsquo;s Letter, Keller on work. Then re-read your vocation section of the theological statement. What does your theology require of you in the specific people and contexts God has placed you in?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write a one-page mission statement: not a professional mission statement, a theological one. Who are you sent to? What are you sent with? What are you sent for? Use your specific context: sales in Austin, Greenline, your church community, your relationship with Dana, your friendships. Let the mission statement be the active form of your theological statement.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Read your mission statement aloud. Does it sound like you? Does it sound like the Jesus of the Gospels? Does it sound like the Wesley who preached to coal miners? Write one sentence: what would it cost you to actually live this?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Formation in the world &mdash; what Muay Thai, landscaping, and cold calls have to do with theology</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Colossians 3:23<br><em>&ldquo;Whatever you do, work at it with all your heart, as working for the Lord.&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times. Every Monday morning, every cold call, every training session: theological territory. Write what this means for next Monday specifically.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your Course 3.1 synthesis essay on Kingdom and work. Then read your action audit from last week. Where is the alignment between your theological statement and your actual week? Where is the gap largest?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write a &lsquo;theological day planner&rsquo; for a typical Monday: show how each part of the day &mdash; morning prayer, first call, gym session, family time, evening &mdash; is inhabited with theological intention. Not a performance schedule &mdash; a picture of what it looks like when the theological statement is actually lived. Make it realistic for the actual Trevor, not the ideal one.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray the Wesleyan covenant prayer over your calendar: <em>&lsquo;Put me to doing, put me to suffering&hellip; I freely and heartily yield all things to your pleasure and disposal.&rsquo;</em> Write one sentence: what would you need to change about next week if you prayed this prayer honestly?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The theological statement reviewed &mdash; what will last</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Isaiah 40:8<br><em>&ldquo;The grass withers and the flowers fall, but the word of our God endures forever.&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times. Your theological statement is not forever &mdash; it is a statement at a moment in time. What in it do you believe will remain? What do you expect will change?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read the Wesleyan covenant prayer one final time. Then read Wesley&rsquo;s final sermon, &lsquo;The More Excellent Way,&rsquo; which you read in Course 3.1. Wesley was 85 when he last preached it. What in his late-life theology do you want to still be true of you at 85?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write a letter to yourself at age 65 from your theological statement. Tell the 65-year-old Trevor: what you believed at 30-something about God, salvation, the church, and your calling. Ask him: did it hold? What changed? What deepened? What would you want the older self to still be doing that you are doing now? What would you want him to have stopped doing?</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Read the letter aloud. File it somewhere. Set a calendar reminder for your 65th birthday to find it. This is the long-arc practice of the theological life &mdash; accountable not just to the present but to the future self who will inherit your current convictions.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Unit 1 complete &mdash; the statement is finished</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> John 17:3<br><em>&ldquo;Now this is eternal life: that they know you, the only true God, and Jesus Christ, whom you have sent.&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times. Eternal life is knowledge &mdash; not doctrinal knowledge alone, but personal knowledge, relational knowledge. The kind that can only come through time and presence. What do you know now that you could not have known three years ago?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Read your complete theological statement one final time &mdash; all of it, from the first sentence about God to the letter to your 65-year-old self. Read it slowly. Read it as a person who has spent three years learning to attend to God.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Sign your theological statement. Write the date. Write one sentence underneath the signature: the thing you most want to be true of yourself as a theologian and a Christian for the rest of your life. This sentence is your theological motto. Make it yours.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen for Unit 1. Four sentences. Then: sit in 15 minutes of silence as your final act of this unit. No words. No petition. Just presence before the God whose character you have just spent four weeks trying to describe.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div><div class="unit-label" style="margin-top:2rem;">Unit 2 &middot; 2 Weeks</div><div class="unit-title">A Rule of Life: Writing What You Will Live</div><div class="unit-desc">Not a resolution but a covenant. The permanent Rule of Life that distills three years of formation into a daily, weekly, and annual rhythm you will actually keep.</div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 5</span>
        <span class="week-title">Writing the Rule</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">What a Rule of Life is &mdash; and why you need one</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Psalm 1:1&ndash;3<br><em>&ldquo;Blessed is the one who does not walk in step with the wicked or stand in the way that sinners take or sit in the company of mockers, but whose delight is in the law of the Lord, and who meditates on his law day and night.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. A Rule of Life is a way of structuring your days so that you meditate on God&rsquo;s law day and night. What does your current structure make habitual?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Marjorie Thompson, <em>Soul Feast</em>, Chapter 10: &lsquo;A Rule of Life.&rsquo; Re-read it carefully. Then read Robert Mulholland, <em>Invitation to a Journey</em>, Chapter 8: &lsquo;The Journey in Community.&rsquo; Mulholland argues that a Rule of Life must be communal as well as personal &mdash; accountable to others, not merely self-imposed.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Thompson says a Rule of Life is not a rigid schedule but a &lsquo;trellis&rsquo; that supports growth rather than constraining it. Your Rule should cover: daily practices, weekly rhythms, monthly disciplines, annual retreats, relational commitments, financial covenant, and vocational purpose. Write a first draft of each category &mdash; not finished, just honest about what you actually do and what you intend.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray your first-draft Rule back to God. Hold each section and ask: Is this grace-responsive or performance-based? Is this sustainable for a person who trains Muay Thai, runs a sales pipeline, and is building a business? Write your honest evaluation.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The daily practices &mdash; the foundation</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Mark 1:35<br><em>&ldquo;Very early in the morning, while it was still dark, Jesus got up, left the house and went off to a solitary place, where he prayed.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Jesus had a morning practice. What is yours? What should it be?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your Course 1.3 prayer synthesis essay. Then re-read your prayer journal from the first week of C1.3. What has your daily prayer practice become over three years? What has held? What has drifted?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write the Daily Practices section of your Rule: morning prayer (what form, how long, what practices), Scripture (Lectio Divina &mdash; maintained? daily?), journaling (frequency, format), fasting (Wednesdays as established, what that actually includes), and evening review (examen). Write what is actually true and what you are committing to. The Rule must be achievable, not aspirational.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Read your Daily Practices section aloud. Is it honest? Is it the actual Trevor or the ideal Trevor? Revise until it is genuinely yours &mdash; ambitious but liveable.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The weekly and monthly rhythms</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Hebrews 4:9&ndash;10<br><em>&ldquo;There remains, then, a Sabbath-rest for the people of God; for anyone who enters God&rsquo;s rest also rests from their own work, just as God did from his.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Sabbath is not optional &mdash; it is theological. What does Sabbath actually look like in your life? What would it need to look like?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Thompson, <em>Soul Feast</em>, Chapter 8: &lsquo;Honoring the Body: Fasting and Feasting.&rsquo; Thompson argues that the weekly and monthly rhythms of the Christian life create a liturgical pattern that shapes the body and soul together. Read her account of how Sabbath, fasting, and Communion work together as rhythmic practices.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write the Weekly and Monthly sections of your Rule: Sabbath (which day, what it includes and excludes), Muay Thai (already established Tue/Thu &mdash; how does it function as formation?), worship and church community (frequency, what you give and receive), monthly extended prayer or retreat, Communion (with what intention). Write concretely.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Read your Weekly and Monthly section aloud. What would someone reading this understand about your priorities? What does the structure reveal about what you believe matters most?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The relational and financial covenant</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Proverbs 27:17<br><em>&ldquo;As iron sharpens iron, so one person sharpens another.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Your Rule must include your relationships because your formation is communal. Who sharpens you? Who are you sharpening? What do you owe the people God has placed in your life?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your Course 2.3 journal on spiritual direction and your Course 2.2 notes on the class meeting. Wesley&rsquo;s Rule was communal &mdash; it was designed to be lived in community. Who is your class meeting? Who asks you &lsquo;How does your soul prosper?&rsquo;</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write the Relational and Financial sections of your Rule: your commitment to Dana (what intentional investment in the relationship looks like), your accountability relationships (who, how often, what you bring), your commitment to your church community, your financial covenant (Wesley&rsquo;s earn/save/give framework applied to your actual income), and your commitment to Greenline and the people you lead there. Write concretely &mdash; not principles, specific commitments.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Read your Relational and Financial sections aloud. What is hardest to commit to on paper? Write one sentence about what resisting that commitment reveals.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Week synthesis &mdash; the Rule takes shape</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Romans 12:1<br><em>&ldquo;Offer your bodies as a living sacrifice, holy and pleasing to God &mdash; this is your true and proper worship.&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times. A Rule of Life is your body offered as a living sacrifice &mdash; time, attention, money, relationship, formation. Read everything you have written this week.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your full Rule of Life draft &mdash; all five sections. Read Thompson&rsquo;s chapter one more time. Ask: does my Rule reflect what I actually believe about God, salvation, and vocation? Is it shaped by my theological statement? Does the statement and the Rule cohere?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write a coherence check: place your theological statement and your Rule of Life side by side. For each section of the theological statement, identify which section of the Rule is the practical response. If a theological conviction has no corresponding practice, add one to the Rule or acknowledge that the conviction is not yet genuinely yours.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Weekly Examen. Four sentences. Then: read your Rule of Life draft one final time and identify the one section that feels most like genuine commitment and the one that feels most aspirational. Mark them. You will return to both next week.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="week-block">
      <div class="week-head" onclick="toggleWeek(this)">
        <span class="week-num">Week 6</span>
        <span class="week-title">Completing and sealing the Rule</span>
        <span class="week-toggle">&#9662;</span>
      </div>
      <div class="week-body">
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Monday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Revising the Rule &mdash; what must change</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Luke 14:28&ndash;30<br><em>&ldquo;Suppose one of you wants to build a tower. Won&rsquo;t you first sit down and estimate the cost to see if you have enough money to complete it?&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. A Rule of Life is a tower you are building. Have you counted the cost? What will it actually require?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Mulholland, <em>Invitation to a Journey</em>, Chapter 9: &lsquo;The Journey in Accountability.&rsquo; Mulholland argues that a Rule of Life without accountability becomes wishful thinking. Read his account of what it means to submit your Rule to another person for honest evaluation.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Show your Rule of Life to one person you trust &mdash; Dana, a close friend, a pastor, a spiritual director. Ask them: does this sound like the actual Trevor? Is anything missing? Is anything unrealistic? Write their feedback. Revise accordingly. The Rule must be tested by someone who knows you.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Revise your Rule based on the feedback. Write what changed and why. What did someone else see that you couldn&rsquo;t see alone?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Tuesday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The vocational section &mdash; what you are building toward</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Habakkuk 2:2<br><em>&ldquo;Write down the revelation and make it plain on tablets so that a herald may run with it.&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. Write it down. Make it plain. What is the vision God has given you that you are running with?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your vocation section of the theological statement. Then re-read your Buechner &lsquo;deep gladness and world&rsquo;s deep hunger&rsquo; notes from Course 2.3. What is the specific vision of your life that your formation is pointing toward?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write the Vocational Purpose section of your Rule: the long-term vision (what are you building toward in five years, ten years, a lifetime?), the specific callings (sales work as Kingdom vocation, Greenline as creation care, your relationships as formation partnerships), and the land vision (the Texas ranch co-ownership you and your friends are working toward &mdash; what is that for, theologically?). Write it as vision, not planning.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Read your Vocational Purpose section aloud. What lights up when you read it? What flattens? Revise toward what lights up. The vocation section of your Rule should produce energy, not obligation.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Thursday</span>
            <span class="day-title">The annual commitment &mdash; retreat and review</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Luke 5:16<br><em>&ldquo;But Jesus often withdrew to lonely places and prayed.&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times. Often. Withdrew. Lonely places. Prayed. Jesus built withdrawal into the rhythm of his life. What is your annual equivalent?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Thompson, <em>Soul Feast</em>, Chapter 11: &lsquo;A Retreat for Rule of Life Review.&rsquo; Thompson gives a structure for an annual retreat in which the Rule of Life is reviewed, revised, and renewed. Read her structure and adapt it for your own context &mdash; your calendar, your rhythms, your access to solitude.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write the Annual Practices section of your Rule: one annual silent retreat (where, when, how long), one annual review of your Rule (with whom, by when), one annual re-reading of your theological statement, one annual act of generosity that stretches you, and one annual physical challenge that tests your formation (a long hike, a fast, something that costs you something physical). Write concretely.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Pray over your annual commitments. For each one: ask whether you are actually willing to do it or whether you are writing it to impress yourself. Revise toward honest commitment. Write one sentence: what annual commitment is most essential for the person you are becoming?</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Friday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Sealing the Rule &mdash; the covenant</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Joshua 24:24<br><em>&ldquo;And the people said to Joshua, &lsquo;We will serve the Lord our God and obey him.&rsquo;&rdquo;</em> Read it three times. The covenant is spoken aloud, before witnesses, in public. Your Rule of Life is a covenant. What does it mean to seal it?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read the Wesleyan covenant prayer one final time. Then re-read your complete Rule of Life. Read both aloud, slowly. The covenant prayer is the posture; the Rule is the practice. They should fit together.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write a one-page preamble to your Rule of Life: the theological grounding (why this Rule, rooted in what convictions), the community context (to whom you are accountable for keeping it), the date of commitment, and the annual review date. The preamble is the covenant language that makes the Rule more than a to-do list.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Read your full Rule of Life with preamble aloud. Sign it. Date it. Write today&rsquo;s date and the date of your first annual review. File it somewhere permanent. This is the document you will carry forward from this curriculum.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="day-card">
          <div class="day-head" onclick="toggleDay(this)">
            <span class="day-label">Saturday</span>
            <span class="day-title">Course 3.3 and Year III final synthesis</span>
            <span class="day-toggle">&#9662;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="day-body">
            <div class="movement c-scripture">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Scripture</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Lectio Divina</span></div>
              <p><strong>Passage:</strong> Revelation 22:20<br><em>&ldquo;He who testifies to these things says, &lsquo;Yes, I am coming soon.&rsquo; Amen. Come, Lord Jesus.&rdquo;</em> Read it ten times. The last words of the biblical canon: not a theological statement but a cry and a prayer. After three years of formation, this is the landing place &mdash; not answers but longing. Write: what are you longing for?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-tradition">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Tradition</span><span class="mvmt-sub">35 min &middot; Primary Reading</span></div>
              <p><strong>Text:</strong> Re-read your Year I synthesis essay, your Year II synthesis essay, and your theological statement. Read them in order. Read the arc of three years. What do you see?</p>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-reason">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Reason</span><span class="mvmt-sub">20 min &middot; Written Reflection</span></div>
              <div class="prompt-box">Write your final synthesis document: &lsquo;Three Years: What Happened.&rsquo; Not a summary of content &mdash; an account of formation. Who were you when you began? Who are you now? What has been lost? What has been found? What has been completed? What is still unfinished? What do you most want God to do in the next three years? Write two pages, in your own voice, as the final act of the curriculum.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="movement c-experience">
              <div class="mvmt-head"><span class="mvmt-dot"></span><span class="mvmt-label">Experience</span><span class="mvmt-sub">15 min &middot; Formation Practice</span></div>
              <p>Sit in 30 minutes of silence &mdash; the longest silence of the curriculum. No agenda, no examen, no petition. Just presence before the God who has been forming you across three years. Afterward, write three words: what was there in the silence. Then close the journal. The curriculum is complete.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div></div>
</section>
<script>
function showYear(id, btn) {
  document.querySelectorAll('.section').forEach(s => s.classList.remove('active'));
  document.querySelectorAll('.nav-tab').forEach(t => t.classList.remove('active'));
  document.getElementById(id).classList.add('active');
  if (btn) btn.classList.add('active');
  ['y1','y2','y3'].forEach(y => {
    const sn = document.getElementById('sn-'+y);
    if (sn) sn.style.display = (y === id) ? 'flex' : 'none';
  });
  window.scrollTo({top:0, behavior:'smooth'});
}
function showCourse(year, courseId, btn) {
  document.querySelectorAll('#'+year+' .course-section').forEach(s => s.style.display = 'none');
  document.getElementById(year+'-'+courseId).style.display = 'block';
  const sn = document.getElementById('sn-'+year);
  sn.querySelectorAll('.snav-tab').forEach(t => t.classList.remove('active'));
  if (btn) btn.classList.add('active');
}
function toggleWeek(headEl) {
  headEl.closest('.week-block').classList.toggle('open');
}
function toggleDay(headEl) {
  headEl.closest('.day-card').classList.toggle('open');
}
</script>
</main>
</body>
</html>
